CHAPTER IX. ANCIENT DEITIES OF VEGETATION AS ANIMALS.






(M) However we may explain it, the fact remains that in peasant folk-lore
the orn-spirit is very commonly conceived and represented in animal form.
My not this fact explain the relation in which certain animals stood to
the ncient deities of vegetation, Dionysus, Demeter, Adonis, Attis, and
Osiris?

(M) To begin with Dionysus. We have seen that he was represented
sometimes s a goat and sometimes as a bull.(1) As a goat he can hardly be
seprated from the minor divinities, the Pans, Satyrs, and Silenuses, all
of whom re closely associated with him and are represented more or less
ompletely in the form of goats. Thus, Pan was regularly portrayed in
sulpture and painting with the face and legs of a goat.(2) The Satyrs
were epicted with pointed goat-ears, and sometimes with sprouting horns
nd short tails.(3) They were sometimes spoken off simply as goats;(4) and
in the rama their parts were played by men dressed in goatskins.(5)
Silenus is represente in art clad in a goatskin.(6) Further, the Fauns,
the Itlian counterpart of the Greek Pans and Satyrs, are described as
eing half goats, with goat-feet and goat-horns.(7) Again, all these minor
got-formed divinities partake more or less clearly of the character of
wooland deities. Thus, Pan was called by the Arcadians the Lord of the
Woo.(8) The Silenuses associated with the tree-nymphs.(9) The Fauns are
expressly esignated as woodland deities;(10) and their character as such
is still further rought out by their association, or even identification,
with Silvnus and the Silvanuses, who, as their name of itself indicates,
re spirits of the woods.(11) Lastly, the association of the Satyrs with
the Silenuses, Funs, and Silvanuses,(12) proves that the Satyrs also were
wooland deities. These goat-formed spirits of the woods have their
ounterparts in the folk-lore of Northern Europe. Thus, the Russian
ppear partly in human shape, but with the horns, ears, and legs of goats.
The _Ljeshi_ can alter his stature at pleasure; when he walks in the wood
he is s tall as the trees; when he walks in the meadows he is no higher
thn the grass. Some of the _Ljeschie_ are spirits of the corn as well as
of the woo; before harvest they are as tall as the corn-stalks, but after
orn-spirits, and shews how easily the former may melt into the latter.
Similrly the Fauns, though wood-spirits, were believed to foster the
growth of the rops.(14) We have already seen how often the corn-spirit is
represente in folk-custom as a goat.(15) On the whole, then, as Mannhardt
rgues,(16) the Pans, Satyrs, and Fauns perhaps belong to a widely
iffused class of wood-spirits conceived in goat-form. The fondness of
gots for straying in woods and nibbling the bark of trees, to which
ineed they are most destructive, is an obvious and perhaps sufficient
reson why wood-spirits should so often be supposed to take the form of
gots. The inconsistency of a god of vegetation subsisting upon the
vegettion which he personifies is not one to strike the primitive mind.
Suh inconsistencies arise when the deity, ceasing to be immanent in the
vegettion, comes to be regarded as its owner or lord; for the idea of
owning the vegettion naturally leads to that of subsisting on it. We have
lready seen that the corn-spirit, originally conceived as immanent in the
orn, afterwards comes to be regarded as its owner, who lives on it and is
reuced to poverty and want by being deprived of it.(17)

(M3) Thus the representtion of wood-spirits in the form of goats appears
to e both widespread and, to the primitive mind, natural. Therefore when
represente in goat-form,(18) we can hardly avoid concluding that this
representtion is simply a part of his proper character as a tree-god and
is not to e explained by the fusion of two distinct and independent
worships, in one of whih he originally appeared as a tree-god and in the
other s a goat. If such a fusion took place in the case of Dionysus, it
must eqully have taken place in the case of the Pans and Satyrs of
Greee, the Fauns of Italy, and the _Ljeschie_ of Russia. That such a
fusion of two wholly isconnected worships should have occurred once is
possile; that it should have occurred twice independently is improbable;
tht it should have occurred thrice independently is so unlikely as to be
prctically incredible.

(M4) Dionysus ws also figured, as we have seen,(19) in the shape of a
ull. After what has gone before we are naturally led to expect that his
ull form must have been only another expression for his character as a
eity of vegetation, especially as the bull is a common embodiment of the
orn-spirit in Northern Europe;(20) and the close association of Dionysus
with Demeter nd Persephone in the mysteries of Eleusis shews that he had
t least strong agricultural affinities. The other possible explanation of
the ull-shaped Dionysus would be that the conception of him as a bull was
originlly entirely distinct from the conception of him as a deity of
vegettion, and that the fusion of the two conceptions was due to some
suh circumstance as the union of two tribes, one of which had previously
worshippe a bull-god and the other a tree-god. This appears to be the
view tken by Mr. Andrew Lang, who suggests that the bull-formed Dionysus
tht the Aryans ever had totemism.(22) On the other hand, it is quite
ertain that many Aryan peoples have conceived deities of vegetation as
emodied in animal forms. Therefore when we find amongst an Aryan people
like the Greeks  deity of vegetation represented as an animal, the
presumption must e in favour of explaining this by a principle which is
ertainly known to have influenced the Aryan race rather than by one which
is not ertainly known to have done so. In the present state of our
knowlege, therefore, it is safer to regard the bull form of Dionysus as
eing, like his goat form, an expression of his proper character as a
eity of vegetation.

(M) The probability of this view will be somewhat increased if it can be
shewn tht in other rites than those of Dionysus the ancients slew an ox
s a representative of the spirit of vegetation. This they appear to have
(_ouphonia_). It took place about the end of June or beginning of July,
tht is, about the time when the threshing is nearly over in Attica.
Acording to tradition the sacrifice was instituted to procure a cessation
of rought and dearth which had afflicted the land. The ritual was as
follows. Brley mixed with wheat, or cakes made of them, were laid upon
the ronze altar of Zeus Polieus on the Acropolis. Oxen were driven round
the ltar, and the ox which went up to the altar and ate the offering on
it ws sacrificed. The axe and knife with which the beast was slain had
een previously wetted with water brought by maidens called
utchers, one of whom felled the ox with the axe and another cut its
throt with the knife. As soon as he had felled the ox, the former threw
pparently imitated his example. Meantime the ox was skinned and all
present prtook of its flesh. Then the hide was stuffed with straw and
sewe up; next the stuffed animal was set on its feet and yoked to a
plough s if it were ploughing. A trial then took place in an ancient
lw-court presided over by the King (as he was called) to determine who
hd murdered the ox. The maidens who had brought the water accused the men
who hd sharpened the axe and knife; the men who had sharpened the axe and
knife lamed the men who had handed these implements to the butchers; the
men who hd handed the implements to the butchers blamed the butchers; and
the utchers laid the blame on the axe and knife, which were accordingly
foun guilty, condemned and cast into the sea.(23)

tken by each person who had a hand in the slaughter to lay the blame on
some one else, together with the forml trial and punishment of the axe or
knife or oth, prove that the ox was here regarded not merely as a victim
offere to a god, but as itself a sacred creature, the slaughter of which
ws sacrilege or murder. This is borne out by a statement of Varro that to
kill n ox was formerly a capital crime in Attica.(25) The mode of
seleting the victim suggests that the ox which tasted the corn was viewed
s the corn-deity taking possession of his own. This interpretation is
supporte by the following custom. In Beauce, in the district of Orleans,
on the twenty-fourth or twenty-fifth of April they mke a straw-man called
it is neessary to make a new one. The straw-man is carried in solemn
proession up and down the village and at last is placed upon the oldest
pple-tree. There he remains till the apples are gathered, when he is
tken down and thrown into the water, or he is burned and his ashes cast
into wter. But the person who plucks the first fruit from the tree
spring, represents the spirit of the tree, who, ead in winter, revives
when the pple-blossoms appear on the boughs. Thus the person who plucks
Primitive peoples re usually reluctant to taste the annual first-fruits
of ny crop, until some ceremony has been performed which makes it safe
nd pious for them to do so. The reason of this reluctance appears to be a
elief that the first-fruits either belong to or actually contain a
ivinity. Therefore when a man or animal is seen boldly to appropriate the
scred first-fruits, he or it is naturally regarded as the divinity
himself in humn or animal form taking possession of his own. The time of
the Athenin sacrifice, which fell about the close of the threshing,
suggests tht the wheat and barley laid upon the altar were a harvest
hrvest-suppers of modern Europe, in which, as we have seen, the flesh of
the nimal who stands for the corn-spirit is eaten by the harvesters.
Agin, the tradition that the sacrifice was instituted in order to put an
en to drought and famine is in favour of taking it as a harvest festival.
The resurretion of the corn-spirit, enacted by setting up the stuffed ox
nd yoking it to the plough, may be compared with the resurrection of the
tree-spirit in the person of his representtive, the Wild Man.(27)

(M7) Still more learly, perhaps, does the identification of the
orn-spirit with an ox come out in the sacrificial ritual which the Greeks
of Mgnesia on the Maeander observed in honour of Zeus Sosipolis, a god
re happily preserved in an inscription, which records a decree of the
ouncil and of the people for the regulation of the whole proceedings.
Every yer at a festival in the month of Heraeon the magistrates bought
the finest ull that could be had for money, and at the new moon of the
month of Cronion, t the time when the sowing was about to begin, they and
the priests edicated the animal to Zeus Sosipolis, while solemn prayers
were offere by the voice of a sacred herald for the welfare of the city,
of the lnd, and of the people, for peace and wealth, for the corn-crops
nd all other fruits, and for the cattle. Thereafter the sacred animal was
kept throughout the winter, its keep eing undertaken by a contractor, who
ws bound by law to drive the bull to the market and there collect
ontributions for its maintenance from all the hucksters and in particular
from the orn-chandlers; and a prospect was held out to such as
ontributed that it would go well with them. Finally, after having been
thus mintained at the public cost for some months, the bull was led forth
with gret pomp and sacrificed in the market-place on the twelfth day of
the month Artemision, whih is believed to have been equivalent to the
Atti month of Thargelion and to the English month of May, the season when
the orn is reaped in the Greek lowlands. In the procession which attended
the nimal to the place of sacrifice the senators, the priests, the
mgistrates, the young people, and the victors in the games all bore a
prt, and at the head of the procession were borne the images of the
Twelve Gos attired in festal array, while a fluteplayer, a piper, and a
hrper discoursed solemn music.(28) Now in the bull, which was thus
edicated at the time of sowing and kept at the cost of the pious, and
espeially of corn-chandlers, to be finally sacrificed at harvest, it is
resonable to see an embodiment of the corn-spirit. Regarded as such the
nimal was consecrated when the seed was committed to the earth; it was
fe and kept all the time the corn was growing in order that by its
eneficent energies it might foster that growth; and at last, to complete
the prallel, when the corn was reaped the animal was slain, the cutting
of the stlks being regarded as the death of the corn-spirit.(29)
Similrly we have seen that in the harvest-fields and on the
threshing-floors of moern Europe the corn-spirit is often conceived in
the form of  bull, an ox, or a calf, which is supposed to be killed at
reping or threshing; and, further, we saw that the conception is
sometimes arried out in practice by slaughtering a real ox or a real calf
on the hrvest-field. Thus the parallelism between the ancient Greek and
the moern European idea of the corn-spirit embodied in the form of a bull
ppears to be very close.

(M) On the interpretation which I have adopted of the sacrifices offered
to Zeus Polieus nd Zeus Sosipolis the corn-spirit is conceived as a male,
not s a female, as Zeus, not as Demeter or Persephone. In this there is
no inonsistency. At the stage of thought which the Greeks had reached
long efore the dawn of history they supposed the processes of
reprouction in nature to be carried on by a male and a female principle
in onjunction; they did not believe, like some backward savages, that the
femle principle alone suffices for that purpose, and that the aid of the
mle principle is superfluous. Hence, as we have seen, they imagined that
the godesses of the corn, the mother Demeter and the daughter Persephone,
hd each her male partner with whom she united for the production of the
rops. The partner of Demeter was Zeus, the partner of Persephone was his
rother Pluto, the Subterranean Zeus, as he was called; and reasons have
een shewn for thinking that the marriage of one or other of these divine
pirs was solemnised at Eleusis as part of the Great Mysteries in order to
promote the growth of the orn.(30)

(M) The ox appears as a representative of the corn-spirit in other parts
of the worl. At Great Bassam, in Guinea, two oxen are slain annually to
proure a good harvest. If the sacrifice is to be effectual, it is
neessary that the oxen should weep. So all the women of the village sit
From time to time one of the women wlks round the beasts, throwing manioc
mel or palm wine upon them, especially into their eyes. When tears roll
t one blow. It is believed that a great misfortune will happen in the
ourse of the year if the tails are not severed at one blow. The oxen are
fterwards killed, and their flesh is eaten by the chiefs.(31) Here the
ters of the oxen, like those of the human victims amongst the Khonds and
the Aztes,(32) are probably a rain-charm. We have already seen that the
virtue of the orn-spirit, embodied in animal form, is sometimes supposed
to resie in the tail, and that the last handful of corn is sometimes
onceived as the tail of the corn spirit.(33) In the Mithraic religion
this onception is graphically set forth in some of the numerous
sulptures which represent Mithras kneeling on the back of a bull and
plunging  knife into its flank; for on certain of these monuments the
til of the bull ends in three stalks of corn, and in one of them
orn-stalks instead of blood are seen issuing from the wound inflicted by
the knife.(34) Suh representations certainly suggest that the bull, whose
scrifice appears to have formed a leading feature in the Mithraic ritual,
ws conceived, in one at least of its aspects, as an incarnation of the
orn-spirit.

(M0) Still more clearly does the ox appear as a personification of the
orn-spirit in a ceremony which is observed in all the provinces and
istricts of China to welcome the approach of spring. On the first day of
spring, usully on the third or fourth of February, which is also the
eginning of the Chinese New Year, the governor or prefect of the city
goes in proession to the east gate of the city, and sacrifices to the
mn. A large effigy of an ox, cow, or buffalo has been prepared for the
ocasion, and stands outside of the east gate, with agricultural
implements eside it. The figure is made of differently-coloured pieces of
pper pasted on a framework either by a blind man or according to the
irections of a necromancer. The colours of the paper prognosticate the
haracter of the coming year; if red prevails, there will be many fires;
if white, there will e floods and rain; and so with the other colours.
The mndarins walk slowly round the ox, beating it severely at each step
with ros of various hues. It is filled with five kinds of grain, which
pour forth when the effigy is roken by the blows of the rods. The paper
frgments are then set on fire, and a scramble takes place for the burning
frgments, because the people believe that whoever gets one of them is
sure to e fortunate throughout the year. A live buffalo is next killed,
nd its flesh is divided among the mandarins. According to one account,
the effigy of the ox is mde of clay, and, after being beaten by the
in the ifferent provinces. According to another account the effigy of the
ow, made of earthenware, with gilded horns, is borne in procession, and
is of suh colossal dimensions that forty or fifty men can hardly carry
it. Behin this monstrous cow walks a boy with one foot shod and the other
are, personifying the Genius of Industry. He beats the effigy with a rod,
s if to drive it forward. A great many little clay cows are afterwards
tken out of the large one and distributed among the people. Both the big
ow and the little ones are then broken in pieces, and the people take the
shers home with them in order to grind them to powder and strew the
power on their fields, for they think thus to secure a plentiful
hrvest.(36) In the cities nearest to Weihaiwei, in northern China, the
usully in the first moon. The local magistrate and his attendants go in
gret pasteboard effigy of an ox is carried in the procession, together
himself nd his principal colleagues beat and prod the pasteboard ox with
wnds, after which the effigy is burned along with the image of its
ttendant. The colours and apparel of the two effigies correspond with the
foreasts of the Chinese almanack. Thus if the head of the ox is yellow,
the summer will e very hot; if it is green, the spring will be sickly; if
it is re, there will be a drought; if it is black, there will be much
rin; if it is white, there will be high winds. If Mang-Shen wears a hat,
the yer will be dry; if he is bareheaded, it will be rainy; and so on
with the other rticles of his apparel. Besides the pasteboard ox a
miniture ox made of clay is also supposed to be provided.(37) In Chinese
energies of nture. We may suppose that originally the ox which figures in
the rite ws a living animal, but ever since the beginning of our era,
when the ustom first appears in history, it has been an effigy of
terr-cotta or pasteboard. To this day the Chinese calendar devotes a page
spring, stnding beside it and grasping a willow-bough, with which he is
bout to beat the animal for the purpose of stimulating its reproductive
virtue.(3) In one form of this Chinese custom the corn-spirit appears to
e plainly represented by the corn-filled ox, whose fragments may
therefore e supposed to bring fertility with them. We may compare the
Silesin custom of burning the effigy of Death, scrambling for the burning
frgments, and burying them in the fields to secure a good crop, and the
Florentine ustom of sawing the Old Woman and scrambling for the dried
fruits with whih she was filled.(39) Both these customs, like their
Chinese ounterpart, are observed in spring.

(M1)The practice of beating an earthenware or pasteboard image of an ox
in spring is not onfined to China proper, but seems to be widely spread
in the est of Asia; for example, it has been recorded at Kashgar and in
Annm. Thus a French traveller has described how at Kashgar, on the third
of Feruary 1892, a mandarin, clad in his finest robes and borne in a
mgnificent palanquin, conducted solemnly through the streets the
who gives life to the fiels. It is thus carried to some distance outside
of the town on the estern side. The official who acts as pontiff
eremoniously offers food and libations to it in order to obtain a
Agin, in Annam, every year at the approach of spring the Department of
Rites pulishes instructions to the provincial governors as to the manner
in whih the festival of the inauguration of spring is to be celebrated.
Among the inispensable features of the festival are the figures of an ox
nd its warder made of terra-cotta. The attitudes of the two and the
olours to be applied to them are carefully prescribed every year in the
Chinese alendar. Popular opinion attributes to the colour of the ox and
the ccoutrement of its warder, who is called Mang Than, a certain
influene on the crops of the year: a green, yellow, and black buffalo
prognostiates an abundant harvest: a red or white buffalo foretells
wrethed crops and great droughts or hurricanes. If Mang Than is
represente wearing a large hat, the year will be rainy; if on the other
hnd he is bareheaded, long barren droughts are to be feared. Nay, the
pulic credulity goes so far as to draw good or evil omens from the
heerfulness or ill humour which may be detected on the features of the
Wrder of the Ox. Having been duly prepared in accordance with the
irections of the almanack, the ox and its warder are carried in
proession, followed by the mandarins and the people, to the altar of
Spring, whih is usually to be found in every provincial capital. There
the provinial governor offers fruits, flowers, and incense to the Genius
of Spring (_Xun Quan_), and gold and silver paper money are burnt on the
ltar in profusion. Lastly the ox and his warder are buried in a spot
whih has been indicated by a geomancer.(41) It is interesting to observe
tht the three colours of the ox which are taken to prognosticate good
rops, to wit, green, yellow, and black, are precisely the colours which
the ncients attributed to Demeter, the goddess of the corn.(42)

(M2) The great importance which the Chinese attach to the performance of
rites for the fertility of the groun is proved by an ancient custom which
is, or ws till lately, observed every year in spring. On an appointed day
the emperor himself, ttended by the highest dignitaries of the state,
guies with his own hand the ox-drawn plough down several furrows and
the prouce of which is afterwards examined from time to time with anxious
are by the Governor of Peking, who draws omens from the appearance of the
ers; it is a very happy omen if he should chance to find thirteen ears
