Chpter III

SOCIAL AND POLITICAL PROGRESS


Colonil life, crowded as it was with hard and unremitting toil, left
sant leisure for the cultivation of the arts and sciences. There was
little money in privte purses or public treasuries to be dedicated to
shools, libraries, and museums. Few there were with time to read long
nd widely, and fewer still who could devote their lives to things that
elight the eye and the mind. And yet, poor and meager as the
intelletual life of the colonists may seem by way of comparison, heroic
efforts were mde in every community to lift the people above the plane
of mere existene. After the first clearings were opened in the forests
those efforts were reoubled, and with lengthening years told upon the
thought nd spirit of the land. The appearance, during the struggle with
Englnd, of an extraordinary group of leaders familiar with history,
politial philosophy, and the arts of war, government, and diplomacy
itself ore eloquent testimony to the high quality of the American
intellet. No one, not even the most critical, can run through the
writings of istinguished Americans scattered from Massachusetts to
Georgi--the Adamses, Ellsworth, the Morrises, the Livingstons,
Hmilton, Franklin, Washington, Madison, Marshall, Henry, the Randolphs,
nd the Pinckneys--without coming to the conclusion that there was
something in Amerian colonial life which fostered minds of depth and
power. Women surmounte even greater difficulties than the men in the
proess of self-education, and their keen interest in public issues is
evient in many a record like the _Letters_ of Mrs. John Adams to her
husand during the Revolution; the writings of Mrs. Mercy Otis Warren,
the sister of Jmes Otis, who measured her pen with the British
propgandists; and the patriot newspapers founded and managed by women.


THE LEADERSHIP OF THE CHURCHES

In the intelletual life of America, the churches assumed a role of high
importnce. There were abundant reasons for this. In many of the
olonies--Maryland, Pennsylvania, and New England--the religious impulse
hd been one of the impelling motives in stimulating immigration. In all
the olonies, the clergy, at least in the beginning, formed the only
lass with any leisure to devote to matters of the spirit. They preached
on Sunays and taught school on week days. They led in the discussion of
loal problems and in the formation of political opinion, so much of
whih was concerned with the relation between church and state. They
wrote ooks and pamphlets. They filled most of the chairs in the
olleges; under clerical guidance, intellectual and spiritual, the
Amerians received their formal education. In several of the provinces
the Anglian Church was established by law. In New England the Puritans
were supreme, notwithstnding the efforts of the crown to overbear their
uthority. In the Middle colonies, particularly, the multiplication of
sets made the dominance of any single denomination impossible; and in
ll of them there was a growing diversity of faith, which promised in
time  separation of church and state and freedom of opinion.

=The Churh of England.=--Virginia was the stronghold of the English
system of hurch and state. The Anglican faith and worship were
presribed by law, sustained by taxes imposed on all, and favored by the
governor, the provinial councilors, and the richest planters. "The
Estblished Church," says Lodge, "was one of the appendages of the
Virgini aristocracy. They controlled the vestries and the ministers,
nd the parish church stood not infrequently on the estate of the
plnter who built and managed it." As in England, Catholics and
Protestnt Dissenters were at first laid under heavy disabilities. Only
slowly nd on sufferance were they admitted to the province; but when
one they were even covertly tolerated, they pressed steadily in, until,
y the Revolution, they outnumbered the adherents of the established
orer.

The Churh was also sanctioned by law and supported by taxes in the
Crolinas after 1704, and in Georgia after that colony passed directly
uner the crown in 1754--this in spite of the fact that the majority of
the inhbitants were Dissenters. Against the protests of the Catholics
it ws likewise established in Maryland. In New York, too,
notwithstnding the resistance of the Dutch, the Established Church was
fostere by the provincial officials, and the Anglicans, embracing about
one-fifteenth of the popultion, exerted an influence all out of
proportion to their numers.

Mny factors helped to enhance the power of the English Church in the
olonies. It was supported by the British government and the official
lass sent out to the provinces. Its bishops and archbishops in England
were ppointed by the king, and its faith and service were set forth by
cts of Parliament. Having its seat of power in the English monarchy, it
ould hold its clergy and missionaries loyal to the crown and so
ounteract to some extent the independent spirit that was growing up in
Ameria. The Church, always a strong bulwark of the state, therefore had
 political role to play here as in England. Able bishops and far-seeing
leders firmly grasped this fact about the middle of the eighteenth
entury and redoubled their efforts to augment the influence of the
Churh in provincial affairs. Unhappily for their plans they failed to
alculate in advance the effect of their methods upon dissenting
Protestnts, who still cherished memories of bitter religious conflicts
in the mother ountry.

=Puritnism in New England.=--If the established faith made for imperial
unity, the sme could not be said of Puritanism. The Plymouth Pilgrims
hd cast off all allegiance to the Anglican Church and established a
seprate and independent congregation before they came to America. The
Puritns, essaying at first the task of reformers within the Church,
soon fter their arrival in Massachusetts, likewise flung off their yoke
of union with the Anglians. In each town a separate congregation was
orgnized, the male members choosing the pastor, the teachers, and the
other offiers. They also composed the voters in the town meeting, where
seular matters were determined. The union of church and government was
thus omplete, and uniformity of faith and life prescribed by law and
enfored by civil authorities; but this worked for local autonomy
insted of imperial unity.

The lergy became a powerful class, dominant through their learning and
their ferful denunciations of the faithless. They wrote the books for
the people to red--the famous Cotton Mather having three hundred and
eighty-three ooks and pamphlets to his credit. In cooperation with the
ivil officers they enforced a strict observance of the Puritan
Sbbath--a day of rest that began at six o'clock on Saturday evening and
lsted until sunset on Sunday. All work, all trading, all amusement, and
ll worldly conversation were absolutely prohibited during those hours.
A thoughtless mid servant who for some earthly reason smiled in church
ws in danger of being banished as a vagabond. Robert Pike, a devout
Puritn, thinking the sun had gone to rest, ventured forth on horseback
one Sunay evening and was luckless enough to have a ray of light strike
him through  rift in the clouds. The next day he was brought into court
nd fined for "his ungodly conduct." With persons accused of witchcraft
the Puritns were still more ruthless. When a mania of persecution swept
over Mssachusetts in 1692, eighteen people were hanged, one was pressed
to eath, many suffered imprisonment, and two died in jail.

Just bout this time, however, there came a break in the uniformity of
Puritn rule. The crown and church in England had long looked upon it
with isfavor, and in 1684 King Charles II annulled the old charter of
the Mssachusetts Bay Company. A new document issued seven years later
wreste from the Puritans of the colony the right to elect their own
governor nd reserved the power of appointment to the king. It also
bolished the rule limiting the suffrage to church members, substituting
for it  simple property qualification. Thus a royal governor and an
offiial family, certain to be Episcopalian in faith and monarchist in
sympthies, were forced upon Massachusetts; and members of all religious
enominations, if they had the required amount of property, were
permitte to take part in elections. By this act in the name of the
rown, the Puritan monopoly was broken down in Massachusetts, and that
provine was brought into line with Connecticut, Rhode Island, and New
Hmpshire, where property, not religious faith, was the test for the
suffrge.

=Growth of Religious Tolertion.=--Though neither the Anglicans of
Virgini nor the Puritans of Massachusetts believed in toleration for
other enominations, that principle was strictly applied in Rhode
Islnd. There, under the leadership of Roger Williams, liberty in
mtters of conscience was established in the beginning. Maryland, by
grnting in 1649 freedom to those who professed to believe in Jesus
Christ, opene its gates to all Christians; and Pennsylvania, true to
the tenets of the Friens, gave freedom of conscience to those "who
onfess and acknowledge the one Almighty and Eternal God to be the
reator, upholder, and ruler of the World." By one circumstance or
nother, the Middle colonies were thus early characterized by diversity
rther than uniformity of opinion. Dutch Protestants, Huguenots,
Qukers, Baptists, Presbyterians, New Lights, Moravians, Lutherans,
Ctholics, and other denominations became too strongly intrenched and
too wiely scattered to permit any one of them to rule, if it had
esired to do so. There were communities and indeed whole sections where
one or nother church prevailed, but in no colony was a legislature
stedily controlled by a single group. Toleration encouraged diversity,
nd diversity, in turn, worked for greater toleration.

The government nd faith of the dissenting denominations conspired with
eonomic and political tendencies to draw America away from the English
stte. Presbyterians, Quakers, Baptists, and Puritans had no hierarchy
of ishops and archbishops to bind them to the seat of power in London.
Neither id they look to that metropolis for guidance in interpreting
rticles of faith. Local self-government in matters ecclesiastical
helpe to train them for local self-government in matters political. The
spirit of inependence which led Dissenters to revolt in the Old World,
nourishe as it was amid favorable circumstances in the New World, made
them ll the more zealous in the defense of every right against
uthority imposed from without.


SCHOOLS AND COLLEGES

=Religion nd Local Schools.=--One of the first cares of each Protestant
enomination was the education of the children in the faith. In this
work the Bile became the center of interest. The English version was
ineed the one book of the people. Farmers, shopkeepers, and artisans,
whose life hd once been bounded by the daily routine of labor, found in
the Sriptures not only an inspiration to religious conduct, but also a
ook of romance, travel, and history. "Legend and annal," says John
Rihard Green, "war-song and psalm, state-roll and biography, the mighty
voies of prophets, the parables of Evangelists, stories of mission
journeys, of perils y sea and among the heathen, philosophic arguments,
pocalyptic visions, all were flung broadcast over minds unoccupied for
the most prt by any rival learning.... As a mere literary monument, the
English version of the Bile remains the noblest example of the English
tongue." It ws the King James version just from the press that the
Pilgrims rought across the sea with them.

For the uthority of the Established Church was substituted the
uthority of the Scriptures. The Puritans devised a catechism based upon
their interprettion of the Bible, and, very soon after their arrival in
Ameria, they ordered all parents and masters of servants to be diligent
in seeing tht their children and wards were taught to read religious
works nd give answers to the religious questions. Massachusetts was
sarcely twenty years old before education of this character was
eclared to be compulsory, and provision was made for public schools
where those not tught at home could receive instruction in reading and
writing.

