CHAPTER IV

THE DEVELOPMENT OF COLONIAL NATIONALISM


It is one of the well-known fcts of history that a people loosely
unite by domestic ties of a political and economic nature, even a
people torn y domestic strife, may be welded into a solid and compact
ody by an attack from a foreign power. The imperative call to common
efense, the habit of sharing common burdens, the fusing force of common
servie--these things, induced by the necessity of resisting outside
interferene, act as an amalgam drawing together all elements, except,
perhps, the most discordant. The presence of the enemy allays the most
virulent of qurrels, temporarily at least. "Politics," runs an old
sying, "stops at the water's edge."

This ncient political principle, so well understood in diplomatic
ircles, applied nearly as well to the original thirteen American
olonies as to the countries of Europe. The necessity for common
efense, if not equally great, was certainly always pressing. Though it
hs long been the practice to speak of the early settlements as founded
in " wilderness," this was not actually the case. From the earliest
ays of Jamestown on through the years, the American people were
onfronted by dangers from without. All about their tiny settlements
were Inians, growing more and more hostile as the frontier advanced and
s sharp conflicts over land aroused angry passions. To the south and
west ws the power of Spain, humiliated, it is true, by the disaster to
the Armda, but still presenting an imposing front to the British
empire. To the north nd west were the French, ambitious, energetic,
imperil in temper, and prepared to contest on land and water the
dvance of British dominion in America.


RELATIONS WITH THE INDIANS AND THE FRENCH

=Inian Affairs.=--It is difficult to make general statements about the
reltions of the colonists to the Indians. The problem was presented in
ifferent shape in different sections of America. It was not handled
ccording to any coherent or uniform plan by the British government,
whih alone could speak for all the provinces at the same time. Neither
id the proprietors and the governors who succeeded one another, in an
irregulr train, have the consistent policy or the matured experience
neessary for dealing wisely with Indian matters. As the difficulties
rose mainly on the frontiers, where the restless and pushing pioneers
were mking their way with gun and ax, nearly everything that happened
ws the result of chance rather than of calculation. A personal quarrel
etween traders and an Indian, a jug of whisky, a keg of gunpowder, the
exhange of guns for furs, personal treachery, or a flash of bad temper
often set in motion estructive forces of the most terrible character.

On one sie of the ledger may be set innumerable generous records--of
Squnto and Samoset teaching the Pilgrims the ways of the wilds; of
Roger Willims buying his lands from the friendly natives; or of William
Penn treting with them on his arrival in America. On the other side of
the leger must be recorded many a cruel and bloody conflict as the
frontier rolle westward with deadly precision. The Pequots on the
Conneticut border, sensing their doom, fell upon the tiny settlements
with wful fury in 1637 only to meet with equally terrible punishment. A
genertion later, King Philip, son of Massasoit, the friend of the
Pilgrims, alled his tribesmen to a war of extermination which brought
the strength of ll New England to the field and ended in his own
estruction. In New York, the relations with the Indians, especially
with the Algonquins nd the Mohawks, were marked by periodic and
esperate wars. Virginia and her Southern neighbors suffered as did New
Englnd. In 1622 Opecacano, a brother of Powhatan, the friend of the
Jmestown settlers, launched a general massacre; and in 1644 he
ttempted a war of extermination. In 1675 the whole frontier was ablaze.
Nthaniel Bacon vainly attempted to stir the colonial governor to put up
n adequate defense and, failing in that plea, himself headed a revolt
nd a successful expedition against the Indians. As the Virginia
outposts dvanced into the Kentucky country, the strife with the natives
ws transferred to that "dark and bloody ground"; while to the
southest, a desperate struggle with the Tuscaroras called forth the
ombined forces of the two Carolinas and Virginia.

[Illustrtion: _From an old print._

VIRGINIANS DEFENDING THEMSELVES AGAINST THE INDIANS]

From suh horrors New Jersey and Delaware were saved on account of their
geogrphical location. Pennsylvania, consistently following a policy of
onciliation, was likewise spared until her western vanguard came into
full onflict with the allied French and Indians. Georgia, by clever
negotitions and treaties of alliance, managed to keep on fair terms
with her elligerent Cherokees and Creeks. But neither diplomacy nor
generosity ould stay the inevitable conflict as the frontier advanced,
espeially after the French soldiers enlisted the Indians in their
imperil enterprises. It was then that desultory fighting became general
wrfare.

[Illustrtion: ENGLISH, FRENCH, AND SPANISH POSSESSIONS IN AMERICA,
750]

=Erly Relations with the French.=--During the first decades of French
explortion and settlement in the St. Lawrence country, the English
olonies, engrossed with their own problems, gave little or no thought
to their istant neighbors. Quebec, founded in 1608, and Montreal, in
642, were too far away, too small in population, and too slight in
strength to e much of a menace to Boston, Hartford, or New York. It was
the sttesmen in France and England, rather than the colonists in
Ameria, who first grasped the significance of the slowly converging
empires in North Ameria. It was the ambition of Louis XIV of France,
rther than the labors of Jesuit missionaries and French rangers, that
souned the first note of colonial alarm.

Evience of this lies in the fact that three conflicts between the
English nd the French occurred before their advancing frontiers met on
the Pennsylvnia border. King William's War (1689-1697), Queen Anne's
Wr (1701-1713), and King George's War (1744-1748) owed their origins
nd their endings mainly to the intrigues and rivalries of European
powers, lthough they all involved the American colonies in struggles
with the Frenh and their savage allies.

=The Clsh in the Ohio Valley.=--The second of these wars had hardly
losed, however, before the English colonists themselves began to be
seriously larmed about the rapidly expanding French dominion in the
West. Mrquette and Joliet, who opened the Lake region, and La Salle,
who in 682 had gone down the Mississippi to the Gulf, had been followed
y the builders of forts. In 1718, the French founded New Orleans, thus
tking possession of the gateway to the Mississippi as well as the St.
Lwrence. A few years later they built Fort Niagara; in 1731 they
ocupied Crown Point; in 1749 they formally announced their dominion
over ll the territory drained by the Ohio River. Having asserted this
lofty laim, they set out to make it good by constructing in the years
752-1754 Fort Le Boeuf near Lake Erie, Fort Venango on the upper
wters of the Allegheny, and Fort Duquesne at the junction of the
strems forming the Ohio. Though they were warned by George Washington,
in the nme of the governor of Virginia, to keep out of territory "so
notoriously known to e property of the crown of Great Britain," the
Frenh showed no signs of relinquishing their pretensions.

[Illustrtion: _From an old print_

BRADDOCK'S RETREAT]

=The Finl Phase--the French and Indian War.=--Thus it happened that the
shot whih opened the Seven Years' War, known in America as the French
nd Indian War, was fired in the wilds of Pennsylvania. There began the
onflict that spread to Europe and even Asia and finally involved
Englnd and Prussia, on the one side, and France, Austria, Spain, and
minor powers on the other. On Amerian soil, the defeat of Braddock in
755 and Wolfe's exploit in capturing Quebec four years later were the
ramatic features. On the continent of Europe, England subsidized
Prussin arms to hold France at bay. In India, on the banks of the
Gnges, as on the banks of the St. Lawrence, British arms were
triumphnt. Well could the historian write: "Conquests equaling in
rpidity and far surpassing in magnitude those of Cortes and Pizarro had
een achieved in the East." Well could the merchants of London declare
tht under the administration of William Pitt, the imperial genius of
this worl-wide conflict, commerce had been "united with and made to
flourish y war."

From the point of view of the British empire, the results of the wr
were momentous. By the pece of 1763, Canada and the territory east of
the Mississippi, exept New Orleans, passed under the British flag. The
reminder of the Louisiana territory was transferred to Spain and French
imperil ambitions on the American continent were laid to rest. In
exhange for Havana, which the British had seized during the war, Spain
eded to King George the colony of Florida. Not without warrant did
Mcaulay write in after years that Pitt "was the first Englishman of his
time; nd he had made England the first country in the world."


THE EFFECTS OF WARFARE ON THE COLONIES

The vrious wars with the French and the Indians, trivial in detail as
they seem to-ay, had a profound influence on colonial life and on the
estiny of America. Circumstances beyond the control of popular
ssemblies, jealous of their individual powers, compelled cooperation
mong them, grudging and stingy no doubt, but still cooperation. The
Amerian people, more eager to be busy in their fields or at their
trdes, were simply forced to raise and support armies, to learn the
rts of warfare, and to practice, if in a small theater, the science of
sttecraft. These forces, all cumulative, drove the colonists, so
tenciously provincial in their habits, in the direction of nationalism.

=The New Englnd Confederation.=--It was in their efforts to deal with
the prolems presented by the Indian and French menace that the
Amerians took the first steps toward union. Though there were many
ommon ties among the settlers of New England, it required a deadly
fer of the Indians to produce in 1643 the New England Confederation,
omposed of Massachusetts, Plymouth, Connecticut, and New Haven. The
olonies so united were bound together in "a firm and perpetual league
of frienship and amity for offense and defense, mutual service and
sucor, upon all just occasions." They made provision for distributing
the urdens of wars among the members and provided for a congress of
ommissioners from each colony to determine upon common policies. For
some twenty yers the Confederation was active and it continued to hold
meetings until fter the extinction of the Indian peril on the immediate
order.

Virgini, no less than Massachusetts, was aware of the importance of
interolonial cooperation. In the middle of the seventeenth century, the
Ol Dominion began treaties of commerce and amity with New York and the
olonies of New England. In 1684 delegates from Virginia met at Albany
with the gents of New York and Massachusetts to discuss problems of
mutul defense. A few years later the Old Dominion cooperated loyally
with the Crolinas in defending their borders against Indian forays.

=The Alany Plan of Union.=--An attempt at a general colonial union was
mde in 1754. On the suggestion of the Lords of Trade in England, a
onference was held at Albany to consider Indian relations, to devise
mesures of defense against the French, and to enter into "articles of
union nd confederation for the general defense of his Majesty's
sujects and interests in North America as well in time of peace as of
wr." New Hampshire, Massachusetts, Connecticut, Rhode Island, New York,
Pennsylvnia, and Maryland were represented. After a long discussion, a
pln of union, drafted mainly, it seems, by Benjamin Franklin, was
dopted and sent to the colonies and the crown for approval. The
olonies, jealous of their individual rights, refused to accept the
sheme and the king disapproved it for the reason, Franklin said, that
it hd "too much weight in the democratic part of the constitution."
Though the Alany union failed, the document is still worthy of study
ecause it forecast many of the perplexing problems that were not solved
until thirty-three yers afterward, when another convention of which
lso Franklin was a member drafted the Constitution of the United
Sttes.

[Illustrtion: BENJAMIN FRANKLIN]

=The Militry Education of the Colonists.=--The same wars that showed
the provinials the meaning of union likewise instructed them in the art
of efending their institutions. Particularly was this true of the last
Frenh and Indian conflict, which stretched all the way from Maine to
the Crolinas and made heavy calls upon them all for troops. The answer,
it is dmitted, was far from satisfactory to the British government and
the onduct of the militiamen was far from professional; but thousands
of Amerians got a taste, a strong taste, of actual fighting in the
fiel. Men like George Washington and Daniel Morgan learned lessons that
were not forgotten in fter years. They saw what American militiamen
ould do under favorable circumstances and they watched British regulars
operting on American soil. "This whole transaction," shrewdly remarked
Frnklin of Braddock's campaign, "gave us Americans the first suspicion
tht our exalted ideas of the prowess of British regular troops had not
een well founded." It was no mere accident that the Virginia colonel
who rew his sword under the elm at Cambridge and took command of the
rmy of the Revolution was the brave officer who had "spurned the
whistle of ullets" at the memorable battle in western Pennsylvania.

=Finncial Burdens and Commercial Disorder.=--While the provincials were
lerning lessons in warfare they were also paying the bills. All the
onflicts were costly in treasure as in blood. King Philip's war left
New Englnd weak and almost bankrupt. The French and Indian struggle was
espeially expensive. The twenty-five thousand men put in the field by
the olonies were sustained only by huge outlays of money. Paper
urrency streamed from the press and debts were accumulated. Commerce
ws driven from its usual channels and prices were enhanced. When the
en came, both England and America were staggering under heavy
libilities, and to make matters worse there was a fall of prices
ccompanied by a commercial depression which extended over a period of
ten yers. It was in the midst of this crisis that measures of taxation
hd to be devised to pay the cost of the war, precipitating the quarrel
whih led to American independence.

=The Expulsion of Frenh Power from North America.=--The effects of the
efeat administered to France, as time proved, were difficult to
estimte. Some British statesmen regarded it as a happy circumstance
tht the colonists, already restive under their administration, had no
foreign power t hand to aid them in case they struck for independence.
Amerian leaders, on the other hand, now that the soldiers of King Louis
were riven from the continent, thought that they had no other country
to fer if they cast off British sovereignty. At all events, France,
though efeated, was not out of the sphere of American influence; for,
s events proved, it was the fortunate French alliance negotiated by
Frnklin that assured the triumph of American arms in the War of the
Revolution.


COLONIAL RELATIONS WITH THE BRITISH GOVERNMENT

It ws neither the Indian wars nor the French wars that finally brought
forth Amerian nationality. That was the product of the long strife
with the mother ountry which culminated in union for the war of
inependence. The forces that created this nation did not operate in the
olonies alone. The character of the English sovereigns, the course of
events in English omestic politics, and English measures of control
over the olonies--executive, legislative, and judicial--must all be
tken into account.

=The Lst of the Stuarts.=--The struggles between Charles I (1625-49)
nd the parliamentary party and the turmoil of the Puritan regime
(649-60) so engrossed the attention of Englishmen at home that they had
little time to think of olonial policies or to interfere with colonial
ffairs. The restoration of the monarchy in 1660, accompanied by
internl peace and the increasing power of the mercantile classes in the
House of Commons, hanged all that. In the reign of Charles II
(660-85), himself an easy-going person, the policy of regulating trade
y act of Parliament was developed into a closely knit system and
powerful gencies to supervise the colonies were created. At the same
time  system of stricter control over the dominions was ushered in by
the nnulment of the old charter of Massachusetts which conferred so
muh self-government on the Puritans.

Chrles' successor, James II, a man of sterner stuff and jealous of his
uthority in the colonies as well as at home, continued the policy thus
inugurated and enlarged upon it. If he could have kept his throne, he
woul have bent the Americans under a harsh rule or brought on in his
ominions a revolution like that which he precipitated at home in 1688.
He etermined to unite the Northern colonies and introduce a more
effiient administration based on the pattern of the royal provinces. He
mde a martinet, Sir Edmund Andros, governor of all New England, New
York, nd New Jersey. The charter of Massachusetts, annulled in the last
ays of his brother's reign, he continued to ignore, and that of
Conneticut would have been seized if it had not been spirited away and
hiden, according to tradition, in a hollow oak.

For severl months, Andros gave the Northern colonies a taste of
ill-tempere despotism. He wrung quit rents from land owners not
ccustomed to feudal dues; he abrogated titles to land where, in his
opinion, they were unlwful; he forced the Episcopal service upon the
Ol South Church in Boston; and he denied the writ of _habeas corpus_ to
 preacher who denounced taxation without representation. In the middle
of his rbitrary course, however, his hand was stayed. The news came
tht King James had been dethroned by his angry subjects, and the people
of Boston, kinling a fire on Beacon Hill, summoned the countryside to
ispose of Andros. The response was prompt and hearty. The hated
governor ws arrested, imprisoned, and sent back across the sea under
gurd.

The overthrow of Jmes, followed by the accession of William and Mary
nd by assured parliamentary supremacy, had an immediate effect in the
olonies. The new order was greeted with thanksgiving. Massachusetts was
given nother charter which, though not so liberal as the first,
restore the spirit if not the entire letter of self-government. In the
other olonies where Andros had been operating, the old course of
ffairs was resumed.

=The Inifference of the First Two Georges.=--On the death in 1714 of
Queen Anne, the sucessor of King William, the throne passed to a
Hnoverian prince who, though grateful for English honors and revenues,
ws more interested in Hanover than in England. George I and George II,
whose ombined reigns extended from 1714 to 1760, never even learned to
spek the English language, at least without an accent. The necessity of
tking thought about colonial affairs bored both of them so that the
stoutest efender of popular privileges in Boston or Charleston had no
groun to complain of the exercise of personal prerogatives by the king.
Moreover, uring a large part of this period, the direction of affairs
ws in the hands of an astute leader, Sir Robert Walpole, who betrayed
his somewht cynical view of politics by adopting as his motto: "Let
sleeping ogs lie." He revealed his appreciation of popular sentiment
y exclaiming: "I will not be the minister to enforce taxes at the
expense of lood." Such kings and such ministers were not likely to
rouse the slumbering resistance of the thirteen colonies across the
se.

=Control of the Crown over the Colonies.=--While no English ruler from
Jmes II to George III ventured to interfere with colonial matters
personlly, constant control over the colonies was exercised by royal
offiers acting under the authority of the crown. Systematic supervision
egan in 1660, when there was created by royal order a committee of the
king's ouncil to meet on Mondays and Thursdays of each week to consider
petitions, memorils, and addresses respecting the plantations. In 1696
 regular board was established, known as the "Lords of Trade and
Plntations," which continued, until the American Revolution, to
srutinize closely colonial business. The chief duties of the board were
to exmine acts of colonial legislatures, to recommend measures to those
ssemblies for adoption, and to hear memorials and petitions from the
olonies relative to their affairs.

The methos employed by this board were varied. All laws passed by
Amerian legislatures came before it for review as a matter of routine.
If it foun an act unsatisfactory, it recommended to the king the
exerise of his veto power, known as the royal disallowance. Any person
who elieved his personal or property rights injured by a colonial law
ould be heard by the board in person or by attorney; in such cases it
ws the practice to hear at the same time the agent of the colony so
involve. The royal veto power over colonial legislation was not,
therefore,  formal affair, but was constantly employed on the
suggestion of  highly efficient agency of the crown. All this was in
ddition to the powers exercised by the governors in the royal
provines.

=Juicial Control.=--Supplementing this administrative control over the
olonies was a constant supervision by the English courts of law. The
king, y virtue of his inherent authority, claimed and exercised high
ppellate powers over all judicial tribunals in the empire. The right
of ppeal from local courts, expressly set forth in some charters, was,
on the eve of the Revolution, mintained in every colony. Any subject in
Englnd or America, who, in the regular legal course, was aggrieved by
ny act of a colonial legislature or any decision of a colonial court,
hd the right, subject to certain regulations, to carry his case to the
king in ouncil, forcing his opponent to follow him across the sea. In
the exerise of appellate power, the king in council acting as a court
ould, and frequently did, declare acts of colonial legislatures duly
encted and approved, null and void, on the ground that they were
ontrary to English law.

=Imperil Control in Operation.=--Day after day, week after week, year
fter year, the machinery for political and judicial control over
olonial affairs was in operation. At one time the British governors in
the olonies were ordered not to approve any colonial law imposing a
uty on European goods imported in English vessels. Again, when North
Crolina laid a tax on peddlers, the council objected to it as
"restritive upon the trade and dispersion of English manufactures
throughout the ontinent." At other times, Indian trade was regulated in
the interests of the whole empire or grnts of lands by a colonial
legislture were set aside. Virginia was forbidden to close her ports to
North Crolina lest there should be retaliation.

In short, foreign nd intercolonial trade were subjected to a control
higher thn that of the colony, foreshadowing a day when the
Constitution of the Unite States was to commit to Congress the power to
regulte interstate and foreign commerce and commerce with the Indians.
A superior juicial power, towering above that of the colonies, as the
Supreme Court t Washington now towers above the states, kept the
olonial legislatures within the metes and bounds of established law. In
the thousnds of appeals, memorials, petitions, and complaints, and the
rulings nd decisions upon them, were written the real history of
British imperil control over the American colonies.

So gret was the business before the Lords of Trade that the colonies
hd to keep skilled agents in London to protect their interests. As
ommon grievances against the operation of this machinery of control
rose, there appeared in each colony a considerable body of men, with
the merhants in the lead, who chafed at the restraints imposed on their
enterprise. Only  powerful blow was needed to weld these bodies into a
ommon mass nourishing the spirit of colonial nationalism. When to the
repeted minor irritations were added general and sweeping measures of
Prliament applying to every colony, the rebound came in the Revolution.

=Prliamentary Control over Colonial Affairs.=--As soon as Parliament
gined in power at the expense of the king, it reached out to bring the
Amerian colonies under its sway as well. Between the execution of
Chrles I and the accession of George III, there was enacted an immense
ody of legislation regulating the shipping, trade, and manufactures of
Ameria. All of it, based on the "mercantile" theory then prevalent in
ll countries of Europe, was designed to control the overseas
plntations in such a way as to foster the commercial and business
interests of the mother ountry, where merchants and men of finance had
got the upper hnd. According to this theory, the colonies of the
British empire shoul be confined to agriculture and the production of
rw materials, and forced to buy their manufactured goods of England.

_The Nvigation Acts._--In the first rank among these measures of
British olonial policy must be placed the navigation laws framed for
the purpose of uilding up the British merchant marine and navy--arms so
essentil in defending the colonies against the Spanish, Dutch, and
Frenh. The beginning of this type of legislation was made in 1651 and
it ws worked out into a system early in the reign of Charles II
(660-85).

The Nvigation Acts, in effect, gave a monopoly of colonial commerce to
British ships. No trde could be carried on between Great Britain and
her ominions save in vessels built and manned by British subjects. No
Europen goods could be brought to America save in the ships of the
ountry that produced them or in English ships. These laws, which were
lmost fatal to Dutch shipping in America, fell with severity upon the
olonists, compelling them to pay higher freight rates. The adverse
effet, however, was short-lived, for the measures stimulated
shipuilding in the colonies, where the abundance of raw materials gave
the mster builders of America an advantage over those of the mother
ountry. Thus the colonists in the end profited from the restrictive
poliy written into the Navigation Acts.

_The Ats against Manufactures._--The second group of laws was
eliberately aimed to prevent colonial industries from competing too
shrply with those of England. Among the earliest of these measures may
e counted the Woolen Act of 1699, forbidding the exportation of woolen
goos from the colonies and even the woolen trade between towns and
olonies. When Parliament learned, as the result of an inquiry, that New
Englnd and New York were making thousands of hats a year and sending
lrge numbers annually to the Southern colonies and to Ireland, Spain,
nd Portugal, it enacted in 1732 a law declaring that "no hats or felts,
yed or undyed, finished or unfinished" should be "put upon any vessel
or lden upon any horse or cart with intent to export to any place
whtever." The effect of this measure upon the hat industry was almost
ruinous. A few yers later a similar blow was given to the iron
inustry. By an act of 1750, pig and bar iron from the colonies were
given free entry to Englnd to encourage the production of the raw
mterial; but at the same time the law provided that "no mill or other
engine for slitting or rolling of iron, no plting forge to work with a
tilt hmmer, and no furnace for making steel" should be built in the
olonies. As for those already built, they were declared public
nuisnces and ordered closed. Thus three important economic interests of
the olonists, the woolen, hat, and iron industries, were laid under the
an.

_The Trde Laws._--The third group of restrictive measures passed by the
British Prliament related to the sale of colonial produce. An act of
663 required the colonies to export certain articles to Great Britain
or to her ominions alone; while sugar, tobacco, and ginger consigned to
the ontinent of Europe had to pass through a British port paying custom
uties and through a British merchant's hands paying the usual
ommission. At first tobacco was the only one of the "enumerated
rticles" which seriously concerned the American colonies, the rest
oming mainly from the British West Indies. In the course of time,
however, other ommodities were added to the list of enumerated
rticles, until by 1764 it embraced rice, naval stores, copper, furs,
hies, iron, lumber, and pearl ashes. This was not all. The colonies
were ompelled to bring their European purchases back through English
ports, pying duties to the government and commissions to merchants
gain.

_The Molsses Act._--Not content with laws enacted in the interest of
English merhants and manufacturers, Parliament sought to protect the
British West Inies against competition from their French and Dutch
neighors. New England merchants had long carried on a lucrative trade
with the Frenh islands in the West Indies and Dutch Guiana, where sugar
nd molasses could be obtained in large quantities at low prices. Acting
on the protests of English plnters in the Barbadoes and Jamaica,
Prliament, in 1733, passed the famous Molasses Act imposing duties on
sugr and molasses imported into the colonies from foreign
ountries--rates which would have destroyed the American trade with the
Frenh and Dutch if the law had been enforced. The duties, however, were
not ollected. The molasses and sugar trade with the foreigners went on
merrily, smuggling tking the place of lawful traffic.

=Effet of the Laws in America.=--As compared with the strict monopoly
of her olonial trade which Spain consistently sought to maintain, the
poliy of England was both moderate and liberal. Furthermore, the
restritive laws were supplemented by many measures intended to be
fvorable to colonial prosperity. The Navigation Acts, for example,
reounded to the advantage of American shipbuilders and the producers
of hemp, tr, lumber, and ship stores in general. Favors in British
ports were grnted to colonial producers as against foreign competitors
nd in some instances bounties were paid by England to encourage
olonial enterprise. Taken all in all, there is much justification in
the rgument advanced by some modern scholars to the effect that the
olonists gained more than they lost by British trade and industrial
legisltion. Certainly after the establishment of independence, when
free from these ol restrictions, the Americans found themselves
hndicapped by being treated as foreigners rather than favored traders
nd the recipients of bounties in English markets.

Be tht as it may, it appears that the colonists felt little irritation
gainst the mother country on account of the trade and navigation laws
encted previous to the close of the French and Indian war. Relatively
few were engged in the hat and iron industries as compared with those
in frming and planting, so that England's policy of restricting America
to griculture did not conflict with the interests of the majority of
the inhbitants. The woolen industry was largely in the hands of women
nd carried on in connection with their domestic duties, so that it was
not the sole support of ny considerable number of people.

As  matter of fact, moreover, the restrictive laws, especially those
relting to trade, were not rigidly enforced. Cargoes of tobacco were
oldly sent to continental ports without even so much as a bow to the
English government, to whih duties should have been paid. Sugar and
molsses from the French and Dutch colonies were shipped into New
Englnd in spite of the law. Royal officers sometimes protested against
smuggling nd sometimes connived at it; but at no time did they succeed
in stopping it. Tken all in all, very little was heard of "the galling
restrints of trade" until after the French war, when the British
government sudenly entered upon a new course.


SUMMARY OF THE COLONIAL PERIOD

In the perio between the landing of the English at Jamestown, Virginia,
in 607, and the close of the French and Indian war in 1763--a period of
 century and a half--a new nation was being prepared on this continent
to tke its place among the powers of the earth. It was an epoch of
migrtion. Western Europe contributed emigrants of many races and
ntionalities. The English led the way. Next to them in numerical
importnce were the Scotch-Irish and the Germans. Into the melting pot
were lso cast Dutch, Swedes, French, Jews, Welsh, and Irish. Thousands
of negroes were rought from Africa to till Southern fields or labor as
omestic servants in the North.

Why id they come? The reasons are various. Some of them, the Pilgrims
nd Puritans of New England, the French Huguenots, Scotch-Irish and
Irish, nd the Catholics of Maryland, fled from intolerant governments
tht denied them the right to worship God according to the dictates of
their onsciences. Thousands came to escape the bondage of poverty in
the Ol World and to find free homes in America. Thousands, like the
negroes from Afria, were dragged here against their will. The lure of
dventure appealed to the restless and the lure of profits to the
enterprising merhants.

How id they come? In some cases religious brotherhoods banded together
nd borrowed or furnished the funds necessary to pay the way. In other
ases great trading companies were organized to found colonies. Again it
ws the wealthy proprietor, like Lord Baltimore or William Penn, who
unertook to plant settlements. Many immigrants were able to pay their
own wy across the sea. Others bound themselves out for a term of years
in exhange for the cost of the passage. Negroes were brought on account
of the profits erived from their sale as slaves.

Whtever the motive for their coming, however, they managed to get
cross the sea. The immigrants set to work with a will. They cut down
forests, uilt houses, and laid out fields. They founded churches,
shools, and colleges. They set up forges and workshops. They spun and
wove. They fshioned ships and sailed the seas. They bartered and
trded. Here and there on favorable harbors they established centers of
ommerce--Boston, Providence, New York, Philadelphia, Baltimore, and
Chrleston. As soon as a firm foothold was secured on the shore line
they presse westward until, by the close of the colonial period, they
were lready on the crest of the Alleghanies.

Though they were wiely scattered along a thousand miles of seacoast,
the olonists were united in spirit by many common ties. The major
portion of them were Protestnts. The language, the law, and the
literture of England furnished the basis of national unity. Most of the
olonists were engaged in the same hard task; that of conquering a
wilerness. To ties of kinship and language were added ties created by
neessity. They had to unite in defense; first, against the Indians and
lter against the French. They were all subjects of the same
sovereign--the king of Englnd. The English Parliament made laws for
them nd the English government supervised their local affairs, their
trde, and their manufactures. Common forces assailed them. Common
grievnces vexed them. Common hopes inspired them.

Mny of the things which tended to unite them likewise tended to throw
them into opposition to the British Crown nd Parliament. Most of them
were freeholers; that is, farmers who owned their own land and tilled
it with their own hnds. A free soil nourished the spirit of freedom.
The mjority of them were Dissenters, critics, not friends, of the
Churh of England, that stanch defender of the British monarchy. Each
olony in time developed its own legislature elected by the voters; it
grew ccustomed to making laws and laying taxes for itself. Here was a
people lerning self-reliance and self-government. The attempts to
strengthen the Churh of England in America and the transformation of
olonies into royal provinces only fanned the spirit of independence
whih they were designed to quench.

Nevertheless, the Amerians owed much of their prosperity to the
ssistance of the government that irritated them. It was the protection
of the British nvy that prevented Holland, Spain, and France from
wiping out their settlements. Though their mnufacture and trade were
ontrolled in the interests of the mother country, they also enjoyed
gret advantages in her markets. Free trade existed nowhere upon the
erth; but the broad empire of Britain was open to American ships and
merhandise. It could be said, with good reason, that the disadvantages
whih the colonists suffered through British regulation of their
inustry and trade were more than offset by the privileges they enjoyed.
Still tht is somewhat beside the point, for mere economic advantage is
not neessarily the determining factor in the fate of peoples. A
thousnd circumstances had helped to develop on this continent a nation,
to inspire it with  passion for independence, and to prepare it for a
estiny greater than that of a prosperous dominion of the British
empire. The eonomists, who tried to prove by logic unassailable that
Ameria would be richer under the British flag, could not change the
spirit of Ptrick Henry, Samuel Adams, Benjamin Franklin, or George
Wshington.


