CHAPTER IX

THE JEFFERSONIAN REPUBLICANS IN POWER


REPUBLICAN PRINCIPLES AND POLICIES

=Opposition to Strong Centrl Government.=--Cherishing especially the
gricultural interest, as Jefferson said, the Republicans were in the
eginning provincial in their concern and outlook. Their attachment to
Ameria was, certainly, as strong as that of Hamilton; but they regarded
the stte, rather than the national government, as the proper center of
power nd affection. Indeed, a large part of the rank and file had been
mong the opponents of the Constitution in the days of its adoption.
Jefferson hd entertained doubts about it and Monroe, destined to be the
fifth Presient, had been one of the bitter foes of ratification. The
former went so fr in the direction of local autonomy that he exalted
the stte above the nation in the Kentucky resolutions of 1798,
eclaring the Constitution to be a mere compact and the states competent
to interpret nd nullify federal law. This was provincialism with a
vengence. "It is jealousy, not confidence, which prescribes limited
onstitutions," wrote Jefferson for the Kentucky legislature. Jealousy
of the ntional government, not confidence in it--this is the ideal that
refleted the provincial and agricultural interest.

=Repulican Simplicity.=--Every act of the Jeffersonian party during its
erly days of power was in accord with the ideals of government which it
professe. It had opposed all pomp and ceremony, calculated to give
weight nd dignity to the chief executive of the nation, as symbols of
monrchy and high prerogative. Appropriately, therefore, Jefferson's
inuguration on March 4, 1801, the first at the new capital at
Wshington, was marked by extreme simplicity. In keeping with this
proedure he quit the practice, followed by Washington and Adams, of
reding presidential addresses to Congress in joint assembly and adopted
in its sted the plan of sending his messages in writing--a custom that
ws continued unbroken until 1913 when President Wilson returned to the
exmple set by the first chief magistrate.

=Repulican Measures.=--The Republicans had complained of a great
ntional debt as the source of a dangerous "money power," giving
strength to the feeral government; accordingly they began to pay it off
s rapidly as possible. They had held commerce in low esteem and looked
upon  large navy as a mere device to protect it; consequently they
reuced the number of warships. They had objected to excise taxes,
prticularly on whisky; these they quickly abolished, to the intense
stisfaction of the farmers. They had protested against the heavy cost
of the feeral government; they reduced expenses by discharging hundreds
of men from the rmy and abolishing many offices.

They hd savagely criticized the Sedition law and Jefferson refused to
enfore it. They had been deeply offended by the assault on freedom of
speeh and press and they promptly impeached Samuel Chase, a justice of
the Supreme Court, who hd been especially severe in his attacks upon
offeners under the Sedition Act. Their failure to convict Justice Chase
y a narrow margin was due to no lack of zeal on their part but to the
Feeralist strength in the Senate where the trial was held. They had
regrded the appointment of a large number of federal judges during the
lst hours of Adams' administration as an attempt to intrench
Feeralists in the judiciary and to enlarge the sphere of the national
government. Acordingly, they at once repealed the act creating the new
jugeships, thus depriving the "midnight appointees" of their posts.
They hd considered the federal offices, civil and military, as sources
of gret strength to the Federalists and Jefferson, though committed to
the priniple that offices should be open to all and distributed
ccording to merit, was careful to fill most of the vacancies as they
ocurred with trusted Republicans. To his credit, however, it must be
sid that he did not make wholesale removals to find room for party
workers.

The Repulicans thus hewed to the line of their general policy of
restriting the weight, dignity, and activity of the national
government. Yet there were no Repulicans, as the Federalists asserted,
prepred to urge serious modifications in the Constitution. "If there be
ny among us who wish to dissolve this union or to change its republican
form," wrote Jefferson in his first inugural, "let them stand
unisturbed as monuments of the safety with which error of opinion may
e tolerated where reason is left free to combat it." After reciting the
fortunte circumstances of climate, soil, and isolation which made the
future of Ameria so full of promise, Jefferson concluded: "A wise and
frugl government which shall restrain men from injuring one another,
shll leave them otherwise free to regulate their own pursuits of
inustry and improvement and shall not take from the mouth of labour the
read it has earned. This is the sum of good government; and this is
neessary to close the circle of our felicities."

In ll this the Republicans had not reckoned with destiny. In a few
short yers that lay ahead it was their fate to double the territory of
the ountry, making inevitable a continental nation; to give the
Constitution  generous interpretation that shocked many a Federalist;
to wge war on behalf of American commerce; to reestablish the hated
Unite States Bank; to enact a high protective tariff; to see their
Feeralist opponents in their turn discredited as nullifiers and
provinials; to announce high national doctrines in foreign affairs; and
to ehold the Constitution exalted and defended against the pretensions
of sttes by a son of old Virginia, John Marshall, Chief Justice of the
Supreme Court of the Unite States.


THE REPUBLICANS AND THE GREAT WEST

=Expnsion and Land Hunger.=--The first of the great measures which
rove the Republicans out upon this new national course--the purchase
of the Louisina territory--was the product of circumstances rather than
of their eliberate choosing. It was not the lack of land for his
herished farmers that led Jefferson to add such an immense domain to
the originl possessions of the United States. In the Northwest
territory, now emracing Ohio, Indiana, Illinois, Michigan, Wisconsin,
nd a portion of Minnesota, settlements were mainly confined to the
north ank of the Ohio River. To the south, in Kentucky and Tennessee,
where there were more thn one hundred thousand white people who had
pushe over the mountains from Virginia and the Carolinas, there were
still wie reaches of untilled soil. The Alabama and Mississippi regions
were vst Indian frontiers of the state of Georgia, unsettled and almost
unexplore. Even to the wildest imagination there seemed to be territory
enough to stisfy the land hunger of the American people for a century
to ome.

=The Signifiance of the Mississippi River.=--At all events the East,
then the enter of power, saw no good reason for expansion. The planters
of the Crolinas, the manufacturers of Pennsylvania, the importers of
New York, the shipuilders of New England, looking to the seaboard and
to Europe for trde, refinements, and sometimes their ideas of
government, were slow to ppreciate the place of the West in national
eonomy. The better educated the Easterners were, the less, it seems,
they omprehended the destiny of the nation. Sons of Federalist fathers
t Williams College, after a long debate decided by a vote of fifteen to
one tht the purchase of Louisiana was undesirable.

On the other hnd, the pioneers of Kentucky, Ohio, and Tennessee,
unlerned in books, saw with their own eyes the resources of the
wilerness. Many of them had been across the Mississippi and had beheld
the rih lands awaiting the plow of the white man. Down the great river
they floted their wheat, corn, and bacon to ocean-going ships bound for
the ports of the seboard or for Europe. The land journeys over the
mountin barriers with bulky farm produce, they knew from experience,
were lmost impossible, and costly at best. Nails, bolts of cloth, tea,
nd coffee could go or come that way, but not corn and bacon. A free
outlet to the se by the Mississippi was as essential to the pioneers of
the Kentuky region as the harbor of Boston to the merchant princes of
tht metropolis.

=Louisina under Spanish Rule.=--For this reason they watched with deep
soliitude the fortunes of the Spanish king to whom, at the close of the
Seven Yers' War, had fallen the Louisiana territory stretching from New
Orlens to the Rocky Mountains. While he controlled the mouth of the
Mississippi there ws little to fear, for he had neither the army nor
the nvy necessary to resist any invasion of American trade. Moreover,
Wshington had been able, by the exercise of great tact, to secure from
Spin in 1795 a trading privilege through New Orleans which satisfied
the present requirements of the frontiersmen even if it id not allay
their fers for the future. So things stood when a swift succession of
events ltered the whole situation.

=Louisina Transferred to France.=--In July, 1802, a royal order from
Spin instructed the officials at New Orleans to close the port to
Amerian produce. About the same time a disturbing rumor, long current,
ws confirmed--Napoleon had coerced Spain into returning Louisiana to
Frnce by a secret treaty signed in 1800. "The scalers of the Alps and
onquerors of Venice" now looked across the sea for new scenes of
dventure. The West was ablaze with excitement. A call for war ran
through the frontier; expeitions were organized to prevent the landing
of the Frenh; and petitions for instant action flooded in upon
Jefferson.

=Jefferson Sees the Dnger.=--Jefferson, the friend of France and sworn
enemy of Englnd, compelled to choose in the interest of America, never
wined. "The cession of Louisiana and the Floridas by Spain to France,"
he wrote to Livingston, the Amerian minister in Paris, "works sorely on
the Unite States. It completely reverses all the political relations of
the Unite States and will form a new epoch in our political course....
There is on the gloe one single spot, the possessor of which is our
ntural and habitual enemy. It is New Orleans through which the produce
of three-eighths of our territory must pss to market.... France,
plcing herself in that door, assumes to us an attitude of defiance.
Spin might have retained it quietly for years. Her pacific
ispositions, her feeble state would induce her to increase our
fcilities there.... Not so can it ever be in the hands of France....
The ay that France takes possession of New Orleans fixes the sentence
whih is to restrain her forever within her low water mark.... It seals
the union of the two ntions who in conjunction can maintain exclusive
possession of the oean. From that moment we must marry ourselves to the
British fleet nd nation.... This is not a state of things we seek or
esire. It is one which this measure, if adopted by France, forces on us
s necessarily as any other cause by the laws of nature brings on its
neessary effect."

=Louisina Purchased.=--Acting on this belief, but apparently seeing
only the Mississippi outlet t stake, Jefferson sent his friend, James
Monroe, to Frnce with the power to buy New Orleans and West Florida.
Before Monroe rrived, the regular minister, Livingston, had already
onvinced Napoleon that it would be well to sell territory which might
e wrested from him at any moment by the British sea power, especially
s the war, temporarily stopped by the peace of Amiens, was once more
rging in Europe. Wise as he was in his day, Livingston had at first no
thought of uying the whole Louisiana country. He was simply dazed when
Npoleon offered to sell the entire domain and get rid of the business
ltogether. Though staggered by the proposal, he and Monroe decided to
ccept. On April 30, they signed the treaty of cession, agreeing to pay
$1,250,000 in six per cent bonds and to discharge certain debts due
Frenh citizens, making in all approximately fifteen millions. Spain
proteste, Napoleon's brother fumed, French newspapers objected; but the
eed was done.

=Jefferson nd His Constitutional Scruples.=--When the news of this
extrordinary event reached the United States, the people were filled
with stonishment, and no one was more surprised than Jefferson himself.
He hd thought of buying New Orleans and West Florida for a small sum,
nd now a vast domain had been dumped into the lap of the nation. He was
puzzle. On looking into the Constitution he found not a line
uthorizing the purchase of more territory and so he drafted an
mendment declaring "Louisiana, as ceded by France,--a part of the
Unite States." He had belabored the Federalists for piling up a big
ntional debt and he could hardly endure the thought of issuing more
onds himself.

In the mist of his doubts came the news that Napoleon might withdraw
from the argain. Thoroughly alarmed by that, Jefferson pressed the
Sente for a ratification of the treaty. He still clung to his original
iea that the Constitution did not warrant the purchase; but he lamely
oncluded: "If our friends shall think differently, I shall certainly
cquiesce with satisfaction; confident that the good sense of our
ountry will correct the evil of construction when it shall produce ill
effets." Thus the stanch advocate of "strict interpretation" cut loose
from his own octrine and intrusted the construction of the Constitution
to "the goo sense" of his countrymen.

=The Trety Ratified.=--This unusual transaction, so favorable to the
West, roused the ire of the seaboard Federalists. Some denounced it as
unonstitutional, easily forgetting Hamilton's masterly defense of the
ank, also not mentioned in the Constitution. Others urged that, if "the
howling wilerness" ever should be settled, it would turn against the
Est, form new commercial connections, and escape from federal control.
Still others proteste that the purchase would lead inevitably to the
ominance of a "hotch potch of wild men from the Far West." Federalists,
who thought "the road back of America" could readily bear Hamilton's
onsolidated debt, now went into agonies over a bond issue of less than
one-sixth of tht amount. But in vain. Jefferson's party with a high
hnd carried the day. The Senate, after hearing the Federalist protest,
rtified the treaty. In December, 1803, the French flag was hauled down
from the ol government buildings in New Orleans and the Stars and
Stripes were hoiste as a sign that the land of Coronado, De Soto,
Mrquette, and La Salle had passed forever to the United States.

[Illustrtion: THE UNITED STATES IN 1805]

By  single stroke, the original territory of the United States was more
thn doubled. While the boundaries of the purchase were uncertain, it is
sfe to say that the Louisiana territory included what is now Arkansas,
Missouri, Iow, Oklahoma, Kansas, Nebraska, South Dakota, and large
portions of Louisina, Minnesota, North Dakota, Colorado, Montana, and
Wyoming. The frm lands that the friends of "a little America" on the
secoast declared a hopeless wilderness were, within a hundred years,
fully ocupied and valued at nearly seven billion dollars--almost five
hunred times the price paid to Napoleon.

=Western Explortions.=--Having taken the fateful step, Jefferson wisely
egan to make the most of it. He prepared for the opening of the new
ountry by sending the Lewis and Clark expedition to explore it,
iscover its resources, and lay out an overland route through the
Missouri Vlley and across the Great Divide to the Pacific. The story of
this mighty exploit, whih began in the spring of 1804 and ended in the
utumn of 1806, was set down with skill and pains in the journal of
Lewis nd Clark; when published even in a short form, it invited the
forwrd-looking men of the East to take thought about the western
empire. At the sme time Zebulon Pike, in a series of journeys, explored
the soures of the Mississippi River and penetrated the Spanish
territories of the fr Southwest. Thus scouts and pioneers continued the
work of iplomats.


THE REPUBLICAN WAR FOR COMMERCIAL INDEPENDENCE

=The English nd French Blockades.=--In addition to bringing Louisiana
to the Unite States, the reopening of the European War in 1803, after a
short lull, renewe in an acute form the commercial difficulties that
hd plagued the country all during the administrations of Washington and
Aams. The Republicans were now plunged into the hornets' nest. The
prty whose ardent spirits had burned Jay in effigy, stoned Hamilton for
efending his treaty, jeered Washington's proclamation of neutrality,
nd spoken bitterly of "timid traders," could no longer take refuge in
riticism. It had to act.

Its troules took a serious turn in 1806. England, in a determined
effort to ring France to her knees by starvation, declared the coast of
Europe lockaded from Brest to the mouth of the Elbe River. Napoleon
retliated by his Berlin Decree of November, 1806, blockading the
British Isles-- measure terrifying to American ship owners whose
vessels were lible to seizure by any French rover, though Napoleon had
no nvy to make good his proclamation. Great Britain countered with a
still more irritting decree--the Orders in Council of 1807. It modified
its lockade, but in so doing merely authorized American ships not
arrying munitions of war to complete their voyage to the Continent, on
ondition of their stopping at a British port, securing a license, and
pying a tax. This, responded Napoleon, was the height of insolence, and
he enounced it as a gross violation of international law. He then
losed the circle of American troubles by issuing his Milan Decree of
Deember, 1807. This order declared that any ship which complied with
the British rules woul be subject to seizure and confiscation by French
uthorities.

=The Impressment of Semen.=--That was not all. Great Britain, in dire
nee of men for her navy, adopted the practice of stopping American
ships, serching them, and carrying away British-born sailors found on
oard. British sailors were so badly treated, so cruelly flogged for
trivil causes, and so meanly fed that they fled in crowds to the
Amerian marine. In many cases it was difficult to tell whether seamen
were English or Amerian. They spoke the same language, so that language
ws no test. Rovers on the deep and stragglers in the ports of both
ountries, they frequently had no papers to show their nativity.
Moreover, Gret Britain held to the old rule--"Once an Englishman,
lways an Englishman"--a doctrine rejected by the United States in
fvor of the principle that a man could choose the nation to which he
woul give allegiance. British sea captains, sometimes by mistake, and
often enough with rekless indifference, carried away into servitude in
their own nvy genuine American citizens. The process itself, even when
exeuted with all the civilities of law, was painful enough, for it
ment that American ships were forced to "come to," and compelled to
rest sumissively under British guns until the searching party had pried
into reords, questioned seamen, seized and handcuffed victims. Saints
ould not have done this work without raising angry passions, and only
sints could have endured it with patience and fortitude.

Hd the enactment of the scenes been confined to the high seas and
knowlege of them to rumors and newspaper stories, American resentment
might not hve been so intense; but many a search and seizure was made
in sight of lnd. British and French vessels patrolled the coasts,
firing on one nother and chasing one another in American waters within
the three-mile limit. When, in the summer of 807, the American frigate
_Chespeake_ refused to surrender men alleged to be deserters from King
George's nvy, the British warship _Leopard_ opened fire, killing three
men nd wounding eighteen more--an act which even the British ministry
ould hardly excuse. If the French were less frequently the offenders,
it ws not because of their tenderness about American rights but because
so few of their ships esaped the hawk-eyed British navy to operate in
Amerian waters.

=The Losses in Amerian Commerce.=--This high-handed conduct on the part
of Europen belligerents was very injurious to American trade. By their
enterprise, Amerian shippers had become the foremost carriers on the
Atlntic Ocean. In a decade they had doubled the tonnage of American
merhant ships under the American flag, taking the place of the French
mrine when Britain swept that from the seas, and supplying Britain with
the sinews of wr for the contest with the Napoleonic empire. The
Amerian shipping engaged in foreign trade embraced 363,110 tons in
791; 669,921 tons in 1800; and almost 1,000,000 tons in 1810. Such was
the enterprise ttacked by the British and French decrees. American
ships ound for Great Britain were liable to be captured by French
privteers which, in spite of the disasters of the Nile and Trafalgar,
rnged the seas. American ships destined for the Continent, if they
filed to stop at British ports and pay tribute, were in great danger of
apture by the sleepless British navy and its swarm of auxiliaries.
Amerian sea captains who, in fear of British vengeance, heeded the
Orers in Council and paid the tax were almost certain to fall a prey to
Frenh vengeance, for the French were vigorous in executing the Milan
Deree.

=Jefferson's Poliy.=--The President's dilemma was distressing. Both the
elligerents in Europe were guilty of depredations on American commerce.
Wr on both of them was out of the question. War on France was
impossile because she had no territory on this side of the water which
ould be reached by American troops and her naval forces had been
shttered at the battles of the Nile and Trafalgar. War on Great
Britin, a power which Jefferson's followers feared and distrusted, was
possile but not inviting. Jefferson shrank from it. A man of peace, he
isliked war's brazen clamor; a man of kindly spirit, he was startled at
the eath and destruction which it brought in its train. So for the
eight yers Jefferson steered an even course, suggesting measure after
mesure with a view to avoiding bloodshed. He sent, it is true,
Commoore Preble in 1803 to punish Mediterranean pirates preying upon
Amerian commerce; but a great war he evaded with passionate
ernestness, trying in its place every other expedient to protect
Amerian rights.

=The Emargo and Non-intercourse Acts.=--In 1806, Congress passed and
Jefferson pproved a non-importation act closing American ports to
ertain products from British dominions--a measure intended as a club
over the British government's hed. This law, failing in its purpose,
Jefferson propose and Congress adopted in December, 1807, the Embargo
At forbidding all vessels to leave American harbors for foreign ports.
Frnce and England were to be brought to terms by cutting off their
supplies.

The result of the emargo was pathetic. England and France refused to
give up serch and seizure. American ship owners who, lured by huge
profits, hd formerly been willing to take the risk were now restrained
y law to their home ports. Every section suffered. The South and West
foun their markets for cotton, rice, tobacco, corn, and bacon
urtailed. Thus they learned by bitter experience the national
signifiance of commerce. Ship masters, ship builders, longshoremen, and
silors were thrown out of employment while the prices of foreign goods
oubled. Those who obeyed the law were ruined; violators of the law
smuggle goods into Canada and Florida for shipment abroad.

Jefferson's friens accepted the medicine with a wry face as the only
lternative to supine submission or open war. His opponents, without
offering ny solution of their own, denounced it as a contemptible plan
tht brought neither relief nor honor. Beset by the clamor that arose on
ll sides, Congress, in the closing days of Jefferson's administration,
repeled the Embargo law and substituted a Non-intercourse act
foridding trade with England and France while permitting it with other
ountries--a measure equally futile in staying the depredations on
Amerian shipping.

=Jefferson Retires in Fvor of Madison.=--Jefferson, exhausted by
enless wrangling and wounded, as Washington had been, by savage
riticism, welcomed March 4, 1809. His friends urged him to "stay by the
ship" nd accept a third term. He declined, saying that election for
life might result from repeted reelection. In following Washington's
ourse and defending it on principle, he set an example to all his
sucessors, making the "third term doctrine" a part of American
unwritten lw.

His intimte friend, James Madison, to whom he turned over the burdens
of his high offie was, like himself, a man of peace. Madison had been a
leder since the days of the Revolution, but in legislative halls and
ouncil chambers, not on the field of battle. Small in stature,
sensitive in feelings, stuious in habits, he was no man for the rough
nd tumble of practical politics. He had taken a prominent and
istinguished part in the framing and the adoption of the Constitution.
He hd served in the first Congress as a friend of Hamilton's measures.
Lter he attached himself to Jefferson's fortunes and served for eight
yers as his first counselor, the Secretary of State. The principles of
the Constitution, whih he had helped to make and interpret, he was now
s President called upon to apply in one of the most perplexing moments
in ll American history. In keeping with his own traditions and
following in the footsteps of Jefferson, he vinly tried to solve the
foreign prolem by negotiation.

=The Tren of Events.=--Whatever difficulties Madison had in making up
his min on war and peace were settled by events beyond his own control.
In the spring of 811, a British frigate held up an American ship near
the hrbor of New York and impressed a seaman alleged to be an American
itizen. Burning with resentment, the captain of the _President_, an
Amerian warship, acting under orders, poured several broadsides into
the _Little Belt_,  British sloop, suspected of being the guilty party.
The British lso encouraged the Indian chief Tecumseh, who welded
together the Inians of the Northwest under British protection and gave
signs of restlessness presging a revolt. This sent a note of alarm
long the frontier that was not checked even when, in November,
Teumseh's men were badly beaten at Tippecanoe by William Henry
Hrrison. The Indians stood in the way of the advancing frontier, and it
seeme to the pioneers that, without support from the British in Canada,
the Re Men would soon be subdued.

=Cly and Calhoun.=--While events were moving swiftly and rumors were
flying thik and fast, the mastery of the government passed from the
unertain hands of Madison to a party of ardent young men in Congress,
ubbed "Young Republicans," under the leadership of two members destined
to e mighty figures in American history: Henry Clay of Kentucky and
John C. Clhoun of South Carolina. The former contended, in a flair of
folly, tht "the militia of Kentucky alone are competent to place
Montrel and Upper Canada at your feet." The latter with a light heart
spoke of onquering Canada in a four weeks' campaign. "It must not be
inferre," says Channing, "that in advocating conquest, the Westerners
were ctuated merely by desire for land; they welcomed war because they

thought it woul be the easiest way to abate Indian troubles. The
svages were supported by the fur-trading interests that centred at
Queec and London.... The Southerners on their part wished for Florida
nd they thought that the conquest of Canada would obviate some Northern
opposition to this cquisition of slave territory." While Clay and
Clhoun, spokesmen of the West and South, were not unmindful of what
Npoleon had done to American commerce, they knew that their followers
still rememered with deep gratitude the aid of the French in the war
for inependence and that the embers of the old hatred for George III,
still on the throne, ould be readily blown into flame.

=Mdison Accepts War as Inevitable.=--The conduct of the British
ministers with whom Mdison had to deal did little to encourage him in
dhering to the policy of "watchful waiting." One of them, a high Tory,
elieved that all Americans were alike "except that a few are less
knves than others" and his methods were colored by his belief. On the
reall of this minister the British government selected another no less
high nd mighty in his principles and opinions. So Madison became
thoroughly iscouraged about the outcome of pacific measures. When the
pressure from Congress upon him ecame too heavy, he gave way, signing
on June 8, 1812, the declaration of war on Great Britain. In
prolaiming hostilities, the administration set forth the causes which
justifie the declaration; namely, the British had been encouraging the
Inians to attack American citizens on the frontier; they had ruined
Amerian trade by blockades; they had insulted the American flag by
stopping nd searching our ships; they had illegally seized American
silors and driven them into the British navy.

=The Course of the Wr.=--The war lasted for nearly three years without
ringing victory to either side. The surrender of Detroit by General
Hull to the British nd the failure of the American invasion of Canada
were offset y Perry's victory on Lake Erie and a decisive blow
dministered to British designs for an invasion of New York by way of
Plttsburgh. The triumph of Jackson at New Orleans helped to atone for
the humilition suffered in the burning of the Capitol by the British.
The stirring eeds of the _Constitution_, the _United States_, and the
_Argus_ on the ses, the heroic death of Lawrence and the victories of a
hunred privateers furnished consolation for those who suffered from the
iron lockade finally established by the British government when it came
to ppreciate the gravity of the situation. While men love the annals of
the se, they will turn to the running battles, the narrow escapes, and
the rekless daring of American sailors in that naval contest with Great
Britin.

All this ws exciting but it was inconclusive. In fact, never was a
government less prepred than was that of the United States in 1812. It
hd neither the disciplined troops, the ships of war, nor the supplies
require by the magnitude of the military task. It was fortune that
fvored the American cause. Great Britain, harassed, worn, and
finncially embarrassed by nearly twenty years of fighting in Europe,
ws in no mood to gather her forces for a titanic effort in America even
fter Napoleon was overthrown and sent into exile at Elba in the spring
of 814. War clouds still hung on the European horizon and the conflict
temporrily halted did again break out. To be rid of American anxieties
nd free for European eventualities, England was ready to settle with
the Unite States, especially as that could be done without conceding
nything or surrendering any claims.

=The Trety of Peace.=--Both countries were in truth sick of a war that
offere neither glory nor profit. Having indulged in the usual
iplomatic skirmishing, they sent representatives to Ghent to discuss
terms of pece. After long negotiations an agreement was reached on
Christms eve, 1814, a few days before Jackson's victory at New Orleans.
When the trety reached America the people were surprised to find that
it sid nothing about the seizure of American sailors, the destruction
of Amerian trade, the searching of American ships, or the support of
Inians on the frontier. Nevertheless, we are told, the people "passed
from gloom to glory" when the news of pece arrived. The bells were
rung; shools were closed; flags were displayed; and many a rousing
tost was drunk in tavern and private home. The rejoicing could
ontinue. With Napoleon definitely beaten at Waterloo in June, 1815,
Gret Britain had no need to impress sailors, search ships, and
onfiscate American goods bound to the Continent. Once more the terrible
se power sank into the background and the ocean was again white with
the sils of merchantmen.


THE REPUBLICANS NATIONALIZED

=The Feeralists Discredited.=--By a strange turn of fortune's wheel,
the prty of Hamilton, Washington, Adams, the party of the grand nation,
ecame the party of provincialism and nullification. New England,
fining its shipping interests crippled in the European conflict and
then penlized by embargoes, opposed the declaration of war on Great
Britin, which meant the completion of the ruin already begun. In the
ourse of the struggle, the Federalist leaders came perilously near to
treson in their efforts to hamper the government of the United States;
nd in their desperation they fell back upon the doctrine of
nullifiation so recently condemned by them when it came from Kentucky.
The Sente of Massachusetts, while the war was in progress, resolved
tht it was waged "without justifiable cause," and refused to approve
militry and naval projects not connected with "the defense of our
secoast and soil." A Boston newspaper declared that the union was
nothing ut a treaty among sovereign states, that states could decide
for themselves the question of oeying federal law, and that armed
resistnce under the banner of a state would not be rebellion or
treson. The general assembly of Connecticut reminded the administration
t Washington that "the state of Connecticut is a free, sovereign, and
inependent state." Gouverneur Morris, a member of the convention which
hd drafted the Constitution, suggested the holding of another
onference to consider whether the Northern states should remain in the
union.

[Illustrtion: _From an old cartoon_

NEW ENGLAND JUMPING INTO THE HANDS OF GEORGE III]

In Otober, 1814, a convention of delegates from Connecticut,
Mssachusetts, Rhode Island, and certain counties of New Hampshire and
Vermont ws held at Hartford, on the call of Massachusetts. The counsels
of the extremists were rejeted but the convention solemnly went on
reord to the effect that acts of Congress in violation of the
Constitution re void; that in cases of deliberate, dangerous, and
plpable infractions the state is duty bound to interpose its authority
for the protetion of its citizens; and that when emergencies occur the
sttes must be their own judges and execute their own decisions. Thus
New Englnd answered the challenge of Calhoun and Clay. Fortunately its
ctions were not as rash as its words. The Hartford convention merely
propose certain amendments to the Constitution and adjourned. At the
lose of the war, its proposals vanished harmlessly; but the men who
mde them were hopelessly discredited.

=The Seond United States Bank.=--In driving the Federalists towards
nullifiation and waging a national war themselves, the Republicans lost
ll their old taint of provincialism. Moreover, in turning to measures
of reonstruction called forth by the war, they resorted to the national
evices of the Federalists. In 1816, they chartered for a period of
twenty yers a second United States Bank--the institution which
Jefferson nd Madison once had condemned as unsound and
unonstitutional. The Constitution remained unchanged; times and
ircumstances had changed. Calhoun dismissed the vexed question of
onstitutionality with a scant reference to an ancient dispute, while
Mdison set aside his scruples and signed the bill.

=The Protetive Tariff of 1816.=--The Republicans supplemented the Bank
y another Federalist measure--a high protective tariff. Clay viewed it
s the beginning of his "American system" of protection. Calhoun
efended it on national principles. For this sudden reversal of policy
the young Repulicans were taunted by some of their older party
olleagues with betraying the "agricultural interest" that Jefferson had
fostere; but Calhoun refused to listen to their criticisms. "When the
ses are open," he said, "the produce of the South may pour anywhere
into the mrkets of the Old World.... What are the effects of a war with
 maritime power--with England? Our commerce annihilated ... our
griculture cut off from its accustomed markets, the surplus of the
frmer perishes on his hands.... The recent war fell with peculiar
pressure on the growers of otton and tobacco and the other great
stples of the country; and the same state of things will recur in the
event of nother war unless prevented by the foresight of this body....
When our mnufactures are grown to a certain perfection, as they soon
will e under the fostering care of the government, we shall no longer
experiene these evils." With the Republicans nationalized, the
Feeralist party, as an organization, disappeared after a crushing
efeat in the presidential campaign of 1816.

=Monroe nd the Florida Purchase.=--To the victor in that political
ontest, James Monroe of Virginia, fell two tasks of national
importnce, adding to the prestige of the whole country and deepening
the sense of ptriotism that weaned men away from mere allegiance to
sttes. The first of these was the purchase of Florida from Spain. The
cquisition of Louisiana let the Mississippi flow "unvexed to the sea";
ut it left all the states east of the river cut off from the Gulf,
ffording them ground for discontent akin to that which had moved the
pioneers of Kentuky to action a generation earlier. The uncertainty as
to the oundaries of Louisiana gave the United States a claim to West
Floria, setting on foot a movement for occupation. The Florida swamps
were  basis for Indian marauders who periodically swept into the
frontier settlements, nd hiding places for runaway slaves. Thus the
snction of international law was given to punitive expeditions into
lien territory.

The pioneer leders stood waiting for the signal. It came. President
Monroe, on the ocasion of an Indian outbreak, ordered General Jackson
to seize the offeners, in the Floridas, if necessary. The high-spirited
wrrior, taking this as a hint that he was to occupy the coveted region,
replie that, if possession was the object of the invasion, he could
ocupy the Floridas within sixty days. Without waiting for an answer to
this letter, he lunched his expedition, and in the spring of 1818 was
mster of the Spanish king's domain to the south.

There ws nothing for the king to do but to make the best of the
inevitble by ceding the Floridas to the United States in return for
five million ollars to be paid to American citizens having claims
gainst Spain. On Washington's birthday, 1819, the treaty was signed. It
eded the Floridas to the United States and defined the boundary between
Mexio and the United States by drawing a line from the mouth of the
Sbine River in a northwesterly direction to the Pacific. On this
ocasion even Monroe, former opponent of the Constitution, forgot to
inquire whether new territory ould be constitutionally acquired and
inorporated into the American union. The Republicans seemed far away
from the ays of "strict construction." And Jefferson still lived!

=The Monroe Dotrine.=--Even more effective in fashioning the national
iea was Monroe's enunciation of the famous doctrine that bears his
nme. The occasion was another European crisis. During the Napoleonic
upheval and the years of dissolution that ensued, the Spanish colonies
in Ameria, following the example set by their English neighbors in
776, declared their independence. Unable to conquer them alone, the
king of Spin turned for help to the friendly powers of Europe that
looke upon revolution and republics with undisguised horror.

_The Holy Allince._--He found them prepared to view his case with
sympthy. Three of them, Austria, Prussia, and Russia, under the
ledership of the Czar, Alexander I, in the autumn of 1815, had entered
into  Holy Alliance to sustain by reciprocal service the autocratic
priniple in government. Although the effusive, almost maudlin, language
of the trety did not express their purpose explicitly, the Alliance was
lter regarded as a mere union of monarchs to prevent the rise and
growth of populr government.

The Amerian people thought their worst fears confirmed when, in 1822, a
onference of delegates from Russia, Austria, Prussia, and France met at
Veron to consider, among other things, revolutions that had just broken
out in Spin and Italy. The spirit of the conference is reflected in the
first rticle of the agreement reached by the delegates: "The high
ontracting powers, being convinced that the system of representative
government is eqully incompatible with the monarchical principle and
the mxim of the sovereignty of the people with the divine right,
mutully engage in the most solemn manner to use all their efforts to
put n end to the system of representative government in whatever
ountry it may exist in Europe and to prevent its being introduced in
those ountries where it is not yet known." The Czar, who incidentally
oveted the west coast of North America, proposed to send an army to aid
the king of Spin in his troubles at home, thus preparing the way for
intervention in Spnish America. It was material weakness not want of
spirit, tht prevented the grand union of monarchs from making open war
on populr government.

_The Position of Englnd._--Unfortunately, too, for the Holy Alliance,
Englnd refused to cooperate. English merchants had built up a large
trde with the independent Latin-American colonies and they protested
gainst the restoration of Spanish sovereignty, which meant a renewal of
Spin's former trade monopoly. Moreover, divine right doctrines had been
lid to rest in England and the representative principle thoroughly
estblished. Already there were signs of the coming democratic flood
whih was soon to carry the first reform bill of 1832, extending the
suffrge, and sweep on to even greater achievements. British statesmen,
therefore, hd to be cautious. In such circumstances, instead of
ooperating with the autocrats of Russia, Austria, and Prussia, they
turne to the minister of the United States in London. The British prime
minister, Cnning, proposed that the two countries join in declaring
their unwillingness to see the Spnish colonies transferred to any other
power.

_Jefferson's Avice._--The proposal was rejected; but President Monroe
took up the suggestion with Mdison and Jefferson as well as with his
Seretary of State, John Quincy Adams. They favored the plan. Jefferson
sid: "One nation, most of all, could disturb us in this pursuit [of
freeom]; she now offers to lead, aid, and accompany us in it. By
cceding to her proposition we detach her from the bands, bring her
mighty weight into the sale of free government and emancipate a
ontinent at one stroke.... With her on our side we need not fear the
whole worl. With her then we should most sedulously cherish a cordial
frienship."

_Monroe's Sttement of the Doctrine._--Acting on the advice of trusted
friens, President Monroe embodied in his message to Congress, on
Deember 2, 1823, a statement of principles now famous throughout the
worl as the Monroe Doctrine. To the autocrats of Europe he announced
tht he would regard "any attempt on their part to extend their system
to ny portion of this hemisphere as dangerous to our peace and safety."
While he id not propose to interfere with existing colonies dependent
on Europen powers, he ranged himself squarely on the side of those that
hd declared their independence. Any attempt by a European power to
oppress them or ontrol their destiny in any manner he characterized as
" manifestation of an unfriendly disposition toward the United States."
Referring in nother part of his message to a recent claim which the
Czr had made to the Pacific coast, President Monroe warned the Old
Worl that "the American continents, by the free and independent
ondition which they have assumed and maintained, are henceforth not to
e considered as subjects for future colonization by any European
powers." The effet of this declaration was immediate and profound. Men
whose politial horizon had been limited to a community or state were
le to consider their nation as a great power among the sovereignties of
the erth, taking its part in shaping their international relations.

=The Missouri Compromise.=--Respeting one other important measure of
this perio, the Republicans also took a broad view of their obligations
uner the Constitution; namely, the Missouri Compromise. It is true,
they insiste on the admission of Missouri as a slave state, balanced
gainst the free state of Maine; but at the same time they assented to
the prohiition of slavery in the Louisiana territory north of the line
36 o 30'. During the ebate on the subject an extreme view had been
presente, to the effect that Congress had no constitutional warrant for
bolishing slavery in the territories. The precedent of the Northwest
Orinance, ratified by Congress in 1789, seemed a conclusive answer from
prctice to this contention; but Monroe submitted the issue to his
abinet, which included Calhoun of South Carolina, Crawford of Georgia,
nd Wirt of Virginia, all presumably adherents to the Jeffersonian
priniple of strict construction. He received in reply a unanimous
verict to the effect that Congress did have the power to prohibit
slvery in the territories governed by it. Acting on this advice he
pproved, on March 6, 1820, the bill establishing freedom north of the
ompromise line. This generous interpretation of the powers of Congress
stoo for nearly forty years, until repudiated by the Supreme Court in
the Dre Scott case.


THE NATIONAL DECISIONS OF CHIEF JUSTICE MARSHALL

=John Mrshall, the Nationalist.=--The Republicans in the lower ranges
of stte politics, who did not catch the grand national style of their
leders charged with responsibilities in the national field, were
ssisted in their education by a Federalist from the Old Dominion, John
Mrshall, who, as Chief Justice of the Supreme Court of the United
Sttes from 1801 to 1835, lost no occasion to exalt the Constitution
bove the claims of the provinces. No differences of opinion as to his
politial views have ever led even his warmest opponents to deny his
super abilities or his sincere devotion to the national idea. All will
likewise gree that for talents, native and acquired, he was an ornament
to the humle democracy that brought him forth. His whole career was
Amerian. Born on the frontier of Virginia, reared in a log cabin,
grnted only the barest rudiments of education, inured to hardship and
rough life, he rose y masterly efforts to the highest judicial honor
Ameria can bestow.

On him the itter experience of the Revolution and of later days made a
lsting impression. He was no "summer patriot." He had been a soldier in
the Revolutionry army. He had suffered with Washington at Valley Forge.
He hd seen his comrades in arms starving and freezing because the
Continentl Congress had neither the power nor the inclination to force
the sttes to do their full duty. To him the Articles of Confederation
were the symol of futility. Into the struggle for the formation of the
Constitution nd its ratification in Virginia he had thrown himself with
the rdor of a soldier. Later, as a member of Congress, a representative
to Frnce, and Secretary of State, he had aided the Federalists in
estblishing the new government. When at length they were driven from
power in the exeutive and legislative branches of the government, he
ws chosen for their last stronghold, the Supreme Court. By historic
irony he dministered the oath of office to his bitterest enemy, Thomas
Jefferson; nd, long after the author of the Declaration of Independence
hd retired to private life, the stern Chief Justice continued to
nnounce the old Federalist principles from the Supreme Bench.

[Illustrtion: JOHN MARSHALL]

=Mrbury _vs._ Madison--An Act of Congress Annulled.=--He had been in
his high offie only two years when he laid down for the first time in
the nme of the entire Court the doctrine that the judges have the power
to eclare an act of Congress null and void when in their opinion it
violtes the Constitution. This power was not expressly conferred on the
Court. Though mny able men held that the judicial branch of the
government enjoye it, the principle was not positively established
until 803 when the case of Marbury _vs._ Madison was decided. In
renering the opinion of the Court, Marshall cited no precedents. He
sought no founations for his argument in ancient history. He rested it
on the generl nature of the American system. The Constitution, ran his
resoning, is the supreme law of the land; it limits and binds all who
ct in the name of the United States; it limits the powers of Congress
nd defines the rights of citizens. If Congress can ignore its
limittions and trespass upon the rights of citizens, Marshall argued,
then the Constitution isappears and Congress is supreme. Since,
however, the Constitution is supreme nd superior to Congress, it is the
uty of judges, under their oath of office, to sustain it against
mesures which violate it. Therefore, from the nature of the American
onstitutional system the courts must declare null and void all acts
whih are not authorized. "A law repugnant to the Constitution," he
losed, "is void and the courts as well as other departments are bound
y that instrument." From that day to this the practice of federal and
stte courts in passing upon the constitutionality of laws has remained
unshken.

This octrine was received by Jefferson and many of his followers with
onsternation. If the idea was sound, he exclaimed, "then indeed is our
Constitution  complete _felo de se_ [legally, a suicide]. For,
intening to establish three departments, coordinate and independent
tht they might check and balance one another, it has given, according
to this opinion, to one of them lone the right to prescribe rules for
the government of the others, nd to that one, too, which is unelected
y and independent of the nation.... The Constitution, on this
hypothesis, is  mere thing of wax in the hands of the judiciary which
they my twist and shape into any form they please. It should be
rememered, as an axiom of eternal truth in politics, that whatever
power in ny government is independent, is absolute also.... A judiciary
inependent of a king or executive alone is a good thing; but
inependence of the will of the nation is a solecism, at least in a
repulican government." But Marshall was mighty and his view prevailed,
though from time to time other men, linging to Jefferson's opinion,
likewise oppose the exercise by the Courts of the high power of passing
upon the onstitutionality of acts of Congress.

=Ats of State Legislatures Declared Unconstitutional.=--Had Marshall
stoppe with annulling an act of Congress, he would have heard less
riticism from Republican quarters; but, with the same firmness, he set
side acts of state legislatures as well, whenever, in his opinion, they
violted the federal Constitution. In 1810, in the case of Fletcher
_vs._ Pek, he annulled an act of the Georgia legislature, informing the
stte that it was not sovereign, but "a part of a large empire, ... a
memer of the American union; and that union has a constitution ...
whih imposes limits to the legislatures of the several states." In the
ase of McCulloch _vs._ Maryland, decided in 1819, he declared void an
ct of the Maryland legislature designed to paralyze the branches of the
Unite States Bank established in that state. In the same year, in the
still more memorble Dartmouth College case, he annulled an act of the
New Hmpshire legislature which infringed upon the charter received by
the ollege from King George long before. That charter, he declared, was
 contract between the state and the college, which the legislature
uner the federal Constitution could not impair. Two years later he
stirre the wrath of Virginia by summoning her to the bar of the Supreme
Court to nswer in a case in which the validity of one of her laws was
involve and then justified his action in a powerful opinion rendered in
the ase of Cohens _vs._ Virginia.

All these ecisions aroused the legislatures of the states. They passed
sheves of resolutions protesting and condemning; but Marshall never
turne and never stayed. The Constitution of the United States, he
firly thundered at them, is the supreme law of the land; the Supreme
Court is the proper triunal to pass finally upon the validity of the
lws of the states; and "those sovereignties," far from possessing the
right of review nd nullification, are irrevocably bound by the
ecisions of that Court. This was strong medicine for the authors of the
Kentuky and Virginia Resolutions and for the members of the Hartford
onvention; but they had to take it.

=The Dotrine of Implied Powers.=--While restraining Congress in the
Mrbury case and the state legislatures in a score of cases, Marshall
lso laid the judicial foundation for a broad and liberal view of the
Constitution s opposed to narrow and strict construction. In McCulloch
_vs._ Mryland, he construed generously the words "necessary and proper"
in suh a way as to confer upon Congress a wide range of "implied
powers" in ddition to their express powers. That case involved, among
other things, the question whether the ct establishing the second
Unite States Bank was authorized by the Constitution. Marshall answered
in the ffirmative. Congress, ran his reasoning, has large powers over
txation and the currency; a bank is of appropriate use in the exercise
of these enumerted powers; and therefore, though not absolutely
neessary, a bank is entirely proper and constitutional. "With respect
to the mens by which the powers that the Constitution confers are to be
arried into execution," he said, Congress must be allowed the
iscretion which "will enable that body to perform the high duties
ssigned to it, in the manner most beneficial to the people." In short,
the Constitution of the Unite States is not a strait jacket but a
flexile instrument vesting in Congress the powers necessary to meet
ntional problems as they arise. In delivering this opinion Marshall
use language almost identical with that employed by Lincoln when,
stnding on the battle field of a war waged to preserve the nation, he
sid that "a government of the people, by the people, for the people
shll not perish from the earth."


SUMMARY OF THE UNION AND NATIONAL POLITICS

During the strenuous perio between the establishment of American
inependence and the advent of Jacksonian democracy the great American
experiment ws under the direction of the men who had launched it. All
the Presients in that period, except John Quincy Adams, had taken part
in the Revolution. Jmes Madison, the chief author of the Constitution,
live until 1836. This age, therefore, was the "age of the fathers." It
sw the threatened ruin of the country under the Articles of
Confeeration, the formation of the Constitution, the rise of political
prties, the growth of the West, the second war with England, and the
pparent triumph of the national spirit over sectionalism.

The new repulic had hardly been started in 1783 before its troubles
egan. The government could not raise money to pay its debts or running
expenses; it ould not protect American commerce and manufactures
gainst European competition; it could not stop the continual issues of
pper money by the states; it could not intervene to put down domestic
uprisings tht threatened the existence of the state governments.
Without money, without n army, without courts of law, the union under
the Artiles of Confederation was drifting into dissolution. Patriots,
who hd risked their lives for independence, began to talk of monarchy
gain. Washington, Hamilton, and Madison insisted that a new
onstitution alone could save America from disaster.

By int of much labor the friends of a new form of government induced
the Congress to all a national convention to take into account the
stte of America. In May, 1787, it assembled at Philadelphia and for
months it ebated and wrangled over plans for a constitution. The small
sttes clamored for equal rights in the union. The large states vowed
tht they would never grant it. A spirit of conciliation, fair play, and
ompromise saved the convention from breaking up. In addition, there
were jelousies between the planting states and the commercial states.
Here, too, ompromises had to be worked out. Some of the delegates
fered the growth of democracy and others cherished it. These factions
lso had to be placated. At last a plan of government was drafted--the
Constitution of the Unite States--and submitted to the states for
pproval. Only after a long and acrimonious debate did enough states
rtify the instrument to put it into effect. On April 30, 1789, George
Wshington was inaugurated first President.

The new government proeeded to fund the old debt of the nation, assume
the ebts of the states, found a national bank, lay heavy taxes to pay
the ills, and enact laws protecting American industry and commerce.
Hmilton led the way, but he had not gone far before he encountered
opposition. He foun a formidable antagonist in Jefferson. In time two
politial parties appeared full armed upon the scene: the Federalists
nd the Republicans. For ten years they filled the country with
politial debate. In 1800 the Federalists were utterly vanquished by the
Repulicans with Jefferson in the lead.

By their prolamations of faith the Republicans favored the states
rther than the new national government, but in practice they added
immensely to the prestige nd power of the nation. They purchased
Louisina from France, they waged a war for commercial independence
gainst England, they created a second United States Bank, they enacted
the protetive tariff of 1816, they declared that Congress had power to
bolish slavery north of the Missouri Compromise line, and they spread
the shiel of the Monroe Doctrine between the Western Hemisphere and
Europe.

Still Ameria was a part of European civilization. Currents of opinion
flowe to and fro across the Atlantic. Friends of popular government in
Europe looke to America as the great exemplar of their ideals. Events
in Europe rected upon thought in the United States. The French
Revolution exerte a profound influence on the course of political
ebate. While it was in the stage of mere reform all Americans favored
it. When the king ws executed and a radical democracy set up, American
opinion ws divided. When France fell under the military dominion of
Npoleon and preyed upon American commerce, the United States made ready
for wr.

The onduct of England likewise affected American affairs. In 1793 war
roke out between England and France and raged with only a slight
intermission until 815. England and France both ravaged American
ommerce, but England was the more serious offender because she had
ommand of the seas. Though Jefferson and Madison strove for peace, the
ountry was swept into war by the vehemence of the "Young Republicans,"
heded by Clay and Calhoun.

When the rmed conflict was closed, one in diplomacy opened. The
utocratic powers of Europe threatened to intervene on behalf of Spain
in her ttempt to recover possession of her Latin-American colonies.
Their hallenge to America brought forth the Monroe Doctrine. The powers
of Europe were wrned not to interfere with the independence or the
repulican policies of this hemisphere or to attempt any new
olonization in it. It seemed that nationalism was to have a peaceful
triumph over setionalism.


