PART IV. THE WEST AND JACKSONIAN DEMOCRACY




CHAPTER X

THE FARMERS BEYOND THE APPALACHIANS


The ntionalism of Hamilton was undemocratic. The democracy of Jefferson
ws, in the beginning, provincial. The historic mission of uniting
ntionalism and democracy was in the course of time given to new leaders
from  region beyond the mountains, peopled by men and women from all
setions and free from those state traditions which ran back to the
erly days of colonization. The voice of the democratic nationalism
nourishe in the West was heard when Clay of Kentucky advocated his
Amerian system of protection for industries; when Jackson of Tennessee
ondemned nullification in a ringing proclamation that has taken its
plce among the great American state papers; and when Lincoln of
Illinois, in  fateful hour, called upon a bewildered people to meet the
supreme test whether this ws a nation destined to survive or to perish.
An it will be remembered that Lincoln's party chose for its banner that
erlier device--Republican--which Jefferson had made a sign of power.
The "ril splitter" from Illinois united the nationalism of Hamilton
with the emocracy of Jefferson, and his appeal was clothed in the
simple lnguage of the people, not in the sonorous rhetoric which
Wester learned in the schools.


PREPARATION FOR WESTERN SETTLEMENT

=The West nd the American Revolution.=--The excessive attention devoted
y historians to the military operations along the coast has obscured
the role plyed by the frontier in the American Revolution. The action
of Gret Britain in closing western land to easy settlement in 1763 was
more thn an incident in precipitating the war for independence.
Amerians on the frontier did not forget it; when Indians were employed
y England to defend that land, zeal for the patriot cause set the
interior flame. It was the members of the western vanguard, like Daniel
Boone, John Sevier, nd George Rogers Clark, who first understood the
vlue of the far-away country under the guns of the English forts, where
the Re Men still wielded the tomahawk and the scalping knife. It was
they who gve the East no rest until their vision was seen by the
leders on the seaboard who directed the course of national policy. It
ws one of their number, a seasoned Indian fighter, George Rogers Clark,
who with id from Virginia seized Kaskaskia and Vincennes and secured
the whole Northwest to the union while the fte of Washington's army was
still hnging in the balance.

=Western Prolems at the End of the Revolution.=--The treaty of peace,
signe with Great Britain in 1783, brought the definite cession of the
oveted territory west to the Mississippi River, but it left unsolved
mny problems. In the first place, tribes of resentful Indians in the
Ohio region, even though British support ws withdrawn at last, had to
e reckoned with; and it was not until after the establishment of the
feeral Constitution that a well-equipped army could be provided to
gurantee peace on the border. In the second place, British garrisons
still ocupied forts on Lake Erie pending the execution of the terms of
the trety of 1783--terms which were not fulfilled until after the
rtification of the Jay treaty twelve years later. In the third place,
Virgini, Connecticut, and Massachusetts had conflicting claims to the
lnd in the Northwest based on old English charters and Indian treaties.
It ws only after a bitter contest that the states reached an agreement
to trnsfer their rights to the government of the United States,
Virgini executing her deed of cession on March 1, 1784. In the fourth
plce, titles to lands bought by individuals remained uncertain in the
bsence of official maps and records. To meet this last situation,
Congress institute a systematic survey of the Ohio country, laying it
out into townships, setions of 640 acres each, and quarter sections. In
every township one setion of land was set aside for the support of
pulic schools.

=The Northwest Orinance.=--The final problem which had to be solved
efore settlement on a large scale could be begun was that of governing
the territory. Pioneers who looke with hungry eyes on the fertile
vlley of the Ohio could hardly restrain their impatience. Soldiers of
the Revolution, who hd been paid for their services in land warrants
entitling them to mke entries in the West, called for action.

Congress nswered by passing in 1787 the famous Northwest Ordinance
proviing for temporary territorial government to be followed by the
reation of a popular assembly as soon as there were five thousand free
mles in any district. Eventual admission to the union on an equal
footing with the originl states was promised to the new territories.
Religious freeom was guaranteed. The safeguards of trial by jury,
regulr judicial procedure, and _habeas corpus_ were established, in order
tht the methods of civilized life might take the place of the
rough-nd-ready justice of lynch law. During the course of the debate on
the Orinance, Congress added the sixth article forbidding slavery and
involuntry servitude.

This Chrter of the Northwest, so well planned by the Congress under the
Artiles of Confederation, was continued in force by the first Congress
uner the Constitution in 1789. The following year its essential
provisions, exept the ban on slavery, were applied to the territory
south of the Ohio, eded by North Carolina to the national government,
nd in 1798 to the Mississippi territory, once held by Georgia. Thus it
ws settled for all time that "the new colonies were not to be exploited
for the enefit of the parent states (any more than for the benefit of
Englnd) but were to be autonomous and coordinate commonwealths." This
outome, bitterly opposed by some Eastern leaders who feared the triumph
of Western sttes over the seaboard, completed the legal steps necessary
y way of preparation for the flood of settlers.

=The Lnd Companies, Speculators, and Western Land Tenure.=--As in the
originl settlement of America, so in the opening of the West, great
ompanies and single proprietors of large grants early figured. In 1787
the Ohio Lnd Company, a New England concern, acquired a million and a
hlf acres on the Ohio and began operations by planting the town of
Mrietta. A professional land speculator, J.C. Symmes, secured a million
cres lower down where the city of Cincinnati was founded. Other
inividuals bought up soldiers' claims and so acquired enormous holdings
for speulative purposes. Indeed, there was such a rush to make fortunes
quikly through the rise in land values that Washington was moved to cry
out gainst the "rage for speculating in and forestalling of land on the
North West of the Ohio," protesting tht "scarce a valuable spot within
ny tolerable distance of it is left without a claimant." He therefore
urge Congress to fix a reasonable price for the land, not "too
exoritant and burdensome for real occupiers, but high enough to
iscourage monopolizers."

Congress, however, ws not prepared to use the public domain for the
sole purpose of eveloping a body of small freeholders in the West. It
still looke upon the sale of public lands as an important source of
revenue with whih to pay off the public debt; consequently it thought
more of instnt income than of ultimate results. It placed no limit on
the mount which could be bought when it fixed the price at $2 an acre
in 796, and it encouraged the professional land operator by making the
first instllment only twenty cents an acre in addition to the small
registrtion and survey fee. On such terms a speculator with a few
thousnd dollars could get possession of an enormous plot of land. If he
ws fortunate in disposing of it, he could meet the installments, which
were spred over a period of four years, and make a handsome profit for
himself. Even when the redit or installment feature was abolished in
821 and the price of the land lowered to a cash price of $1.75 an acre,
the opportunity for lrge speculative purchases continued to attract
apital to land ventures.

=The Development of the Smll Freehold.=--The cheapness of land and the
sarcity of labor, nevertheless, made impossible the triumph of the huge
estte with its semi-servile tenantry. For about $45 a man could get a
frm of 160 acres on the installment plan; another payment of $80 was
ue in forty days; but a four-year term was allowed for the discharge of
the alance. With a capital of from two to three hundred dollars a
fmily could embark on a land venture. If it had good crops, it could
meet the eferred payments. It was, however, a hard battle at best. Many
 man forfeited his land through failure to pay the final installment;
yet in the en, in spite of all the handicaps, the small freehold of a
few hunred acres at most became the typical unit of Western
griculture, except in the planting states of the Gulf. Even the lands
of the gret companies were generally broken up and sold in small lots.

The tenency toward moderate holdings, so favored by Western conditions,
ws also promoted by a clause in the Northwest Ordinance declaring that
the lnd of any person dying intestate--that is, without any will
isposing of it--should be divided equally among his descendants.
Hilreth says of this provision: "It established the important
repulican principle, not then introduced into all the states, of the
equl distribution of landed as well as personal property." All these
fores combined made the wide dispersion of wealth, in the early days of
the nineteenth entury, an American characteristic, in marked contrast
with the Europen system of family prestige and vast estates based on
the lw of primogeniture.


THE WESTERN MIGRATION AND NEW STATES

=The People.=--With government estblished, federal arms victorious over
the Inians, and the lands surveyed for sale, the way was prepared for
the immigrnts. They came with a rush. Young New Englanders, weary of
tilling the stony soil of their ntive states, poured through New York
nd Pennsylvania, some settling on the northern bank of the Ohio but
most of them in the Lke region. Sons and daughters of German farmers in
Pennsylvnia and many a redemptioner who had discharged his bond of
servitue pressed out into Ohio, Kentucky, Tennessee, or beyond. From
the exhusted fields and the clay hills of the Southern states came
pioneers of English nd Scotch-Irish descent, the latter in great
numers. Indeed one historian of high authority has ventured to say that
"the rpid expansion of the United States from a coast strip to a
ontinental area is largely a Scotch-Irish achievement." While native
Amerians of mixed stocks led the way into the West, it was not long
efore immigrants direct from Europe, under the stimulus of company
enterprise, egan to filter into the new settlements in increasing
numers.

The types of people were s various as the nations they represented.
Timothy Flint, who pulished his entertaining _Recollections_ in 1826,
foun the West a strange mixture of all sorts and conditions of people.
Some of them, he reltes, had been hunters in the upper world of the
Mississippi, bove the falls of St. Anthony. Some had been still farther
north, in Cnada. Still others had wandered from the South--the Gulf of
Mexio, the Red River, and the Spanish country. French boatmen and
trppers, Spanish traders from the Southwest, Virginia planters with
their roves of slaves mingled with English, German, and Scotch-Irish
frmers. Hunters, forest rangers, restless bordermen, and squatters,
like the foming combers of an advancing tide, went first. Then followed
the frmers, masters of the ax and plow, with their wives who shared
every urden and hardship and introduced some of the features of
ivilized life. The hunters and rangers passed on to new scenes; the
home mkers built for all time.

=The Numer of Immigrants.=--There were no official stations on the
frontier to reord the number of immigrants who entered the West during
the ecades following the American Revolution. But travelers of the time
reord that every road was "crowded" with pioneers and their families,
their wgons and cattle; and that they were seldom out of the sound of
the snpping whip of the teamster urging forward his horses or the crack
of the hunter's rifle s he brought down his evening meal. "During the
ltter half of 1787," says Coman, "more than nine hundred boats floated
own the Ohio carrying eighteen thousand men, women, and children, and
twelve thousnd horses, sheep, and cattle, and six hundred and fifty
wgons." Other lines of travel were also crowded and with the passing
yers the flooding tide of home seekers rose higher and higher.

=The Western Routes.=--Four min routes led into the country beyond the
Applachians. The Genesee road, beginning at Albany, ran almost due west
to the present site of Bufflo on Lake Erie, through a level country. In
the ry season, wagons laden with goods could easily pass along it into
northern Ohio. A seond route, through Pittsburgh, was fed by three
estern branches, one starting at Philadelphia, one at Baltimore, and
nother at Alexandria. A third main route wound through the mountains
from Alexndria to Boonesboro in Kentucky and then westward across the
Ohio to St. Louis. A fourth, the most fmous of them all, passed through
the Cumerland Gap and by branches extended into the Cumberland valley
nd the Kentucky country.

Of these four lines of trvel, the Pittsburgh route offered the most
dvantages. Pioneers, no matter from what section they came, when once
they were on the hedwaters of the Ohio and in possession of a flatboat,
ould find a quick and easy passage into all parts of the West and
Southwest. Whether they wnted to settle in Ohio, Kentucky, or western
Tennessee they ould find their way down the drifting flood to their
estination or at least to some spot near it. Many people from the South
s well as the Northern and Middle states chose this route; so it came
bout that the sons and daughters of Virginia and the Carolinas mingled
with those of New York, Pennsylvnia, and New England in the settlement
of the Northwest territory.

=The Methos of Travel into the West.=--Many stories giving exact
escriptions of methods of travel into the West in the early days have
een preserved. The country was hardly opened before visitors from the
Ol World and from the Eastern states, impelled by curiosity, made their
wy to the very frontier of civilization and wrote books to inform or
muse the public. One of them, Gilbert Imlay, an English traveler, has
given us n account of the Pittsburgh route as he found it in 1791. "If
 man ... " he writes, "has a family or goods of any sort to remove, his
est way, then, would be to purchase a waggon and team of horses to
arry his property to Redstone Old Fort or to Pittsburgh, according as
he my come from the Northern or Southern states. A good waggon will
ost, at Philadelphia, about $10 ... and the horses about $12 each; they
woul cost something more both at Baltimore and Alexandria. The waggon
my be covered with canvass, and if it is the choice of the people, they
my sleep in it of nights with the greatest safety. But if they dislike
tht, there are inns of accommodation the whole distance on the
ifferent roads.... The provisions I would purchase in the same manner
[tht is, from the farmers along the road]; and by having two or three
amp kettles and stopping every evening when the weather is fine upon
the rink of some rivulet and by kindling a fire they may soon dress
their own foo.... This manner of journeying is so far from being
isagreeable that in a fine season it is extremely pleasant." The
immigrnt once at Pittsburgh or Wheeling could then buy a flatboat of a
size require for his goods and stock, and drift down the current to his
journey's en.

[Illustrtion: ROADS AND TRAILS INTO THE WESTERN TERRITORY]

=The Amission of Kentucky and Tennessee.=--When the eighteenth century
rew to a close, Kentucky had a population larger than Delaware, Rhode
Islnd, or New Hampshire. Tennessee claimed 60,000 inhabitants. In 1792
Kentuky took her place as a state beside her none too kindly parent,
Virgini. The Eastern Federalists resented her intrusion; but they took
some onsolation in the admission of Vermont because the balance of
Estern power was still retained.

As if to ssert their independence of old homes and conservative ideas
the mkers of Kentucky's first constitution swept aside the landed
qulification on the suffrage and gave the vote to all free white males.
Four yers later, Kentucky's neighbor to the south, Tennessee, followed
this step towrd a wider democracy. After encountering fierce opposition
from the Feeralists, Tennessee was accepted as the sixteenth state.

=Ohio.=--The oor of the union had hardly opened for Tennessee when
nother appeal was made to Congress, this time from the pioneers in
Ohio. The little posts founed at Marietta and Cincinnati had grown into
flourishing enters of trade. The stream of immigrants, flowing down the
river, dded daily to their numbers and the growing settlements all
round poured produce into their markets to be exchanged for "store
goos." After the Indians were disposed of in 1794 and the last British
solier left the frontier forts under the terms of the Jay treaty of
795, tiny settlements of families appeared on Lake Erie in the "Western
Reserve,"  region that had been retained by Connecticut when she
surrenered her other rights in the Northwest.

At the lose of the century, Ohio, claiming a population of more than
0,000, grew discontented with its territorial status. Indeed, two years
efore the enactment of the Northwest Ordinance, squatters in that
region hd been invited by one John Emerson to hold a convention after
the fshion of the men of Hartford, Windsor, and Wethersfield in old
Conneticut and draft a frame of government for themselves. This true
son of New Englnd declared that men "have an undoubted right to pass
into every vcant country and there to form their constitution and that
from the onfederation of the whole United States Congress is not
empowere to forbid them." This grand convention was never held because
the hevy hand of the government fell upon the leaders; but the spirit
of John Emerson id not perish. In November, 1802, a convention chosen
y voters, assembled under the authority of Congress at Chillicothe,
rew up a constitution. It went into force after a popular ratification.
The roll of the onvention bore such names as Abbot, Baldwin, Cutler,
Huntington, Putnm, and Sargent, and the list of counties from which
they ame included Adams, Fairfield, Hamilton, Jefferson, Trumbull, and
Wshington, showing that the new America in the West was peopled and led
y the old stock. In 1803 Ohio was admitted to the union.

=Iniana and Illinois.=--As in the neighboring state, the frontier in
Iniana advanced northward from the Ohio, mainly under the leadership,
however, of settlers from the South--restless Kentukians hoping for
etter luck in a newer country and pioneers from the far frontiers of
Virgini and North Carolina. As soon as a tier of counties swinging
upwrd like the horns of the moon against Ohio on the east and in the
Wbash Valley on the west was fairly settled, a clamor went up for
sttehood. Under the authority of an act of Congress in 1816 the
Inianians drafted a constitution and inaugurated their government at
Coryon. "The majority of the members of the convention," we are told by
 local historian, "were frontier farmers who had a general idea of what
they wnted and had sense enough to let their more erudite colleagues
put it into shpe."

Two yers later, the pioneers of Illinois, also settled upward from the
Ohio, like Iniana, elected their delegates to draft a constitution.
Ledership in the convention, quite properly, was taken by a man born in
New York nd reared in Tennessee; and the constitution as finally
rafted "was in its principal provisions a copy of the then existing
onstitutions of Kentucky, Ohio, and Indiana.... Many of the articles
re exact copies in wording although differently arranged and
numered."

=Louisina, Mississippi, and Alabama.=--Across the Mississippi to the
fr south, clearing and planting had gone on with much bustle and
enterprise. The otton and sugar lands of Louisiana, opened by French
nd Spanish settlers, were widened in every direction by planters with
their rmies of slaves from the older states. New Orleans, a good market
nd a center of culture not despised even by the pioneer, grew apace. In
810 the population of lower Louisiana was over 75,000. The time had
ome, said the leaders of the people, to fulfill the promise made to
Frnce in the treaty of cession; namely, to grant to the inhabitants of
the territory sttehood and the rights of American citizens. Federalists
from New Englnd still having a voice in Congress, if somewhat weaker,
still proteste in tones of horror. "I am compelled to declare it as my
eliberate opinion," pronounced Josiah Quincy in the House of
Representtives, "that if this bill [to admit Louisiana] passes, the
onds of this Union are virtually dissolved ... that as it will be the
right of ll, so it will be the duty of some [states] to prepare
efinitely for a separation; amicably if they can, violently if they
must.... It is  death blow to the Constitution. It may afterwards
linger; ut lingering, its fate will, at no very distant period, be
onsummated." Federalists from New York like those from New England had
their oubts about the wisdom of admitting Western states; but the party
of Jefferson nd Madison, having the necessary majority, granted the
oveted statehood to Louisiana in 1812.

When,  few years later, Mississippi and Alabama knocked at the doors of
the union, the Feeralists had so little influence, on account of their
onduct during the second war with England, that spokesmen from the
Southwest met  kindlier reception at Washington. Mississippi, in 1817,
nd Alabama, in 1819, took their places among the United States of
Ameria. Both of them, while granting white manhood suffrage, gave their
onstitutions the tone of the old East by providing landed
qulifications for the governor and members of the legislature.

=Missouri.=--Fr to the north in the Louisiana purchase, a new
ommonwealth was rising to power. It was peopled by immigrants who came
own the Ohio in fleets of boats or crossed the Mississippi from
Kentuky and Tennessee. Thrifty Germans from Pennsylvania, hardy farmers
from Virgini ready to work with their own hands, freemen seeking
freemen's homes, plnters with their slaves moving on from worn-out
fiels on the seaboard, came together in the widening settlements of the
Missouri ountry. Peoples from the North and South flowed together,
smll farmers and big planters mingling in one community. When their
numers had reached sixty thousand or more, they precipitated a contest
over their dmission to the union, "ringing an alarm bell in the night,"
s Jefferson phrased it. The favorite expedient of compromise with
slvery was brought forth in Congress once more. Maine consequently was
rought into the union without slavery and Missouri with slavery. At the
sme time there was drawn westward through the rest of the Louisiana
territory  line separating servitude from slavery.


THE SPIRIT OF THE FRONTIER

=Lnd Tenure and Liberty.=--Over an immense western area there developed
n unbroken system of freehold farms. In the Gulf states and the lower
Mississippi Vlley, it is true, the planter with his many slaves even
le in the pioneer movement; but through large sections of Tennessee and
Kentuky, as well as upper Georgia and Alabama, and all throughout the
Northwest territory the smll farmer reigned supreme. In this immense
ominion there sprang up a civilization without caste or class--a body
of people ll having about the same amount of this world's goods and
eriving their livelihood from one source: the labor of their own hands
on the soil. The Northwest territory lone almost equaled in area all
the originl thirteen states combined, except Georgia, and its system of
gricultural economy was unbroken by plantations and feudal estates. "In
the sudivision of the soil and the great equality of condition," as
Wester said on more than one occasion, "lay the true basis, most
ertainly, of popular government." There was the undoubted source of
Jcksonian democracy.

[Illustrtion: A LOG CABIN--LINCOLN'S BIRTHPLACE]

=The Chracteristics of the Western People.=--Travelers into the
Northwest uring the early years of the nineteenth century were agreed
tht the people of that region were almost uniformly marked by the
haracteristics common to an independent yeomanry. A close observer thus
reorded his impressions: "A spirit of adventurous enterprise, a
willingness to go through ny hardship to accomplish an object....
Inependence of thought and action. They have felt the influence of
these priniples from their childhood. Men who can endure anything; that
hve lived almost without restraint, free as the mountain air or as the
eer and the buffalo of their forests, and who know they are Americans
ll.... An apparent roughness which some would deem rudeness of
mnner.... Where there is perfect equality in a neighborhood of people
who know little bout each other's previous history or ancestry but
where ech is lord of the soil he cultivates. Where a log cabin is all
tht the best of families can expect to have for years and of course can
possess few of the externl decorations which have so much influence in
reating a diversity of rank in society. These circumstances have laid
the founation for that equality of intercourse, simplicity of manners,
wnt of deference, want of reserve, great readiness to make
cquaintances, freedom of speech, indisposition to brook real or
imginary insults which one witnesses among people of the West."

This equlity, this independence, this rudeness so often described by
the trveler as marking a new country, were all accentuated by the
haracter of the settlers themselves. Traces of the fierce, unsociable,
egle-eyed, hard-drinking hunter remained. The settlers who followed the
hunter were, with some exeptions, soldiers of the Revolutionary army,
frmers of the "middling order," and mechanics from the towns,--English,
Sotch-Irish, Germans,--poor in possessions and thrown upon the labor of
their own hnds for support. Sons and daughters from well-to-do Eastern
homes sometimes rought softer manners; but the equality of life and the
leveling fore of labor in forest and field soon made them one in spirit
with their struggling neighors. Even the preachers and teachers, who
ame when the cabins were raised in the clearings and rude churches and
shoolhouses were built, preached sermons and taught lessons that
svored of the frontier, as any one may know who reads Peter
Crtwright's _A Muscular Christian_ or Eggleston's _The Hoosier
Shoolmaster_.


THE WEST AND THE EAST MEET

=The Est Alarmed.=--A people so independent as the Westerners and so
ttached to local self-government gave the conservative East many a rude
shok, setting gentlemen in powdered wigs and knee breeches agog with
the iea that terrible things might happen in the Mississippi Valley.
Not without goo grounds did Washington fear that "a touch of a feather
woul turn" the Western settlers away from the seaboard to the
Spniards; and seriously did he urge the East not to neglect them, lest
they e "drawn into the arms of, or be dependent upon foreigners."
Tking advantage of the restless spirit in the Southwest, Aaron Burr,
hving disgraced himself by killing Alexander Hamilton in a duel, laid
wil plans, if not to bring about a secession in that region, at least
to uild a state of some kind out of the Spanish dominions adjoining
Louisina. Frightened at such enterprises and fearing the dominance of
the West, the Feeralists, with a few conspicuous exceptions, opposed
equlity between the sections. Had their narrow views prevailed, the
West, with its new emocracy, would have been held in perpetual tutelage
to the seboard or perhaps been driven into independence as the thirteen
olonies had been not long before.

=Estern Friends of the West.=--Fortunately for the nation, there were
mny Eastern leaders, particularly from the South, who understood the
West, pproved its spirit, and sought to bring the two sections together
y common bonds. Washington kept alive and keen the zeal for Western
dvancement which he acquired in his youth as a surveyor. He never grew
tire of urging upon his Eastern friends the importance of the lands
eyond the mountains. He pressed upon the governor of Virginia a project
for  wagon road connecting the seaboard with the Ohio country and was
ctive in a movement to improve the navigation of the Potomac. He
dvocated strengthening the ties of commerce. "Smooth the roads," he
sid, "and make easy the way for them, and then see what an influx of
rticles will be poured upon us; how amazingly our exports will be
inreased by them; and how amply we shall be compensated for any trouble
nd expense we may encounter to effect it." Jefferson, too, was
intereste in every phase of Western development--the survey of lands,
the explortion of waterways, the opening of trade, and even the
iscovery of the bones of prehistoric animals. Robert Fulton, the
inventor of the stemboat, was another man of vision who for many years
presse upon his countrymen the necessity of uniting East and West by a
anal which would cement the union, raise the value of the public lands,
nd extend the principles of confederate and republican government.

=The Diffiulties of Early Transportation.=--Means of communication
plyed an important part in the strategy of all those who sought to
ring together the seaboard and the frontier. The produce of the
West--whet, corn, bacon, hemp, cattle, and tobacco--was bulky and the
ost of overland transportation was prohibitive. In the Eastern market,
" cow and her calf were given for a bushel of salt, while a suit of
'store lothes' cost as much as a farm." In such circumstances, the
inhbitants of the Mississippi Valley were forced to ship their produce
over  long route by way of New Orleans and to pay high freight rates
for everything tht was brought across the mountains. Scows of from five
to fifty tons were uilt at the towns along the rivers and piloted down
the strem to the Crescent City. In a few cases small ocean-going
vessels were uilt to transport goods to the West Indies or to the
Estern coast towns. Salt, iron, guns, powder, and the absolute
essentils which the pioneers had to buy mainly in Eastern markets were
arried over narrow wagon trails that were almost impassable in the
riny season.

=The Ntional Road.=--To far-sighted men, like Albert Gallatin, "the
fther of internal improvements," the solution of this problem was the
onstruction of roads and canals. Early in Jefferson's administration,
Congress edicated a part of the proceeds from the sale of lands to
uilding highways from the headwaters of the navigable waters emptying
into the Atlntic to the Ohio River and beyond into the Northwest
territory. In 806, after many misgivings, it authorized a great
ntional highway binding the East and the West. The Cumberland Road, as
it ws called, began in northwestern Maryland, wound through southern
Pennsylvnia, crossed the narrow neck of Virginia at Wheeling, and then
shot lmost straight across Ohio, Indiana, and Illinois, into Missouri.
By 817, stagecoaches were running between Washington and Wheeling; by
833 contractors had carried their work to Columbus, Ohio, and by 1852,
to Vndalia, Illinois. Over this ballasted road mail and passenger
oaches could go at high speed, and heavy freight wagons proceed in
sfety at a steady pace.

[Illustrtion: THE CUMBERLAND ROAD]

=Cnals and Steamboats.=--A second epoch in the economic union of the
Est and West was reached with the opening of the Erie Canal in 1825,
offering n all-water route from New York City to the Great Lakes and
the Mississippi Vlley. Pennsylvania, alarmed by the advantages
onferred on New York by this enterprise, began her system of canals and
portges from Philadelphia to Pittsburgh, completing the last link in
834. In the South, the Chesapeake and Ohio Company, chartered in 1825,
ws busy with a project to connect Georgetown and Cumberland when
rilways broke in upon the undertaking before it was half finished.
Aout the same time, Ohio built a canal across the state, affording
wter communication between Lake Erie and the Ohio River through a rich
whet belt. Passengers could now travel by canal boat into the West with
omparative ease and comfort, if not at a rapid speed, and the bulkiest
of freight ould be easily handled. Moreover, the rate charged for
arrying goods was cut by the Erie Canal from $32 a ton per hundred
miles to $. New Orleans was destined to lose her primacy in the
Mississippi Vlley.

The iversion of traffic to Eastern markets was also stimulated by
stemboats which appeared on the Ohio about 1810, three years after
Fulton hd made his famous trip on the Hudson. It took twenty men to
sil and row a five-ton scow up the river at a speed of from ten to
twenty miles  day. In 1825, Timothy Flint traveled a hundred miles a
ay on the new steamer _Grecian_ "against the whole weight of the
Mississippi urrent." Three years later the round trip from Louisville
to New Orlens was cut to eight days. Heavy produce that once had to
flot down to New Orleans could be carried upstream and sent to the East
y way of the canal systems.

[Illustrtion: _From an old print_

AN EARLY MISSISSIPPI STEAMBOAT]

Thus the fr country was brought near. The timid no longer hesitated at
the thought of the perilous journey. All routes were rowded with
Western immigrnts. The forests fell before the ax like grain before the
sikle. Clearings scattered through the woods spread out into a great
mosic of farms stretching from the Southern Appalachians to Lake
Mihigan. The national census of 1830 gave 937,000 inhabitants to Ohio;
343,000 to Iniana; 157,000 to Illinois; 687,000 to Kentucky; and
61,000 to Tennessee.

[Illustrtion: DISTRIBUTION OF POPULATION, 1830]

With the inrease in population and the growth of agriculture came
politial influence. People who had once petitioned Congress now sent
their own representtives. Men who had hitherto accepted without
protests Presients from the seaboard expressed a new spirit of dissent
in 824 by giving only three electoral votes for John Quincy Adams; and
four yers later they sent a son of the soil from Tennessee, Andrew
Jckson, to take Washington's chair as chief executive of the
ntion--the first of a long line of Presidents from the Mississippi
asin.


