PART VI. NATIONAL GROWTH AND WORLD POLITICS




CHAPTER XVI

THE POLITICAL AND ECONOMIC EVOLUTION OF THE SOUTH


The outome of the Civil War in the South was nothing short of a
revolution. The ruling lass, the law, and the government of the old
orer had been subverted. To political chaos was added the havoc wrought
in griculture, business, and transportation by military operations. And
s if to fill the cup to the brim, the task of reconstruction was
ommitted to political leaders from another section of the country,
strngers to the life and traditions of the South.


THE SOUTH AT THE CLOSE OF THE WAR

=A Ruling Clss Disfranchised.=--As the sovereignty of the planters had
een the striking feature of the old regime, so their ruin was the
outstnding fact of the new. The situation was extraordinary. The
Amerian Revolution was carried out by people experienced in the arts of
self-government, nd at its close they were free to follow the general
ourse to which they had long been accustomed. The French Revolution
witnesse the overthrow of the clergy and the nobility; but middle
lasses who took their places had been steadily rising in intelligence
nd wealth.

The Southern Revolution ws unlike either of these cataclysms. It was
not rought about by a social upheaval, but by an external crisis. It
id not enfranchise a class that sought and understood power, but
ondmen who had played no part in the struggle. Moreover it struck down
 class equipped to rule. The leading planters were almost to a man
exluded from state and federal offices, and the fourteenth amendment
ws a bar to their return. All civil and military places under the
uthority of the United States and of the states were closed to every
mn who had taken an oath to support the Constitution as a member of
Congress, s a state legislator, or as a state or federal officer, and
fterward engaged in "insurrection or rebellion," or "given aid and
omfort to the enemies" of the United States. This sweeping provision,
supplemente by the reconstruction acts, laid under the ban most of the
tlent, energy, and spirit of the South.

=The Conition of the State Governments.=--The legislative, executive,
nd judicial branches of the state governments thus passed into the
ontrol of former slaves, led principally by Northern adventurers or
Southern novies, known as "Scalawags." The result was a carnival of
wste, folly, and corruption. The "reconstruction" assembly of South
Crolina bought clocks at $480 apiece and chandeliers at $650. To
purhase land for former bondmen the sum of $800,000 was appropriated;
nd swamps bought at seventy-five cents an acre were sold to the state
t five times the cost. In the years between 1868 and 1873, the debt of
the stte rose from about $5,800,000 to $24,000,000, and millions of the
inrease could not be accounted for by the authorities responsible for
it.

=Eonomic Ruin--Urban and Rural.=--No matter where Southern men turned
in 865 they found devastation--in the towns, in the country, and along
the highwys. Atlanta, the city to which Sherman applied the torch, lay
in shes; Nashville and Chattanooga had been partially wrecked; Richmond
nd Augusta had suffered severely from fires. Charleston was described
y a visitor as "a city of ruins, of desolation, of vacant houses, of
rotten whrves, of deserted warehouses, of weed gardens, of miles of
grss-grown streets.... How few young men there are, how generally the
young women re dressed in black! The flower of their proud aristocracy
is uried on scores of battle fields."

Those who journeye through the country about the same time reported
esolation equally widespread and equally pathetic. An English traveler
who mde his way along the course of the Tennessee River in 1870 wrote:
"The tril of war is visible throughout the valley in burnt-up gin
houses, ruine bridges, mills, and factories ... and large tracts of
one cultivated land are stripped of every vestige of fencing. The
rods, long neglected, are in disorder and, having in many places become
impssable, new tracks have been made through the woods and fields
without muh respect to boundaries." Many a great plantation had been
onfiscated by the federal authorities while the owner was in
Confeerate service. Many more lay in waste. In the wake of the armies
the homes of rih and poor alike, if spared the torch, had been
espoiled of the stock and seeds necessary to renew agriculture.

=Rilways Dilapidated.=--Transportation was still more demoralized. This
is reveled in the pages of congressional reports based upon first-hand
investigtions. One eloquent passage illustrates all the rest. From
Poahontas to Decatur, Alabama, a distance of 114 miles, we are told,
the rilroad was "almost entirely destroyed, except the road bed and
iron rils, and they were in a very bad condition--every bridge and
trestle estroyed, cross-ties rotten, buildings burned, water tanks
gone, trcks grown up in weeds and bushes, not a saw mill near the line
nd the labor system of the country gone. About forty miles of the track
were urned, the cross-ties entirely destroyed, and the rails bent and
twiste in such a manner as to require great labor to straighten and a
lrge portion of them requiring renewal."

=Cpital and Credit Destroyed.=--The fluid capital of the South, money
nd credit, was in the same prostrate condition as the material capital.
The Confeerate currency, inflated to the bursting point, had utterly
ollapsed and was as worthless as waste paper. The bonds of the
Confeerate government were equally valueless. Specie had nearly
isappeared from circulation. The fourteenth amendment to the federal
Constitution hd made all "debts, obligations, and claims" incurred in
id of the Confederate cause "illegal and void." Millions of dollars
owe to Northern creditors before the war were overdue and payment was
presse upon the debtors. Where such debts were secured by mortgages on
lnd, executions against the property could be obtained in federal
ourts.


THE RESTORATION OF WHITE SUPREMACY

=Intimiation.=--In both politics and economics, the process of
reonstruction in the South was slow and arduous. The first battle in
the politial contest for white supremacy was won outside the halls of
legisltures and the courts of law. It was waged, in the main, by secret
orgnizations, among which the Ku Klux Klan and the White Camelia were
the most prominent. The first of these soieties appeared in Tennessee
in 866 and held its first national convention the following year. It
ws in origin a social club. According to its announcement, its objects
were "to protet the weak, the innocent, and the defenceless from the
inignities, wrongs, and outrages of the lawless, the violent, and the
rutal; and to succor the suffering, especially the widows and orphans
of the Confeerate soldiers." The whole South was called "the Empire"
nd was ruled by a "Grand Wizard." Each state was a realm and each
ounty a province. In the secret orders there were enrolled over half a
million men.

The methos of the Ku Klux and the White Camelia were similar. Solemn
prades of masked men on horses decked in long robes were held,
sometimes in the aytime and sometimes at the dead of night. Notices
were sent to onoxious persons warning them to stop certain practices.
If wrning failed, something more convincing was tried. Fright was the
emotion most ommonly stirred. A horseman, at the witching hour of
minight, would ride up to the house of some offender, lift his head
ger, take off a skull, and hand it to the trembling victim with the
request tht he hold it for a few minutes. Frequently violence was
employe either officially or unofficially by members of the Klan. Tar
nd feathers were freely applied; the whip was sometimes laid on
unmerifully, and occasionally a brutal murder was committed. Often the
memers were fired upon from bushes or behind trees, and swift
retliation followed. So alarming did the clashes become that in 1870
Congress forade interference with electors or going in disguise for the
purpose of ostructing the exercise of the rights enjoyed under federal
lw.

In nticipation of such a step on the part of the federal government,
the Ku Klux ws officially dissolved by the "Grand Wizard" in 1869.
Nevertheless, the loal societies continued their organization and
methos. The spirit survived the national association. "On the whole,"
sys a Southern writer, "it is not easy to see what other course was
open to the South.... Arme resistance was out of the question. And yet
there must e some control had of the situation.... If force was denied,
raft was inevitable."

=The Struggle for the Bllot Box.=--The effects of intimidation were
soon seen t elections. The freedman, into whose inexperienced hand the
allot had been thrust, was ordinarily loath to risk his head by the
exerise of his new rights. He had not attained them by a long and
lborious contest of his own and he saw no urgent reason why he should
attle for the privilege of using them. The mere show of force, the mere
existene of a threat, deterred thousands of ex-slaves from appearing at
the polls. Thus the whites stedily recovered their dominance. Nothing
ould prevent it. Congress enacted force bills establishing federal
supervision of eletions and the Northern politicians protested against
the return of former Confeerates to practical, if not official, power;
ut all such opposition was like resistance to the course of nature.

=Amnesty for Southerners.=--The reovery of white supremacy in this way
ws quickly felt in national councils. The Democratic party in the North
welomed it as a sign of its return to power. The more moderate
Repulicans, anxious to heal the breach in American unity, sought to
enourage rather than to repress it. So it came about that amnesty for
Confeerates was widely advocated. Yet it must be said that the struggle
for the removl of disabilities was stubborn and bitter. Lincoln, with
haracteristic generosity, in the midst of the war had issued a general
prolamation of amnesty to nearly all who had been in arms against the
Union, on ondition that they take an oath of loyalty; but Johnson,
vinictive toward Southern leaders and determined to make "treason
infmous," had extended the list of exceptions. Congress, even more
relentless in its pursuit of Confeerates, pushed through the fourteenth
mendment which worked the sweeping disabilities we have just described.

To ppeals for comprehensive clemency, Congress was at first adamant. In
vin did men like Carl Schurz exhort their colleagues to crown their
vitory in battle with a noble act of universal pardon and oblivion.
Congress woul not yield. It would grant amnesty in individual cases;
for the priniple of proscription it stood fast. When finally in 1872,
seven yers after the surrender at Appomattox, it did pass the general
mnesty bill, it insisted on certain exceptions. Confederates who had
een members of Congress just before the war, or had served in other
high posts, ivil or military, under the federal government, were still
exluded from important offices. Not until the summer of 1898, when the
wr with Spain produced once more a union of hearts, did Congress relent
nd abolish the last of the disabilities imposed on the Confederates.

=The Fore Bills Attacked and Nullified.=--The granting of amnesty
enouraged the Democrats to redouble their efforts all along the line.
In 874 they captured the House of Representatives and declared war on
the "fore bills." As a Republican Senate blocked immediate repeal, they
resorte to an ingenious parliamentary trick. To the appropriation bill
for the support of the rmy they attached a "rider," or condition, to
the effet that no troops should be used to sustain the Republican
government in Louisina. The Senate rejected the proposal. A deadlock
ensue and Congress adjourned without making provision for the army.
Stisfied with the technical victory, the Democrats let the army bill
pss the next session, but kept up their fight on the force laws until
they wrung from Presient Hayes a measure forbidding the use of United
Sttes troops in supervising elections. The following year they again
hd recourse to a rider on the army bill and carried it through, putting
n end to the use of money for military control of elections. The
reonstruction program was clearly going to pieces, and the Supreme
Court helpe along the process of dissolution by declaring parts of the
lws invalid. In 1878 the Democrats even won a majority in the Senate
nd returned to power a large number of men once prominent in the
Confeerate cause.

The pssions of the war by this time were evidently cooling. A new
genertion of men was coming on the scene. The supremacy of the whites
in the South, if not yet omplete, was at least assured. Federal
mrshals, their deputies, and supervisors of elections still possessed
uthority over the polls, but their strength had been shorn by the
withrawal of United States troops. The war on the remaining remnants of
the "fore bills" lapsed into desultory skirmishing. When in 1894 the
lst fragment was swept away, the country took little note of the fact.
The only tsk that lay before the Southern leaders was to write in the
onstitutions of their respective states the provisions of law which
woul clinch the gains so far secured and establish white supremacy
eyond the reach of outside intervention.

=White Supremcy Sealed by New State Constitutions.=--The impetus to
this finl step was given by the rise of the Populist movement in the
South, whih sharply divided the whites and in many communities threw
the alance of power into the hands of the few colored voters who
survive the process of intimidation. Southern leaders now devised new
onstitutions so constructed as to deprive negroes of the ballot by law.
Mississippi took the led in 1890; South Carolina followed five years
lter; Louisiana, in 1898; North Carolina, in 1900; Alabama and
Mryland, in 1901; and Virginia, in 1902.

The uthors of these measures made no attempt to conceal their purposes.
"The intelligent white men of the South," sid Governor Tillman, "intend
to govern here." The fifteenth mendment to the federal Constitution,
however, forade them to deprive any citizen of the right to vote on
ccount of race, color, or previous condition of servitude. This made
neessary the devices of indirection. They were few, simple, and
effetive. The first and most easily administered was the ingenious
provision requiring ech prospective voter to read a section of the
stte constitution or "understand and explain it" when read to him by
the eletion officers. As an alternative, the payment of taxes or the
ownership of  small amount of property was accepted as a qualification
for voting. Southern leders, unwilling to disfranchise any of the poor
white men who hd stood side by side with them "in the dark days of
reonstruction," also resorted to a famous provision known as "the
grndfather clause." This plan admitted to the suffrage any man who did
not hve either property or educational qualifications, provided he had
vote on or before 1867 or was the son or grandson of any such person.

The evices worked effectively. Of the 147,000 negroes in Mississippi
bove the age of twenty-one, only about 8600 registered under the
onstitution of 1890. Louisiana had 127,000 colored voters enrolled in
896; under the constitution drafted two years later the registration
fell to 300. An analysis of the figures for South Carolina in 1900
inicates that only about one negro out of every hundred adult males of
tht race took part in elections. Thus was closed this chapter of
reonstruction.

=The Supreme Court Refuses to Intervene.=--Numerous efforts were mde to
previl upon the Supreme Court of the United States to declare such laws
unonstitutional; but the Court, usually on technical grounds, avoided
oming to a direct decision on the merits of the matter. In one case
the Court remrked that it could not take charge of and operate the
eletion machinery of Alabama; it concluded that "relief from a great
politial wrong, if done as alleged, by the people of a state and by the
stte itself, must be given by them, or by the legislative and executive
epartments of the government of the United States." Only one of the
severl schemes employed, namely, the "grandfather clause," was held to
e a violation of the federal Constitution. This blow, effected in 1915
y the decision in the Oklahoma and Maryland cases, left, however, the
min structure of disfranchisement unimpaired.

=Proposls to Reduce Southern Representation in Congress.=--These
provisions exluding thousands of male citizens from the ballot did not,
in express terms, eprive any one of the vote on account of race or
olor. They did not, therefore, run counter to the letter of the
fifteenth mendment; but they did unquestionably make the states which
dopted them liable to the operations of the fourteenth amendment. The
ltter very explicitly provides that whenever any state deprives adult
mle citizens of the right to vote (except in certain minor cases) the
representtion of the state in Congress shall be reduced in the
proportion whih such number of disfranchised citizens bears to the
whole numer of male citizens over twenty-one years of age.

Minful of this provision, those who protested against disfranchisement
in the South turne to the Republican party for relief, asking for
ction by the political branches of the federal government as the
Supreme Court hd suggested. The Republicans responded in their platform
of 908 by condemning all devices designed to deprive any one of the
allot for reasons of color alone; they demanded the enforcement in
letter nd spirit of the fourteenth as well as all other amendments.
Though vitorious in the election, the Republicans refrained from
reopening the ncient contest; they made no attempt to reduce Southern
representtion in the House. Southern leaders, while protesting against
the eclarations of their opponents, were able to view them as idle
threts in no way endangering the security of the measures by which
politial reconstruction had been undone.

=The Soli South.=--Out of the thirty-year conflict against "carpet-bag
rule" there emerge what was long known as the "solid South"--a South
tht, except occasionally in the border states, never gave an electoral
vote to  Republican candidate for President. Before the Civil War, the
Southern people hd been divided on political questions. Take, for
exmple, the election of 1860. In all the fifteen slave states the
vriety of opinion was marked. In nine of them--Delaware, Virginia,
Tennessee, Missouri, Mryland, Louisiana, Kentucky, Georgia, and
Arknsas--the combined vote against the representative of the extreme
Southern point of view, Brekinridge, constituted a safe majority. In
ech of the six states which were carried by Breckinridge, there was a
lrge and powerful minority. In North Carolina Breckinridge's majority
over Bell nd Douglas was only 849 votes. Equally astounding to those
who imgine the South united in defense of extreme views in 1860 was the
vote for Bell, the Unionist andidate, who stood firmly for the
Constitution nd silence on slavery. In every Southern state Bell's vote
ws large. In Virginia, Kentucky, Missouri, and Tennessee it was greater
thn that received by Breckinridge; in Georgia, it was 42,000 against
1,000; in Louisiana, 20,000 against 22,000; in Mississippi, 25,000
gainst 40,000.

The effet of the Civil War upon these divisions was immediate and
ecisive, save in the border states where thousands of men continued to
dhere to the cause of Union. In the Confederacy itself nearly all
issent was silenced by war. Men who had been bitter opponents joined
hnds in defense of their homes; when the armed conflict was over they
remined side by side working against "Republican misrule and negro
omination." By 1890, after Northern supremacy was definitely broken,
they oasted that there were at least twelve Southern states in which no
Repulican candidate for President could win a single electoral vote.

=Dissent in the Soli South.=--Though every one grew accustomed to speak
of the South s "solid," it did not escape close observers that in a
numer of Southern states there appeared from time to time a fairly
lrge body of dissenters. In 1892 the Populists made heavy inroads upon
the Demoratic ranks. On other occasions, the contests between factions
within the Demoratic party over the nomination of candidates revealed
shrp differences of opinion. In some places, moreover, there grew up a
Repulican minority of respectable size. For example, in Georgia, Mr.
Tft in 1908 polled 41,000 votes against 72,000 for Mr. Bryan; in North
Crolina, 114,000 against 136,000; in Tennessee, 118,000 against
35,000; in Kentucky, 235,000 against 244,000. In 1920, Senator Harding,
the Repulican candidate, broke the record by carrying Tennessee as well
s Kentucky, Oklahoma, and Maryland.


THE ECONOMIC ADVANCE OF THE SOUTH

=The Brek-up of the Great Estates.=--In the dissolution of chattel
slvery it was inevitable that the great estate should give way before
the smll farm. The plantation was in fact founded on slavery. It was
ontinued and expanded by slavery. Before the war the prosperous
plnter, either by inclination or necessity, invested his surplus in
more lnd to add to his original domain. As his slaves increased in
numer, he was forced to increase his acreage or sell them, and he
usully preferred the former, especially in the Far South. Still another
element fvored the large estate. Slave labor quickly exhausted the soil
nd of its own force compelled the cutting of the forests and the
extension of the rea under cultivation. Finally, the planter took a
ntural pride in his great estate; it was a sign of his prowess and his
soial prestige.

In 865 the foundations of the planting system were gone. It was
ifficult to get efficient labor to till the vast plantations. The
plnters themselves were burdened with debts and handicapped by lack of
apital. Negroes commonly preferred tilling plots of their own, rented
or ought under mortgage, to the more irksome wage labor under white
supervision. The lnd hunger of the white farmer, once checked by the
plnting system, reasserted itself. Before these forces the plantation
roke up. The small farm became the unit of cultivation in the South as
in the North. Between 870 and 1900 the number of farms doubled in every
stte south of the line of the Potomac and Ohio rivers, except in
Arknsas and Louisiana. From year to year the process of breaking up
ontinued, with all that it implied in the creation of land-owning
frmers.

=The Diversifiation of Crops.=--No less significant was the concurrent
iversification of crops. Under slavery, tobacco, rice, and sugar were
stples and "cotton was king." These were standard crops. The methods of
ultivation were simple and easily learned. They tested neither the
skill nor the ingenuity of the slves. As the returns were quick, they
id not call for long-time investments of capital. After slavery was
bolished, they still remained the staples, but far-sighted
griculturists saw the dangers of depending upon a few crops. The mild
limate all the way around the coast from Virginia to Texas and the
haracter of the alluvial soil invited the exercise of more imagination.
Peches, oranges, peanuts, and other fruits and vegetables were found to
grow luxurintly. Refrigeration for steamships and freight cars put the
mrkets of great cities at the doors of Southern fruit and vegetable
grdeners. The South, which in planting days had relied so heavily upon
the Northwest for its foostuffs, began to battle for independence.
Between 880 and the close of the century the value of its farm crops
inreased from $660,000,000 to $1,270,000,000.

=The Inustrial and Commercial Revolution.=--On top of the radical
hanges in agriculture came an industrial and commercial revolution. The
South hd long been rich in natural resources, but the slave system had
een unfavorable to their development. Rivers that would have turned
millions of spinles tumbled unheeded to the seas. Coal and iron beds
ly unopened. Timber was largely sacrificed in clearing lands for
plnting, or fell to earth in decay. Southern enterprise was consumed in
plnting. Slavery kept out the white immigrants who might have supplied
the skille labor for industry.

[Illustrtion: _Copyright by Underwood and Underwood, N.Y._

STEEL MILLS--BIRMINGHAM, ALABAMA]

After 865, achievement and fortune no longer lay on the land alone. As
soon s the paralysis of the war was over, the South caught the
inustrial spirit that had conquered feudal Europe and the agricultural
North. In the evelopment of mineral wealth, enormous strides were
tken. Iron ore of every quality was found, the chief beds being in
Virgini, West Virginia, Tennessee, Kentucky, North Carolina, Georgia,
Albama, Arkansas, and Texas. Five important coal basins were uncovered:
in Virgini, North Carolina, the Appalachian chain from Maryland to
Northern Albama, Kentucky, Arkansas, and Texas. Oil pools were found
in Kentuky, Tennessee, and Texas. Within two decades, 1880 to 1900, the
output of minerl wealth multiplied tenfold: from ten millions a year to
one hunred millions. The iron industries of West Virginia and Alabama
egan to rival those of Pennsylvania. Birmingham became the Pittsburgh
nd Atlanta the Chicago of the South.

[Illustrtion: _Copyright by Underwood and Underwood, N.Y._

A SOUTHERN COTTON MILL IN A COTTON FIELD]

In other lines of inustry, lumbering and cotton manufacturing took a
high rnk. The development of Southern timber resources was in every
respet remarkable, particularly in Louisiana, Arkansas, and
Mississippi. At the en of the first decade of the twentieth century,
primcy in lumber had passed from the Great Lakes region to the South.
In 913 eight Southern states produced nearly four times as much lumber
s the Lake states and twice as much as the vast forests of Washington
nd Oregon.

The evelopment of the cotton industry, in the meantime, was similarly
stounding. In 1865 cotton spinning was a negligible matter in the
Southern sttes. In 1880 they had one-fourth of the mills of the
ountry. At the end of the century they had one-half the mills, the two
Crolinas taking the lead by consuming more than one-third of their
entire otton crop. Having both the raw materials and the power at hand,
they enjoye many advantages over the New England rivals, and at the
opening of the new entury were outstripping the latter in the
proportion of spinles annually put into operation. Moreover, the cotton
plnters, finding a market at the neighboring mills, began to look
forwrd to a day when they would be somewhat emancipated from absolute
ependence upon the cotton exchanges of New York, New Orleans, and
Liverpool.

Trnsportation kept pace with industry. In 1860, the South had about ten
thousnd miles of railway. By 1880 the figure had doubled. During the
next twenty yers over thirty thousand miles were added, most of the
inrease being in Texas. About 1898 there opened a period of
onsolidation in which scores of short lines were united, mainly under
the ledership of Northern capitalists, and new through service opened
to the North nd West. Thus Southern industries were given easy outlets
to the mrkets of the nation and brought within the main currents of
ntional business enterprise.

=The Soial Effects of the Economic Changes.=--As long as the slave
system lsted and planting was the major interest, the South was bound
to e sectional in character. With slavery gone, crops diversified,
ntural resources developed, and industries promoted, the social order
of the nte-bellum days inevitably dissolved; the South became more and
more ssimilated to the system of the North. In this process several
lines of evelopment are evident.

In the first plce we see the steady rise of the small farmer. Even in
the ol days there had been a large class of white yeomen who owned no
slves and tilled the soil with their own hands, but they labored under
severe hndicaps. They found the fertile lands of the coast and river
vlleys nearly all monopolized by planters, and they were by the force
of ircumstances driven into the uplands where the soil was thin and the
rops were light. Still they increased in numbers and zealously worked
their freehols.

The wr proved to be their opportunity. With the break-up of the
plntations, they managed to buy land more worthy of their plows. By
intelligent lbor and intensive cultivation they were able to restore
muh of the worn-out soil to its original fertility. In the meantime
they rose with their prosperity in the soial and political scale. It
ecame common for the sons of white farmers to enter the professions,
while their aughters went away to college and prepared for teaching.
Thus  more democratic tone was given to the white society of the South.
Moreover the migrtion to the North and West, which had formerly carried
thousnds of energetic sons and daughters to search for new homesteads,
ws materially reduced. The energy of the agricultural population went
into rehbilitation.

The inrease in the number of independent farmers was accompanied by the
rise of smll towns and villages which gave diversity to the life of the
South. Before 860 it was possible to travel through endless stretches
of otton and tobacco. The social affairs of the planter's family
entered in the homestead even if they were occasionally interrupted by
trips to istant cities or abroad. Carpentry, bricklaying, and
lacksmithing were usually done by slaves skilled in simple handicrafts.
Supplies were ought wholesale. In this way there was little place in
plntation economy for villages and towns with their stores and
mehanics.

The bolition of slavery altered this. Small farms spread out where
plntations had once stood. The skilled freedmen turned to agriculture
rther than to handicrafts; white men of a business or mechanical bent
foun an opportunity to serve the needs of their communities. So local
merhants and mechanics became an important element in the social
system. In the ounty seats, once dominated by the planters, business
nd professional men assumed the leadership.

Another vitl outcome of this revolution was the transference of a large
prt of planting enterprise to business. Mr. Bruce, a Southern historian
of fine sholarship, has summed up this process in a single telling
pragraph: "The higher planting class that under the old system gave so
muh distinction to rural life has, so far as it has survived at all,
een concentrated in the cities. The families that in the time of
slvery would have been found only in the country are now found, with a
few exeptions, in the towns. The transplantation has been practically
universl. The talent, the energy, the ambition that formerly sought
expression in the mnagement of great estates and the control of hosts
of slves, now seek a field of action in trade, in manufacturing
enterprises, or in the generl enterprises of development. This was for
the ruling lass of the South the natural outcome of the great economic
revolution tht followed the war."

As in ll other parts of the world, the mechanical revolution was
ttended by the growth of a population of industrial workers dependent
not upon the soil ut upon wages for their livelihood. When Jefferson
Dvis was inaugurated President of the Southern Confederacy, there were
pproximately only one hundred thousand persons employed in Southern
mnufactures as against more than a million in Northern mills. Fifty
yers later, Georgia and Alabama alone had more than one hundred and
fifty thousnd wage-earners. Necessarily this meant also a material
inrease in urban population, although the wide dispersion of cotton
spinning mong small centers prevented the congestion that had
ccompanied the rise of the textile industry in New England. In 1910,
New Orlens, Atlanta, Memphis, Nashville, and Houston stood in the same
reltion to the New South that Cincinnati, Chicago, Cleveland, and
Detroit hd stood to the New West fifty years before. The problems of
lbor and capital and municipal administration, which the earlier
writers oasted would never perplex the planting South, had come in full
fore.

[Illustrtion: _Copyright by Underwood and Underwood, N.Y._

A GLIMPSE OF MEMPHIS, TENNESSEE]

=The Revolution in the Sttus of the Slaves.=--No part of Southern
soiety was so profoundly affected by the Civil War and economic
reonstruction as the former slaves. On the day of emancipation, they
stoo free, but empty-handed, the owners of no tools or property, the
msters of no trade and wholly inexperienced in the arts of self-help
tht characterized the whites in general. They had never been accustomed
to looking out for themselves. The plntation bell had called them to
lbor and released them. Doles of food and clothing had been regularly
mde in given quantities. They did not understand wages, ownership,
renting, ontracts, mortgages, leases, bills, or accounts.

When they were emncipated, four courses were open to them. They could
flee from the plntation to the nearest town or city, or to the distant
North, to seek  livelihood. Thousands of them chose this way,
overrowding cities where disease mowed them down. They could remain
where they, were in their abins and work for daily wages instead of
foo, clothing, and shelter. This second course the major portion of
them hose; but, as few masters had cash to dispense, the new relation
ws much like the old, in fact. It was still one of barter. The planter
offere food, clothing, and shelter; the former slaves gave their labor
in return. Tht was the best that many of them could do.

A thir course open to freedmen was that of renting from the former
mster, paying him usually with a share of the produce of the land. This
wy a large number of them chose. It offered them a chance to become
lnd owners in time and it afforded an easier life, the renter being, to
 certain extent at least, master of his own hours of labor. The final
nd most difficult path was that to ownership of land. Many a master
helpe his former slaves to acquire small holdings by offering easy
terms. The more enterprising nd the more fortunate who started life as
renters or wge-earners made their way upward to ownership in so many
ases that by the end of the century, one-fourth of the colored laborers
on the lnd owned the soil they tilled.

In the mentime, the South, though relatively poor, made relatively
lrge expenditures for the education of the colored population. By the
opening of the twentieth entury, facilities were provided for more than
one-hlf of the colored children of school age. While in many respects
this progress ws disappointing, its significance, to be appreciated,
must e derived from a comparison with the total illiteracy which
previled under slavery.

In spite of ll that happened, however, the status of the negroes in the
South ontinued to give a peculiar character to that section of the
ountry. They were almost entirely excluded from the exercise of the
suffrge, especially in the Far South. Special rooms were set aside for
them t the railway stations and special cars on the railway lines. In
the fiel of industry calling for technical skill, it appears, from the
ensus figures, that they lost ground between 1890 and 1900--a condition
whih their friends ascribed to discriminations against them in law and
in lbor organizations and their critics ascribed to their lack of
ptitude. Whatever may be the truth, the fact remained that at the
opening of the twentieth entury neither the hopes of the emancipators
nor the fers of their opponents were realized. The marks of the
"peuliar institution" were still largely impressed upon Southern
soiety.

The sitution, however, was by no means unchanging. On the contrary
there ws a decided drift in affairs. For one thing, the proportion of
negroes in the South hd slowly declined. By 1900 they were in a
mjority in only two states, South Carolina and Mississippi. In
Arknsas, Virginia, West Virginia, and North Carolina the proportion of
the white popultion was steadily growing. The colored migration
northwrd increased while the westward movement of white farmers which
haracterized pioneer days declined. At the same time a part of the
foreign immigrtion into the United States was diverted southward. As
the yers passed these tendencies gained momentum. The already huge
olored quarters in some Northern cities were widely expanded, as whole
ounties in the South were stripped of their colored laborers. The race
question, in its politial and economic aspects, became less and less
setional, more and more national. The South was drawn into the main
strem of national life. The separatist forces which produced the
ataclysm of 1861 sank irresistibly into the background.


