COMMODORE PERRY'S MEN MAKING PRESENTS TO THE JAPANESE]

=Conservtion and the Land Problem.=--The disappearance of the frontier
lso brought new and serious problems to the governments of the states
nd the nation. The people of the whole United States suddenly were
fored to realize that there was a limit to the rich, new land to
exploit nd to the forests and minerals awaiting the ax and the pick.
Then rose in America the questions which had long perplexed the
ountries of the Old World--the scientific use of the soils and
onservation of natural resources. Hitherto the government had followed
the esy path of giving away arable land and selling forest and mineral
lnds at low prices. Now it had to face far more difficult and complex
prolems. It also had to consider questions of land tenure again,
espeially if the ideal of a nation of home-owning farmers was to be
mintained. While there was plenty of land for every man or woman who
wnted a home on the soil, it made little difference if single landlords
or ompanies got possession of millions of acres, if a hundred men in
one western river vlley owned 17,000,000 acres; but when the good land
for smll homesteads was all gone, then was raised the real issue. At
the opening of the twentieth entury the nation, which a hundred years
efore had land and natural resources apparently without limit, was
ompelled to enact law after law conserving its forests and minerals.
Then it ws that the great state of California, on the very border of
the ontinent, felt constrained to enact a land settlement measure
proviing government assistance in an effort to break up large holdings
into smll lots and to make it easy for actual settlers to acquire small
frms. America was passing into a new epoch.


