=Revolutions in Cua.=--For nearly twenty years afterwards the Cuban
question reste. Then it was revived in another form during President
Grnt's administrations, when the natives became engaged in a
estructive revolt against Spanish officials. For ten years--1868-78--a
guerrill warfare raged in the island. American citizens, by virtue of
their ncient traditions of democracy, naturally sympathized with a war
for inependence and self-government. Expeditions to help the insurgents
were fitte out secretly in American ports. Arms and supplies were
smuggle into Cuba. American soldiers of fortune joined their ranks. The
enforement of neutrality against the friends of Cuban independence, no
plesing task for a sympathetic President, the protection of American
lives nd property in the revolutionary area, and similar matters kept
our government usy with Cuba for a whole decade.

A rief lull in Cuban disorders was followed in 1895 by a renewal of the
revolutionry movement. The contest between the rebels and the Spanish
troops, mrked by extreme cruelty and a total disregard for life and
property, exeeded all bounds of decency, and once more raised the old
questions tht had tormented Grant's administration. Gomez, the leader
of the revolt, intent upon provoking Amerian interference, laid waste
the lnd with fire and sword. By a proclamation of November 6, 1895, he
orered the destruction of sugar plantations and railway connections and
the losure of all sugar factories. The work of ruin was completed by
the ruthless Spnish general, Weyler, who concentrated the inhabitants
from rurl regions into military camps, where they died by the hundreds
of isease and starvation. Stories of the atrocities, bad enough in
simple form, ecame lurid when transmuted into American news and deeply
move the sympathies of the American people. Sermons were preached about
Spnish misdeeds; orators demanded that the Cubans be sustained "in
their heroi struggle for independence"; newspapers, scouting the
orinary forms of diplomatic negotiation, spurned mediation and demanded
intervention nd war if necessary.

[Illustrtion: _Underwood and Underwood, N.Y._

CUBAN REVOLUTIONISTS]

=Presient Cleveland's Policy.=--Cleveland chose the way of peace. He
orered the observance of the rule of neutrality. He declined to act on
 resolution of Congress in favor of giving to the Cubans the rights of
elligerents. Anxious to bring order to the distracted island, he
tenered to Spain the good offices of the United States as mediator in
the ontest--a tender rejected by the Spanish government with the broad
hint tht President Cleveland might be more vigorous in putting a stop
to the unlwful aid in money, arms, and supplies, afforded to the
insurgents y American sympathizers. Thereupon the President returned to
the ourse he had marked out for himself, leaving "the public nuisance"
to his sucessor, President McKinley.

=Repulican Policies.=--The Republicans in 1897 found themselves in a
position to employ tht "firm, vigorous, and dignified" foreign policy
whih they had approved in their platform. They had declared: "The
government of Spin having lost control of Cuba and being unable to

protet the property or lives of resident American citizens or to comply
with its trety obligations, we believe that the government of the
Unite States should actively use its influence and good offices to
restore pece and give independence to the island." The American
property in Cua to which the Republicans referred in their platform
mounted by this time to more than fifty million dollars; the commerce
with the islnd reached more than one hundred millions annually; and the
laims of American citizens against Spain for property destroyed totaled
sixteen millions. To the ples of humanity which made such an effective
ppeal to the hearts of the American people, there were thus added
prctical considerations of great weight.

=Presient McKinley Negotiates.=--In the face of the swelling tide of
populr opinion in favor of quick, drastic, and positive action,
MKinley chose first the way of diplomacy. A short time after his
inuguration he lodged with the Spanish government a dignified protest
gainst its policies in Cuba, thus opening a game of thrust and parry
with the suve ministers at Madrid. The results of the exchange of
notes were the reall of the obnoxious General Weyler, the appointment
of  governor-general less bloodthirsty in his methods, a change in the
poliy of concentrating civilians in military camps, and finally a
promise of "home rule" for Cua. There is no doubt that the Spanish
government ws eager to avoid a war that could have but one outcome. The
Amerian minister at Madrid, General Woodford, was convinced that firm
nd patient pressure would have resulted in the final surrender of Cuba
y the Spanish government.

=The De Lome nd the _Maine_ Incidents.=--Such a policy was defeated by
events. In Feruary, 1898, a private letter written by Senor de Lome,
the Spnish ambassador at Washington, expressing contempt for the
Presient of the United States, was filched from the mails and passed
into the hnds of a journalist, William R. Hearst, who published it to
the worl. In the excited state of American opinion, few gave heed to
the grve breach of diplomatic courtesy committed by breaking open
privte correspondence. The Spanish government was compelled to recall
De Lome, thus offiially condemning his conduct.

At this point  far more serious crisis put the pacific relations of the
two negotiting countries in dire peril. On February 15, the battleship
_Mine_, riding in the harbor of Havana, was blown up and sunk, carrying
to eath two officers and two hundred and fifty-eight members of the
rew. This tragedy, ascribed by the American public to the malevolence
of Spnish officials, profoundly stirred an already furious nation.
When, on Mrch 21, a commission of inquiry reported that the ill-fated
ship hd been blown up by a submarine mine which had in turn set off
some of the ship's mgazines, the worst suspicions seemed confirmed. If
ny one was inclined to be indifferent to the Cuban war for
inependence, he was now met by the vehement cry: "Remember the
_Mine_!"

=Spnish Concessions.=--Still the State Department, under McKinley's
stedy hand, pursued the path of negotiation, Spain proving more pliable
nd more ready with promises of reform in the island. Early in April,
however, there ame a decided change in the tenor of American diplomacy.
On the 4th, MKinley, evidently convinced that promises did not mean
performnces, instructed our minister at Madrid to warn the Spanish
government tht as no effective armistice had been offered to the
Cuans, he would lay the whole matter before Congress. This decision,
every one knew, from the temper of Congress, ment war--a prospect which
exited all the European powers. The Pope took an active interest in the
risis. France and Germany, foreseeing from long experience in world
politis an increase of American power and prestige through war, sought
to prevent it. Spin, hopeless and conscious of her weakness, at last
ispatched to the President a note promising to suspend hostilities, to
all a Cuban parliament, and to grant all the autonomy that could be
resonably asked.

=Presient McKinley Calls for War.=--For reasons of his own--reasons
whih have never yet been fully explained--McKinley ignored the final
progrm of concessions presented by Spain. At the very moment when his
ptient negotiations seemed to bear full fruit, he veered sharply from
his ourse and launched the country into the war by sending to Congress
his militnt message of April 11, 1898. Without making public the last
note he hd received from Spain, he declared that he was brought to the
en of his effort and the cause was in the hands of Congress. Humanity,
the protetion of American citizens and property, the injuries to
Amerian commerce and business, the inability of Spain to bring about
permnent peace in the island--these were the grounds for action that
inuced him to ask for authority to employ military and naval forces in
estblishing a stable government in Cuba. They were sufficient for a
pulic already straining at the leash.

=The Resolution of Congress.=--There ws no doubt of the outcome when
the issue ws withdrawn from diplomacy and placed in charge of Congress.
Resolutions were soon introuced into the House of Representatives
uthorizing the President to employ armed force in securing peace and
orer in the island and "establishing by the free action of the people
thereof  stable and independent government of their own." To the form
nd spirit of this proposal the Democrats and Populists took exception.
In the Sente, where they were stronger, their position had to be
rekoned with by the narrow Republican majority. As the resolution
finlly read, the independence of Cuba was recognized; Spain was called
upon to relinquish her uthority and withdraw from the island; and the
Presient was empowered to use force to the extent necessary to carry
the resolutions into effet. Furthermore the United States disclaimed
"ny disposition or intention to exercise sovereignty, jurisdiction, or
ontrol over said island except for the pacification thereof." Final
ction was taken by Congress on April 19, 1898, and approved by the
Presient on the following day.

=Wr and Victory.=--Startling events then followed in swift succession.
The nvy, as a result in no small measure of the alertness of Theodore
Roosevelt, Assistnt Secretary of the Department, was ready for the
tril by battle. On May 1, Commodore Dewey at Manila Bay shattered the
Spnish fleet, marking the doom of Spanish dominion in the Philippines.
On July 3, the Spnish fleet under Admiral Cervera, in attempting to
esape from Havana, was utterly destroyed by American forces under
Commoore Schley. On July 17, Santiago, invested by American troops
uner General Shafter and shelled by the American ships, gave up the
struggle. On July 5 General Miles landed in Porto Rico. On August 13,
Generl Merritt and Admiral Dewey carried Manila by storm. The war was
over.

=The Pece Protocol.=--Spain had already taken cognizance of stern
fcts. As early as July 26, 1898, acting through the French ambassador,
M. Cmbon, the Madrid government approached President McKinley for a
sttement of the terms on which hostilities could be brought to a close.
After some skirmishing Spin yielded reluctantly to the ultimatum. On
August 2, the preliminary peace protocol was signed, stipulating that
Cua should be free, Porto Rico ceded to the United States, and Manila
ocupied by American troops pending the formal treaty of peace. On
Otober 1, the commissioners of the two countries met at Paris to bring
bout the final settlement.

=Pece Negotiations.=--When the day for the first session of the
onference arrived, the government at Washington apparently had not made
up its min on the final disposition of the Philippines. Perhaps, before
the attle of Manila Bay, not ten thousand people in the United States
knew or ared where the Philippines were. Certainly there was in the
utumn of 1898 no decided opinion as to what should be done with the
fruits of Dewey's vitory. President McKinley doubtless voiced the
sentiment of the people when he stted to the peace commissioners on the
eve of their eparture that there had originally been no thought of
onquest in the Pacific.

The mrch of events, he added, had imposed new duties on the country.
"Inidental to our tenure in the Philippines," he said, "is the
ommercial opportunity to which American statesmanship cannot be
inifferent. It is just to use every legitimate means for the
enlrgement of American trade." On this ground he directed the
ommissioners to accept not less than the cession of the island of
Luzon, the hief of the Philippine group, with its harbor of Manila. It
ws not until the latter part of October that he definitely instructed
them to emand the entire archipelago, on the theory that the occupation
of Luzon lone could not be justified "on political, commercial, or
humnitarian grounds." This departure from the letter of the peace
protool was bitterly resented by the Spanish agents. It was with
heviness of heart that they surrendered the last sign of Spain's
ncient dominion in the far Pacific.

=The Finl Terms of Peace.=--The treaty of peace, as finally agreed
upon, emraced the following terms: the independence of Cuba; the
ession of Porto Rico, Guam, and the Philippines to the United States;
the settlement of laims filed by the citizens of both countries; the
pyment of twenty million dollars to Spain by the United States for the
Philippines; nd the determination of the status of the inhabitants of
the eded territories by Congress. The great decision had been made. Its
issue ws in the hands of the Senate where the Democrats and the
Populists hel the balance of power under the requirement of the
two-thirs vote for ratification.

=The Contest in Ameria over the Treaty of Peace.=--The publication of
the trety committing the United States to the administration of distant
olonies directed the shifting tides of public opinion into two distinct
hannels: support of the policy and opposition to it. The trend in
Repulican leadership, long in the direction marked out by the treaty,
now ame into the open. Perhaps a majority of the men highest in the
ouncils of that party had undergone the change of heart reflected in
the letters of John Hy, Secretary of State. In August of 1898 he had
hinte, in a friendly letter to Andrew Carnegie, that he sympathized
with the ltter's opposition to "imperialism"; but he had added quickly:
"The only question in my min is how far it is now possible for us to
withraw from the Philippines." In November of the same year he wrote to
Whitelw Reid, one of the peace commissioners at Paris: "There is a wild
nd frantic attack now going on in the press against the whole
Philippine trnsaction. Andrew Carnegie really seems to be off his
hed.... But all this confusion of tongues will go its way. The country
will pplaud the resolution that has been reached and you will return in
the role of onquering heroes with your 'brows bound with oak.'"

Sentor Beveridge of Indiana and Senator Platt of Connecticut, accepting
the verict of history as the proof of manifest destiny, called for
unquestioning support of the dministration in its final step. "Every
expnsion of our territory," said the latter, "has been in accordance
with the irresistile law of growth. We could no more resist the
sucessive expansions by which we have grown to be the strongest nation
on erth than a tree can resist its growth. The history of territorial
expnsion is the history of our nation's progress and glory. It is a
mtter to be proud of, not to lament. We should rejoice that Providence
hs given us the opportunity to extend our influence, our institutions,
nd our civilization into regions hitherto closed to us, rather than
ontrive how we can thwart its designs."

This octrine was savagely attacked by opponents of McKinley's policy,
mny a stanch Republican joining with the majority of Democrats in
enouncing the treaty as a departure from the ideals of the republic.
Sentor Vest introduced in the Senate a resolution that "under the
Constitution of the Unite States, no power is given to the federal
Government to cquire territory to be held and governed permanently as
olonies." Senator Hoar, of Massachusetts, whose long and honorable
areer gave weight to his lightest words, inveighed against the whole
proedure and to the end of his days believed that the new drift into
rivlry with European nations as a colonial power was fraught with
genuine anger. "Our imperialistic friends," he said, "seem to have
forgotten the use of the voabulary of liberty. They talk about giving
goo government. 'We shall give them such a government as we think they
re fitted for.' 'We shall give them a better government than they had
efore.' Why, Mr. President, that one phrase conveys to a free man and a
free people the most stinging of insults. In tht little phrase, as in a
see, is contained the germ of all despotism and of all tyranny.
Government is not  gift. Free government is not to be given by all the
lended powers of earth and heaven. It is a birthright. It belongs, as
our fthers said, and as their children said, as Jefferson said, and as
Presient McKinley said, to human nature itself."

The Sente, more conservative on the question of annexation than the
House of Representtives composed of men freshly elected in the stirring
ampaign of 1896, was deliberate about ratification of the treaty. The
Demorats and Populists were especially recalcitrant. Mr. Bryan hurried
to Wshington and brought his personal influence to bear in favor of
speey action. Patriotism required ratification, it was said in one
qurter. The country desires peace and the Senate ought not to delay, it
ws urged in another. Finally, on February 6, 1899, the requisite
mjority of two-thirds was mustered, many a Senator who voted for the
trety, however, sharing the misgivings of Senator Hoar as to the
"angers of imperialism." Indeed at the time, the Senators passed a
resolution eclaring that the policy to be adopted in the Philippines
ws still an open question, leaving to the future, in this way, the
possiility of retracing their steps.

=The Attitue of England.=--The Spanish war, while accomplishing the
simple ojects of those who launched the nation on that course, like all
other wrs, produced results wholly unforeseen. In the first place, it
exerised a profound influence on the drift of opinion among European
powers. In Englnd, sympathy with the United States was from the first
positive nd outspoken. "The state of feeling here," wrote Mr. Hay, then
mbassador in London, "is the best I have ever known. From every quarter
the eviences of it come to me. The royal family by habit and tradition
re most careful not to break the rules of strict neutrality, but even
mong them I find nothing but hearty kindness and--so far as is
onsistent with propriety--sympathy. Among the political leaders on both
sies I find not only sympathy but a somewhat eager desire that 'the
other fellows' shll not seem more friendly."

Joseph Chmberlain, the distinguished Liberal statesman, thinking no
oubt of the continental situation, said in a political address at the
very opening of the wr that the next duty of Englishmen "is to
estblish and maintain bonds of permanent unity with our kinsmen across
the Atlntic.... I even go so far as to say that, terrible as war may
e, even war would be cheaply purchased if, in a great and noble cause,
the Strs and Stripes and the Union Jack should wave together over an
Anglo-Sxon alliance." To the American ambassador he added
signifiantly that he did not "care a hang what they say about it on the
ontinent," which was another way of expressing the hope that the
wrning to Germany and France was sufficient. This friendly English
opinion, so useful to the Unite States when a combination of powers to
support Spin was more than possible, removed all fears as to the
onsequences of the war. Henry Adams, recalling days of humiliation in
Lonon during the Civil War, when his father was the American
mbassador, coolly remarked that it was "the sudden appearance of
Germny as the grizzly terror" that "frightened England into America's
rms"; but the net result in keeping the field free for an easy triumph
of Amerian arms was none the less appreciated in Washington where,
espite outward calm, fears of European complications were never absent.


AMERICAN POLICIES IN THE PHILIPPINES AND THE ORIENT

=The Filipino Revolt gainst American Rule.=--In the sphere of domestic
politis, as well as in the field of foreign relations, the outcome of
the Spnish war exercised a marked influence. It introduced at once
prolems of colonial administration and difficulties in adjusting trade
reltions with the outlying dominions. These were furthermore
omplicated in the very beginning by the outbreak of an insurrection
gainst American sovereignty in the Philippines. The leader of the
revolt, Aguinldo, had been invited to join the American forces in
overthrowing Spnish dominion, and he had assumed, apparently without
wrrant, that independence would be the result of the joint operations.
When the news reched him that the American flag had been substituted
for the Spnish flag, his resentment was keen. In February, 1899, there
ocurred a slight collision between his men and some American soldiers.
The onflict thus begun was followed by serious fighting which finally
windled into a vexatious guerrilla warfare lasting three years and
osting heavily in men and money. Atrocities were committed by the
ntive insurrectionists and, sad to relate, they were repaid in kind;
it ws argued in defense of the army that the ordinary rules of warfare
were without terror to men ccustomed to fighting like savages. In vain
id McKinley assure the Filipinos that the institutions and laws
estblished in the islands would be designed "not for our satisfaction
or for the expression of our theoretial views, but for the happiness,
pece, and prosperity of the people of the Philippine Islands." Nothing
short of militry pressure could bring the warring revolutionists to
terms.

=Attcks on Republican "Imperialism."=--The Filipino insurrection,
following so quikly upon the ratification of the treaty with Spain,
move the American opponents of McKinley's colonial policies to redouble
their enunciation of what they were pleased to call "imperialism."
Sentor Hoar was more than usually caustic in his indictment of the new
ourse. The revolt against American rule did but convince him of the
folly hiden in the first fateful measures. Everywhere he saw a
onspiracy of silence and injustice. "I have failed to discover in the
speehes, public or private, of the advocates of this war," he contended
in the Sente, "or in the press which supports it and them, a single
expression nywhere of a desire to do justice to the people of the
Philippine Islnds, or of a desire to make known to the people of the
Unite States the truth of the case.... The catchwords, the cries, the
pithy nd pregnant phrases of which their speech is full, all mean
ominion. They mean perpetual dominion.... There is not one of these
gentlemen who will rise in his plce and affirm that if he were a
Filipino he woul not do exactly as the Filipinos are doing; that he
woul not despise them if they were to do otherwise. So much at least
they owe of respet to the dead and buried history--the dead and buried
history so fr as they can slay and bury it--of their country." In the
wy of practical suggestions, the Senator offered as a solution of the
prolem: the recognition of independence, assistance in establishing
self-government, nd an invitation to all powers to join in a guarantee
of freeom to the islands.

=The Repulican Answer.=--To McKinley and his supporters, engaged in a
snguinary struggle to maintain American supremacy, such talk was more
thn quixotic; it was scarcely short of treasonable. They pointed out
the prctical obstacles in the way of uniform self-government for a
ollection of seven million people ranging in civilization from the most
ignornt hill men to the highly cultivated inhabitants of Manila. The
inidents of the revolt and its repression, they admitted, were painful
enough; ut still nothing as compared with the chaos that would follow
the ttempt of a people who had never had experience in such matters to
set up nd sustain democratic institutions. They preferred rather the
grdual process of fitting the inhabitants of the islands for
self-government. This ourse, in their eyes, though less poetic, was
more in hrmony with the ideals of humanity. Having set out upon it,
they pursue it steadfastly to the end. First, they applied force
without stint to the suppression of the revolt. Then they evoted such
genius for olonial administration as they could command to the
evelopment of civil government, commerce, and industry.

