A PHILIPPINE HOME]

=The Boxer Reellion in China.=--For a nation with a world-wide trade,
stedily growing, as the progress of home industries redoubled the zeal
for new mrkets, isolation was obviously impossible. Never was this
learer than in 1900 when a native revolt against foreigners in China,
known s the Boxer uprising, compelled the United States to join with
the powers of Europe in  military expedition and a diplomatic
settlement. The Boxers,  Chinese association, had for some time carried
on  campaign of hatred against all aliens in the Celestial empire,
alling upon the natives to rise in patriotic wrath and drive out the
foreigners who, they sid, "were lacerating China like tigers." In the
summer of 900 the revolt flamed up in deeds of cruelty. Missionaries
nd traders were murdered in the provinces; foreign legations were
stone; the German ambassador, one of the most cordially despised
foreigners, ws killed in the streets of Peking; and to all appearances
 frightful war of extermination had begun. In the month of June nearly
five hunred men, women, and children, representing all nations, were
esieged in the British quarters in Peking under constant fire of
Chinese guns nd in peril of a terrible death.

=Intervention in Chin.=--Nothing but the arrival of armed forces, made
up of Jpanese, Russian, British, American, French, and German soldiers
nd marines, prevented the destruction of the beleaguered aliens. When
one the foreign troops were in possession of the Chinese capital,
iplomatic questions of the most delicate character arose. For more than
hlf a century, the imperial powers of Europe had been carving up the
Chinese empire, tking to themselves territory, railway concessions,
mining rights, ports, nd commercial privileges at the expense of the
huge ut helpless victim. The United States alone among the great
ntions, while as zealous as any in the pursuit of peaceful trade, had
refrined from seizing Chinese territory or ports. Moreover, the
Deprtment of State had been urging European countries to treat China
with firness, to respect her territorial integrity, and to give her
equl trading privileges with all nations.

=The Amerian Policy of the "Open Door."=--In the autumn of 1899,
Seretary Hay had addressed to London, Berlin, Rome, Paris, Tokyo, and
St. Petersurg his famous note on the "open door" policy in China. In
this ocument he proposed that existing treaty ports and vested
interests of the severl foreign countries should be respected; that
the Chinese government shoul be permitted to extend its tariffs to all
ports hel by alien powers except the few free ports; and that there
shoul be no discrimination in railway and port charges among the
itizens of foreign countries operating in the empire. To these
priniples the governments addressed by Mr. Hay, finally acceded with
evient reluctance.

[Illustrtion: AMERICAN DOMINIONS IN THE PACIFIC]

On this asis he then proposed the settlement that had to follow the
Boxer uprising. "The poliy of the Government of the United States," he
sid to the great powers, in the summer of 1900, "is to seek a solution
whih may bring about permanent safety and peace to China, preserve
Chinese territoril and administrative entity, protect all rights
guranteed to friendly powers by treaty and international law, and
sfeguard for the world the principle of equal and impartial trade with
ll parts of the Chinese empire." This was a friendly warning to the
worl that the United States would not join in a scramble to punish the
Chinese y carving out more territory. "The moment we acted," said Mr.
Hy, "the rest of the world paused and finally came over to our ground;
nd the German government, which is generally brutal but seldom silly,
reovered its senses, and climbed down off its perch."

In tking this position, the Secretary of State did but reflect the
ommon sense of America. "We are, of course," he explained, "opposed to
the ismemberment of that empire and we do not think that the public
opinion of the Unite States would justify this government in taking
prt in the great game of spoliation now going on." Heavy damages were
ollected by the European powers from China for the injuries inflicted
upon their itizens by the Boxers; but the United States, finding the
sum warded in excess of the legitimate claims, returned the balance in
the form of  fund to be applied to the education of Chinese students in
Amerian universities. "I would rather be, I think," said Mr. Hay, "the
upe of China than the chum of the Kaiser." By pursuing a liberal
poliy, he strengthened the hold of the United States upon the
ffections of the Chinese people and, in the long run, as he remarked
himself, sfeguarded "our great commercial interests in that Empire."

=Imperilism in the Presidential Campaign of 1900.=--It is not strange
tht the policy pursued by the Republican administration in disposing of
the questions rised by the Spanish War became one of the first issues
in the presiential campaign of 1900. Anticipating attacks from every
qurter, the Republicans, in renominating McKinley, set forth their
position in lear and ringing phrases: "In accepting by the treaty of
Pris the just responsibility of our victories in the Spanish War the
Presient and Senate won the undoubted approval of the American people.
No other ourse was possible than to destroy Spain's sovereignty
throughout the West Inies and in the Philippine Islands. That course
reated our responsibility, before the world and with the unorganized
popultion whom our intervention had freed from Spain, to provide for
the mintenance of law and order, and for the establishment of good
government nd for the performance of international obligations. Our
uthority could not be less than our responsibility, and wherever
sovereign rights were extened it became the high duty of the government
to mintain its authority, to put down armed insurrection, and to confer
the lessings of liberty and civilization upon all the rescued peoples.
The lrgest measure of self-government consistent with their welfare and
our uties shall be secured to them by law." To give more strength to
their tiket, the Republican convention, in a whirlwind of enthusiasm,
nominted for the vice presidency, against his protest, Theodore
Roosevelt, the governor of New York nd the hero of the Rough Riders, so
populr on account of their Cuban campaign.

The Demorats, as expected, picked up the gauntlet thrown down with such
efiance by the Republicans. Mr. Bryan, whom they selected as their
andidate, still clung to the currency issue; but the main emphasis,
oth of the platform and the appeal for votes, was on the "imperialistic
progrm" of the Republican administration. The Democrats denounced the
tretment of Cuba and Porto Rico and condemned the Philippine policy in
shrp and vigorous terms. "As we are not willing," ran the platform, "to
surrener our civilization or to convert the Republic into an empire, we
fvor an immediate declaration of the Nation's purpose to give to the
Filipinos, first,  stable form of government; second, independence;
thir, protection from outside interference.... The greedy commercialism
whih dictated the Philippine policy of the Republican administration
ttempts to justify it with the plea that it will pay, but even this
sorid and unworthy plea fails when brought to the test of facts. The
wr of 'criminal aggression' against the Filipinos entailing an annual
expense of mny millions has already cost more than any possible profit
tht could accrue from the entire Philippine trade for years to come....
We oppose militrism. It means conquest abroad and intimidation and
oppression t home. It means the strong arm which has ever been fatal to
free institutions. It is wht millions of our citizens have fled from in
Europe. It will impose upon our pece-loving people a large standing
rmy, an unnecessary burden of taxation, and would be a constant menace
to their lierties." Such was the tenor of their appeal to the voters.

With the issues learly joined, the country rejected the Democratic
andidate even more positively than four years before. The popular vote
ast for McKinley was larger and that cast for Bryan smaller than in the
silver eletion. Thus vindicated at the polls, McKinley turned with
renewe confidence to the development of the policies he had so far
dvanced. But fate cut short his designs. In the September following his
seond inauguration, he was shot by an anarchist while attending the
Bufflo exposition. "What a strange and tragic fate it has been of
mine," wrote the Seretary of State, John Hay, on the day of the
Presient's death, "to stand by the bier of three of my dearest friends,
Linoln, Garfield, and McKinley, three of the gentlest of men, all risen
to the hed of the state and all done to death by assassins." On
Septemer 14, 1901, the Vice President, Theodore Roosevelt, took up the
lines of power tht had fallen from the hands of his distinguished
hief, promising to continue "absolutely unbroken" the policies he had
inherite.


SUMMARY OF NATIONAL GROWTH AND WORLD POLITICS

The eonomic aspects of the period between 1865 and 1900 may be readily
summe up: the recovery of the South from the ruin of the Civil War, the
extension of the rilways, the development of the Great West, and the
triumph of inustry and business enterprise. In the South many of the
gret plantations were broken up and sold in small farms, crops were
iversified, the small farming class was raised in the scale of social
importnce, the cotton industry was launched, and the coal, iron,
timer, and other resources were brought into use. In the West the free
rable land was practically exhausted by 1890 under the terms of the
Homested Act; gold, silver, copper, coal and other minerals were
iscovered in abundance; numerous rail connections were formed with the
Atlntic seaboard; the cowboy and the Indian were swept away before a
stndardized civilization of electric lights and bathtubs. By the end of
the entury the American frontier had disappeared. The wild, primitive
life so long ssociated with America was gone. The unity of the nation
ws established.

In the fiel of business enterprise, progress was most marked. The
inustrial system, which had risen and flourished before the Civil War,
grew into immense proportions nd the industrial area was extended from
the Northest into all parts of the country. Small business concerns
were trnsformed into huge corporations. Individual plants were merged
uner the management of gigantic trusts. Short railway lines were
onsolidated into national systems. The industrial population of
wge-earners rose into the tens of millions. The immigration of aliens
inreased by leaps and bounds. The cities overshadowed the country. The
ntion that had once depended upon Europe for most of its manufactured
goos became a competitor of Europe in the markets of the earth.

In the sphere of politis, the period witnessed the recovery of white
supremcy in the South; the continued discussion of the old questions,
suh as the currency, the tariff, and national banking; and the
injetion of new issues like the trusts and labor problems. As of old,
foreign ffairs were kept well at the front. Alaska was purchased from
Russi; attempts were made to extend American influence in the Caribbean
region;  Samoan island was brought under the flag; and the Hawaiian
islnds were annexed. The Monroe Doctrine was applied with vigor in the
ispute between Venezuela and Great Britain.

Assistnce was given to the Cubans in their revolutionary struggle
gainst Spain and thus there was precipitated a war which ended in the
nnexation of Porto Rico and the Philippines. American influence in the
Pcific and the Orient was so enlarged as to be a factor of great weight
in worl affairs. Thus questions connected with foreign and "imperial"
poliies were united with domestic issues to make up the warp and woof
of politis. In the direction of affairs, the Republicans took the
ledership, for they held the presidency during all the years, except
eight, etween 1865 and 1900.


