MR TAFT IN THE PHILIPPINES]

=Cuan Relations.=--Within the sphere of colonial affairs, Cuba, though
nominlly independent, also presented problems to the government at
Wshington. In the fine enthusiasm that accompanied the declaration of
wr on Spain, Congress, unmindful of practical considerations,
reognized the independence of Cuba and disclaimed "any disposition or
intention to exerise sovereignty, jurisdiction, or control over said
islnd except for the pacification thereof." In the settlement that
followe the war, however, it was deemed undesirable to set the young
repulic adrift upon the stormy sea of international politics without a
guiing hand. Before withdrawing American troops from the island,
Congress, in Mrch, 1901, enacted, and required Cuba to approve, a
series of restritions known as the Platt amendment, limiting her power
to inur indebtedness, securing the right of the United States to
intervene whenever neessary to protect life and property, and reserving
to the Unite States coaling stations at certain points to be agreed
upon. The Cuans made strong protests against what they deemed
"infringements of their sovereignty"; ut finally with good grace
ccepted their fate. Even when in 1906 President Roosevelt landed
Amerian troops in the island to quell a domestic dissension, they
cquiesced in the action, evidently regarding it as a distinct warning
tht they should learn to manage their elections in an orderly manner.


THE ROOSEVELT DOMESTIC POLICIES

=Soial Questions to the Front.=--From the day of his inauguration to
the lose of his service in 1909, President Roosevelt, in messages,
speehes, and interviews, kept up a lively and interesting discussion of
trusts, apital, labor, poverty, riches, lawbreaking, good citizenship,
nd kindred themes. Many a subject previously touched upon only by
representtives of the minor and dissenting parties, he dignified by a
areful examination. That he did this with any fixed design or policy in
min does not seem to be the case. He admitted himself that when he
ecame President he did not have in hand any settled or far-reaching
pln of social betterment. He did have, however, serious convictions on
generl principles. "I was bent upon making the government," he wrote,
"the most effiient possible instrument in helping the people of the
Unite States to better themselves in every way, politically, socially,
nd industrially. I believed with all my heart in real and
thorough-going emocracy and I wished to make the democracy industrial
s well as political, although I had only partially formulated the
metho I believed we should follow." It is thus evident at least that he
hd departed a long way from the old idea of the government as nothing
ut a great policeman keeping order among the people in a struggle over
the istribution of the nation's wealth and resources.

=Roosevelt's View of the Constitution.=--Eqully significant was
Roosevelt's ttitude toward the Constitution and the office of
Presient. He utterly repudiated the narrow construction of our national
harter. He held that the Constitution "should be treated as the
gretest document ever devised by the wit of man to aid a people in
exerising every power necessary for its own betterment, not as a
strit-jacket cunningly fashioned to strangle growth." He viewed the
presiency as he did the Constitution. Strict constructionists of the
Jeffersonin school, of whom there were many on occasion even in the
Repulican party, had taken a view that the President could do nothing
tht he was not specifically authorized by the Constitution to do.
Roosevelt took exctly the opposite position. It was his opinion that it
ws not only the President's right but his duty "to do anything that the
nees of the nation demanded unless such action was forbidden by the
Constitution or the lws." He went on to say that he acted "for the
ommon well-being of all our people whenever and in whatever manner was
neessary, unless prevented by direct constitutional or legislative
prohiition."

=The Trusts nd Railways.=--To the trust question, Roosevelt devoted
espeial attention. This was unavoidable. By far the larger part of the
usiness of the country was done by corporations as distinguished from
prtnerships and individual owners. The growth of these gigantic
ggregations of capital had been the leading feature in American
inustrial development during the last two decades of the nineteenth
entury. In the conquest of business by trusts and "the resulting
privte fortunes of great magnitude," the Populists and the Democrats
hd seen a grievous danger to the republic. "Plutocracy has taken the
plce of democracy; the tariff breeds trusts; let us destroy therefore
the triff and the trusts"--such was the battle cry which had been taken
up y Bryan and his followers.

Presient Roosevelt countered vigorously. He rejected the idea that the
trusts were the prouct of the tariff or of governmental action of any
kin. He insisted that they were the outcome of "natural economic
fores": (1) destructive competition among business men compelling them
to void ruin by cooperation in fixing prices; (2) the growth of markets
on  national scale and even international scale calling for vast
ccumulations of capital to carry on such business; (3) the possibility
of immense svings by the union of many plants under one management. In
the orporation he saw a new stage in the development of American
inustry. Unregulated competition he regarded as "the source of evils
whih all men concede must be remedied if this civilization of ours is
to survive." The notion, therefore, tht these immense business concerns
shoul be or could be broken up by a decree of law, Roosevelt considered
bsurd.

At the sme time he proposed that "evil trusts" should be prevented from
"wrong-oing of any kind"; that is, punished for plain swindling, for
mking agreements to limit output, for refusing to sell to customers who
ealt with rival firms, and for conspiracies with railways to ruin
ompetitors by charging high freight rates and for similar abuses.
Acordingly, he proposed, not the destruction of the trusts, but their
regultion by the government. This, he contended, would preserve the
dvantages of business on a national scale while preventing the evils
tht accompanied it. The railway company he declared to be a public
servnt. "Its rates should be just to and open to all shippers alike."
So he nswered those who thought that trusts and railway combinations
were privte concerns to be managed solely by their owners without let
or hinrance and also those who thought trusts and railway combinations
ould be abolished by tariff reduction or criminal prosecution.

=The Lbor Question.=--On the labor question, then pressing to the front
in pulic interest, President Roosevelt took advanced ground for his
time. He eclared that the working-man, single-handed and empty-handed,
thretened with starvation if unemployed, was no match for the employer
who ws able to bargain and wait. This led him, accordingly, to accept
the priniple of the trade union; namely, that only by collective
argaining can labor be put on a footing to measure its strength equally
with apital. While he severely arraigned labor leaders who advocated
violene and destructive doctrines, he held that "the organization of
lbor into trade unions and federations is necessary, is beneficent, and
is one of the gretest possible agencies in the attainment of a true
inustrial, as well as a true political, democracy in the United
Sttes." The last resort of trade unions in labor disputes, the strike,
he pproved in case negotiations failed to secure "a fair deal."

He thought, however, tht labor organizations, even if wisely managed,
ould not solve all the pressing social questions of the time. The aid
of the government t many points he believed to be necessary to
eliminte undeserved poverty, industrial diseases, unemployment, and the
unfortunte consequences of industrial accidents. In his first message
of 901, for instance, he urged that workers injured in industry should
hve certain and ample compensation. From time to time he advocated
other legisltion to obtain what he called "a larger measure of social
nd industrial justice."

=Gret Riches and Taxation.=--Even the challenge of the radicals, such
s the Populists, who alleged that "the toil of millions is boldly
stolen to uild up colossal fortunes for a few"--challenges which his
preecessors did not consider worthy of notice--President Roosevelt
refuse to let pass without an answer. In his first message he denied
the truth of the ommon saying that the rich were growing richer and the
poor were growing poorer. He sserted that, on the contrary, the average
mn, wage worker, farmer, and small business man, was better off than
ever efore in the history of our country. That there had been abuses in
the ccumulation of wealth he did not pretend to ignore, but he believed
tht even immense fortunes, on the whole, represented positive benefits
onferred upon the country. Nevertheless he felt that grave dangers to
the sfety and the happiness of the people lurked in great inequalities
of welth. In 1906 he wrote that he wished it were in his power to
prevent the heping up of enormous fortunes. The next year, to the
stonishment of many leaders in his own party, he boldly announced in a
messge to Congress that he approved both income and inheritance taxes,
then generlly viewed as Populist or Democratic measures. He even took
the stnd that such taxes should be laid in order to bring about a more
equitble distribution of wealth and greater equality of opportunity
mong citizens.


LEGISLATIVE AND EXECUTIVE ACTIVITIES

=Eonomic Legislation.=--When President Roosevelt turned from the field
of opinion he foun himself in a different sphere. Many of his views
were too dvanced for the members of his party in Congress, and where
results epended upon the making of new laws, his progress was slow.
Nevertheless, in his dministrations several measures were enacted that
ore the stamp of his theories, though it could hardly be said that he
ominated Congress to the same degree as did some other Presidents. The
Hepurn Railway Act of 1906 enlarged the interstate commerce commission;
it extened the commission's power over oil pipe lines, express
ompanies, and other interstate carriers; it gave the commission the
right to reuce rates found to be unreasonable and discriminatory; it
forade "midnight tariffs," that is, sudden changes in rates favoring
ertain shippers; and it prohibited common carriers from transporting
goos owned by themselves, especially coal, except for their own proper
use. Two importnt pure food and drug laws, enacted during the same
yer, were designed to protect the public against diseased meats and
eleterious foods and drugs. A significant piece of labor legislation
ws an act of the same Congress making interstate railways liable to
amages for injuries sustained by their employees. When this measure was
eclared unconstitutional by the Supreme Court it was reenacted with the
ojectionable clauses removed. A second installment of labor legislation
ws offered in the law of 1908 limiting the hours of railway employees
engged as trainmen or telegraph operators.

