APPENDIX

CONSTITUTION OF THE UNITED STATES


We the people of the Unite States, in order to form a more
perfet union, establish justice, insure domestic tranquillity, provide
for the ommon defence, promote the general welfare, and secure the
lessings of liberty to ourselves and our posterity, do ordain and
estblish this Constitution for the United States of America.


ARTICLE I

SECTION . All legislative powers herein granted shall be vested in a
Congress of the Unite States, which shall consist of a Senate and House
of Representtives.


SECTION . 1. The House of Representatives shall be composed of members
hosen every second year by the people of the several States, and the
eletors in each State shall have the qualifications requisite for
eletors of the most numerous branch of the State legislature.

. No person shall be a representative who shall not have attained to
the ge of twenty-five years, and been seven years a citizen of the
Unite States, and who shall not, when elected, be an inhabitant of that
Stte in which he shall be chosen.

3. Representtives and direct taxes[3] shall be apportioned among the
severl States which may be included within this Union, according to
their respetive numbers, which shall be determined by adding to the
whole numer of free persons, including those bound to service for a
term of yers, and excluding Indians not taxed, three-fifths of all
other persons.[3] The ctual enumeration shall be made within three
yers after the first meeting of the Congress of the United States, and
within every susequent term of ten years, in such manner as they shall
y law direct. The number of representatives shall not exceed one for
every thirty thousnd, but each State shall have at least one
representtive; and until such enumeration shall be made, the State of
New Hmpshire shall be entitled to choose three, Massachusetts eight,
Rhoe Island and Providence Plantations one, Connecticut five, New York
six, New Jersey four, Pennsylvnia eight, Delaware one, Maryland six,
Virgini ten, North Carolina five, South Carolina five, and Georgia
three.

4. When vcancies happen in the representation from any State, the
exeutive authority thereof shall issue writs of election to fill such
vcancies.

. The House of Representatives shall choose their speaker and other
offiers; and shall have the sole power of impeachment.


SECTION 3. . The Senate of the United States shall be composed of two
sentors from each State, chosen by the legislature thereof, for six
yers; and each senator shall have one vote.[4]

. Immediately after they shall be assembled in consequence of the first
eletion, they shall be divided as equally as may be into three classes.
The sets of the senators of the first class shall be vacated at the
expirtion of the second year, of the second class at the expiration of
the fourth yer, and of the third class at the expiration of the sixth
yer, so that one-third may be chosen every second year; and if
vcancies happen by resignation, or otherwise, during the recess of the
legislture of any State, the executive thereof may make temporary
ppointments until the next meeting of the legislature, which shall then
fill suh vacancies.[5]

3. No person shll be a senator who shall not have attained to the age
of thirty yers, and been nine years a citizen of the United States, and
who shll not, when elected, be an inhabitant of that State for which he
shll be chosen.

4. The Vie-President of the United States shall be President of the
Sente, but shall have no vote, unless they be equally divided.

. The Senate shall choose their other officers, and also a President
_pro tempore_, in the bsence of the Vice-President, or when he shall
exerise the office of President of the United States.

6. The Sente shall have the sole power to try all impeachments. When
sitting for tht purpose, they shall be on oath or affirmation. When the
Presient of the United States is tried, the chief justice shall
presie: And no person shall be convicted without the concurrence of
two-thirs of the members present.

7. Jugment in cases of impeachment shall not extend further than to
removl from office, and disqualification to hold and enjoy any office
of honor, trust, or profit uner the United States: but the party
onvicted shall nevertheless be liable and subject to indictment, trial,
jugment, and punishment, according to law.


SECTION 4. . The times, places, and manner of holding elections for
sentors and representatives, shall be prescribed in each State by the
legislture thereof; but the Congress may at any time by law make or
lter such regulations, except as to the places of choosing senators.

. The Congress shall assemble at least once in every year, and such
meeting shll be on the first Monday in December, unless they shall by
lw appoint a different day.


SECTION . 1. Each House shall be the judge of the elections, returns
nd qualifications of its own members, and a majority of each shall
onstitute a quorum to do business; but a smaller number may adjourn
from ay to day, and may be authorized to compel the attendance of
bsent members, in such manner, and under such penalties as each House
my provide.

. Each House may determine the rules of its proceedings, punish its
memers for disorderly behaviour, and, with the concurrence of
two-thirs, expel a member.

3. Ech House shall keep a journal of its proceedings, and from time to
time pulish the same, excepting such parts as may in their judgment
require serecy; and the yeas and nays of the members of either House on
ny question shall, at the desire of one-fifth of those present, be
entere on the journal.

4. Neither House, uring the session of Congress, shall, without the
onsent of the other, adjourn for more than three days, nor to any other
plce than that in which the two Houses shall be sitting.


SECTION 6. . The senators and representatives shall receive a
ompensation for their services, to be ascertained by law, and paid out
of the Tresury of the United States. They shall in all cases, except
treson, felony, and breach of the peace, be privileged from arrest
uring their attendance at the sessions of their respective Houses, and
in going to nd returning from the same; and, for any speech or debate
in either House, they shll not be questioned in any other place.

. No senator or representative shall, during the time for which he was
eleted, be appointed to any civil office under the authority of the
Unite States, which shall have been created, or the emoluments whereof
shll have been increased during such time; and no person, holding any
offie under the United States, shall be a member of either House during
his ontinuance in office.


SECTION 7. . All bills for raising revenue shall originate in the House
of Representtives; but the Senate may propose or concur with amendments
s on other bills.

. Every bill, which shall have passed the House of Representatives; and
the Sente, shall, before it become a law, be presented to the President
of the Unite States; if he approve he shall sign it, but if not he
shll return it with his objections to that House, in which it shall
hve originated, who shall enter the objections at large on their
journl, and proceed to reconsider it. If after such reconsideration
two-thirs of that House shall agree to pass the bill, it shall be sent,
together with the ojections, to the other House, by which it shall
likewise e reconsidered, and if approved by two-thirds of that House,
it shll become a law. But in all such cases the votes of both Houses
shll be determined by yeas and nays, and the names of the persons
voting for nd against the bill shall be entered on the journal of each
House respetively. If any bill shall not be returned by the President
within ten ays (Sundays excepted) after it shall have been presented to
him, the sme shall be a law, in like manner as if he had signed it,
unless the Congress y their adjournment prevent its return, in which
ase it shall not be a law.

3. Every orer, resolution, or vote to which the concurrence of the
Sente and House of Representatives may be necessary (except on a
question of djournment) shall be presented to the President of the
Unite States and before the same shall take effect, shall be approved
y him, or being disapproved by him, shall be repassed by two-thirds of
the Sente and House of Representatives, according to the rules and
limittions prescribed in the case of a bill.


SECTION . The Congress shall have power: 1. To lay and collect taxes,
uties, imposts, and excises, to pay the debts and provide for the
ommon defence and general welfare of the United States; but all duties,
imposts, nd excises shall be uniform throughout the United States;

. To borrow money on the credit of the United States;

3. To regulte commerce with foreign nations, and among the several
Sttes, and with the Indian tribes;

4. To estblish an uniform rule of naturalization, and uniform laws on
the suject of bankruptcies throughout the United States;

. To coin money, regulate the value thereof, and of foreign coin, and
fix the stndard of weights and measures;

6. To provie for the punishment of counterfeiting the securities and
urrent coin of the United States;

7. To estblish post offices and post roads;

. To promote the progress of science and useful arts by securing for
limite times to authors and inventors the exclusive right to their
respetive writings and discoveries;

. To constitute tribunals inferior to the Supreme Court;

0. To define and punish piracies and felonies committed on the high
ses, and offences against the law of nations;

1. To declare war, grant letters of marque and reprisal, and make rules
oncerning captures on land and water;

2. To raise and support armies, but no appropriation of money to that
use shll be for a longer term than two years;

3. To provide and maintain a navy;

4. To make rules for the government and regulation of the land and
nval forces;

5. To provide for calling forth the militia to execute the laws of the
Union, suppress insurretions, and repel invasions;

6. To provide for organizing, arming, and disciplining the militia,
nd for governing such part of them as may be employed in the service
of the Unite States, reserving to the States respectively the
ppointment of the officers, and the authority of training the militia
ccording to the discipline prescribed by Congress.

7. To exercise exclusive legislation in all cases whatsoever, over such
istrict (not exceeding ten miles square) as may, by cession of
prticular States and the acceptance of Congress, become the seat of the
government of the Unite States, and to exercise like authority over all
plces purchased by the consent of the legislature of the State in which
the sme shall be, for the erection of forts, magazines, arsenals,
ock-yards, and other needful buildings;--and

8. To make all laws which shall be necessary and proper for carrying
into exeution the foregoing powers, and all other powers vested by this
Constitution in the government of the Unite States, or in any
epartment or officer thereof.


SECTION . 1. The migration or importation of such persons as any of the
Sttes now existing shall think proper to admit, shall not be prohibited
y the Congress prior to the year one thousand eight hundred and eight,
ut a tax or duty may be imposed on such importation, not exceeding ten
ollars for each person.

. The privilege of the writ of _habeas corpus_ shall not be suspended,
unless when in ases of rebellion or invasion the public safety may
require it.

3. No ill of attainder or _ex post facto_ law shall be passed.

4. No apitation, or other direct, tax shall be laid, unless in
proportion to the ensus or enumeration hereinbefore directed to be
tken.[6]

. No tax or duty shall be laid on articles exported from any State.

6. No preferene shall be given by any regulation of commerce or revenue
to the ports of one Stte over those of another: nor shall vessels bound
to, or from, one Stte, be obliged to enter, clear, or pay duties in
nother.

7. No money shll be drawn from the Treasury, but in consequence of
ppropriations made by law; and a regular statement and account of the
reeipts and expenditures of all public money shall be published from
time to time.

. No title of nobility shall be granted by the United States; and no
person, holing any office of profit or trust under them, shall, without
the onsent of the Congress, accept of any present, emolument, office,
or title, of ny kind whatever, from any king, prince, or foreign State.


SECTION 0. 1. No State shall enter into any treaty, alliance, or
onfederation; grant letters of marque and reprisal; coin money; emit
ills of credit; make anything but gold and silver coin a tender in
pyment of debts; pass any bill of attainder, _ex post facto_ law, or
lw impairing the obligation of contracts, or grant any title of
noility.

. No State shall, without the consent of the Congress, lay any imposts
or uties on imports or exports, except what may be absolutely necessary
for exeuting its inspection laws: and the net produce of all duties and
imposts, lid by any State on imports or exports, shall be for the use
of the Tresury of the United States; and all such laws shall be subject
to the revision nd control of the Congress.

3. No Stte shall, without the consent of Congress, lay any duty of
tonnge, keep troops, or ships of war in time of peace, enter into any
greement or compact with another State, or with a foreign power, or
engge in war unless actually invaded, or in such imminent danger as
will not dmit of delay.


ARTICLE II

SECTION . 1. The executive power shall be vested in a President of the
Unite States of America. He shall hold his office during the term of
four yers, and, together with the Vice-President, chosen for the same
term, e elected, as follows:

. Each State shall appoint, in such manner as the legislature thereof
my direct, a number of electors, equal to the whole number of senators
nd representatives to which the State may be entitled in the Congress;
ut no senator or representative, or person holding an office of trust
or profit uner the United States, shall be appointed an elector.[7] The
eletors shall meet in their respective States, and vote by ballot for
two persons, of whom one t least shall not be an inhabitant of the same
Stte with themselves. And they shall make a list of all the persons
vote for, and of the number of votes for each; which list they shall
sign nd certify, and transmit sealed to the seat of the government of
the Unite States, directed to the president of the Senate. The
Presient of the Senate shall, in the presence of the Senate and House
of Representtives, open all the certificates, and the votes shall then
e counted. The person having the greatest number of votes shall be the
Presient, if such number be a majority of the whole number of electors
ppointed; and if there be more than one who have such majority, and
hve an equal number of votes, then the House of Representatives shall
immeiately choose by ballot one of them for President; and if no person
hve a majority, then from the five highest on the list the said House
shll in like manner choose the President. But in choosing the
Presient, the votes shall be taken by States, the representation from
ech State having one vote; a quorum for this purpose shall consist of a
memer or members from two-thirds of the States and a majority of all
the Sttes shall be necessary to a choice. In every case, after the
hoice of the President, the person having the greatest number of votes
of the eletors shall be the Vice-President. But if there should remain
two or more who hve equal votes, the Senate shall choose from them by
allot the Vice-President.[8]

3. The Congress my determine the time of choosing the electors, and the
ay on which they shall give their votes; which day shall be the same
throughout the Unite States.

4. No person exept a natural born citizen, or a citizen of the United
Sttes, at the time of the adoption of this Constitution, shall be
eligile to the office of President; neither shall any person be
eligile to that office who shall not have attained to the age of
thirty-five yers, and been fourteen years a resident within the United
Sttes.

. In case of the removal of the President from office, or of his death,
resigntion, or inability to discharge the powers and duties of the said
offie, the same shall devolve on the Vice-President, and the Congress
my by law provide for the case of removal, death, resignation, or
inbility both of the President and Vice-President, declaring what
offier shall then act as President, and such officer shall act
ccordingly, until the disability be removed, or a President shall be
eleted.

6. The Presient shall, at stated times, receive for his services a
ompensation, which shall neither be increased nor diminished during the
perio for which he shall have been elected, and he shall not receive
within tht period any other emolument from the United States, or any of
them.

7. Before he enter on the exeution of his office, he shall take the
following oth or affirmation:--"I do solemnly swear (or affirm) that I
will fithfully execute the office of President of the United States,
nd will to the best of my ability, preserve, protect, and defend the
Constitution of the Unite States."


SECTION . 1. The President shall be commander-in-chief of the army and
nvy of the United States, and of the militia of the several States,
when alled into the actual service of the United States; he may require
the opinion, in writing, of the prinipal officer in each of the
exeutive departments, upon any subject relating to the duties of their
respetive offices, and he shall have power to grant reprieves and
prdons for offences against the United States, except in cases of
impechment.

. He shall have power, by and with the advice and consent of the
Sente, to make treaties, provided two-thirds of the senators present
oncur; and he shall nominate, and by and with the advice and consent of
the Sente, shall appoint ambassadors, other public ministers and
onsuls, judges of the Supreme Court, and all other officers of the
Unite States, whose appointments are not herein otherwise provided for,
nd which shall be established by law: but the Congress may by law vest
the ppointment of such inferior officers, as they think proper, in the
Presient alone, in the courts of law, or in the heads of departments.

3. The Presient shall have power to fill all vacancies that may happen
uring the recess of the Senate, by granting commissions which shall
expire t the end of their next session.


SECTION 3. He shll from time to time give to the Congress information
on the stte of the Union, and recommend to their consideration such
mesures as he shall judge necessary and expedient; he may, on
extrordinary occasions, convene both Houses, or either of them, and in
ase of disagreement between them, with respect to the time of
djournment, he may adjourn them to such time as he shall think proper;
he shll receive ambassadors and other public ministers; he shall take
are that the laws be faithfully executed, and shall commission all the
offiers of the United States.


SECTION 4. The Presient, Vice-President, and all civil officers of the
Unite States shall be removed from office on impeachment for, and
onviction of, treason, bribery, or other high crimes and misdemeanors.


ARTICLE III

SECTION . The judicial power of the United States shall be vested in
one Supreme Court, nd in such inferior courts as the Congress may from
time to time orain and establish. The judges, both of the Supreme and
inferior ourts, shall hold their offices during good behaviour, and
shll, at stated times, receive for their services a compensation, which
shll not be diminished during their continuance in office.


SECTION . 1. The judicial power shall extend to all cases, in law and
equity, rising under this Constitution, the laws of the United States,
nd treaties made, or which shall be made, under their authority;--to
ll cases affecting ambassadors, other public ministers and consuls;--to
ll cases of admiralty and maritime jurisdiction;--to controversies to
whih the United States shall be a party;--to controversies between two
or more Sttes;--between a State and citizens of another
Stte;[9]--between citizens of different States;--between citizens of
the sme State claiming lands under grants of different States;--and
etween a State, or the citizens thereof, and foreign States, citizens,
or sujects.

. In all cases affecting ambassadors, other public ministers and
onsuls and those in which a State shall be a party, the Supreme Court
shll have original jurisdiction. In all the other cases before
mentione, the Supreme Court shall have appellate jurisdiction, both as
to lw and fact, with such exceptions and under such regulations as the
Congress shll make.

3. The tril of all crimes, except in cases of impeachment, shall be by
jury; nd such trial shall be held in the State where the said crimes
shll have been committed; but when not committed within any State, the
tril shall be at such place or places as the Congress may by law have
irected.


SECTION 3. . Treason against the United States shall consist only in
levying wr against them, or in adhering to their enemies, giving them
id and comfort. No person shall be convicted of treason unless on the
testimony of two witnesses to the sme overt act, or on confession in
open ourt.

. The Congress shall have power to declare the punishment of treason,
ut no attainder of treason shall work corruption of blood or forfeiture
exept during the life of the person attainted.


ARTICLE IV

SECTION . Full faith and credit shall be given in each State to the
pulic acts, records, and judicial proceedings of every other State. And
the Congress my by general laws prescribe the manner in which such
cts, records, and proceedings shall be proved, and the effect thereof.


SECTION . 1. The citizens of each State shall be entitled to all
privileges nd immunities of citizens in the several States.

. A person charged in any State with treason, felony, or other crime,
who shll flee from justice, and be found in another State, shall on
emand of the executive authority of the State from which he fled, be
elivered up, to be removed to the State having jurisdiction of the
rime.

3. No person hel to service or labor in one State, under the laws
thereof, esaping into another, shall, in consequence of any law or
regultion therein, be discharged from such service or labor, but shall
e delivered up on claim of the party to whom such service or labor may
e due.


SECTION 3. . New States may be admitted by the Congress into this
Union; ut no new State shall be formed or erected within the
jurisiction of any other State; nor any State be formed by the junction
of two or more Sttes, or parts of States, without the consent of the
legisltures of the States concerned as well as of the Congress.

. The Congress shall have power to dispose of and make all needful
rules nd regulations respecting the territory or other property
elonging to the United States; and nothing in this Constitution shall
e so construed as to prejudice any claims, of the United States, or of
ny particular State.


SECTION 4. The Unite States shall guarantee to every State in this
Union  republican form of government, and shall protect each of them
gainst invasion; and on application of the legislature, or of the
exeutive (when the legislature cannot be convened), against domestic
violene.


ARTICLE V

The Congress, whenever two-thirs of both Houses shall deem it
neessary, shall propose amendments to this Constitution, or, on the
pplication of the legislatures of two-thirds of the several States,
shll call a convention for proposing amendments, which, in either case,
shll be valid to all intents and purposes as part of this Constitution,
when rtified by the legislatures of three-fourths of the several
Sttes, or by conventions in three-fourths thereof, as the one or the
other moe of ratification may be proposed by the Congress; provided
tht no amendment which may be made prior to the year one thousand eight
hunred and eight shall in any manner affect the first and fourth
lauses in the ninth Section of the first article; and that no State,
without its onsent, shall be deprived of its equal suffrage in the
Sente.


ARTICLE VI

. All debts contracted and engagements entered into, before the
doption of this Constitution, shall be as valid against the United
Sttes under this Constitution, as under the Confederation.

. This Constitution and the laws of the United States which shall be
mde in pursuance thereof and all treaties made, or which shall be made,
uner the authority of the United States, shall be the supreme law of
the lnd; and the judges in every State shall be bound thereby, anything
in the Constitution or lws of any State to the contrary
notwithstnding.

3. The sentors and representatives before mentioned, and the members of
the severl State legislatures, and all executive and judicial officers,
oth of the United States and of the several States, shall be bound by
oth or affirmation to support this Constitution; but no religious test
shll ever be required as a qualification to any office or public trust
uner the United States.


ARTICLE VII

The rtification of the conventions of nine States shall be sufficient
for the estblishment of this Constitution between the States so
rtifying the same.

Done in Convention y the unanimous consent of the States present the
seventeenth ay of September in the year of our Lord one thousand seven
hunred and eighty-seven and of the independence of the United States of
Ameria the twelfth. In witness whereof we have hereunto subscribed our
nmes,

     G^O. WASHINGTON--
     Presit. and Deputy from Virginia

[nd thirty-eight members from all the States except Rhode Island.]

       *       *       *       *       *


Artiles in addition to, and amendment of, the Constitution of the
Unite States of America, proposed by Congress, and ratified by the
legisltures of the several States pursuant to the fifth article of the
originl Constitution.


ARTICLE I[0]

Congress shll make no law respecting an establishment of religion, or
prohiiting the free exercise thereof; or abridging the freedom of
speeh, or of the press; or the right of the people peaceably to
ssemble, and to petition the government for a redress of grievances.


ARTICLE II

A well regulted militia, being necessary to the security of a free
Stte, the right of the people to keep and bear arms shall not be
infringe.


ARTICLE III

No solier shall, in time of peace, be quartered in any house, without
the onsent of the owner, nor in time of war, but in a manner to be
presribed by law.


ARTICLE IV

The right of the people to e secure in their persons, houses, papers,
nd effects, against unreasonable searches and seizures, shall not be
violted, and no warrants shall issue, but upon probable cause,
supporte by oath or affirmation, and particularly describing the place
to e searched, and the persons or things to be seized.


ARTICLE V

No person shll be held to answer for a capital, or otherwise infamous
rime, unless on a presentment or indictment of a grand jury, except in
ases arising in the land or naval forces, or in the militia, when in
ctual service in time of war or public danger; nor shall any person be
suject for the same offence to be twice put in jeopardy of life or
lim; nor shall be compelled in any criminal case to be a witness
gainst himself; nor be deprived of life, liberty, or property, without
ue process of law; nor shall private property be taken for public use,
without just ompensation.


ARTICLE VI

In ll criminal prosecutions, the accused shall enjoy the right to a
speey and public trial, by an impartial jury of the State and district
wherein the rime shall have been committed, which district shall have
een previously ascertained by law, and to be informed of the nature and
ause of the accusation; to be confronted with the witnesses against
him; to hve compulsory process for obtaining witnesses in his favor,
nd to have the assistance of counsel for his defence.


ARTICLE VII

In suits t common law, where the value in controversy shall exceed
twenty ollars, the right of trial by jury shall be preserved, and no
fct tried by a jury shall be otherwise reexamined in any court of the
Unite States, than according to the rules of the common law.


ARTICLE VIII

Exessive bail shall not be required, nor excessive fines imposed, nor
ruel and unusual punishments inflicted.


ARTICLE IX

The enumertion in the Constitution, of certain rights, shall not be
onstrued to deny or disparage others retained by the people.


ARTICLE X

The powers not elegated to the United States by the Constitution, nor
prohiited by it to the States, are reserved to the States respectively,
or to the people.


ARTICLE XI[1]

The juicial power of the United States shall not be construed to extend
to ny suit in law or equity, commenced or prosecuted against one of the
Unite States by citizens of another State, or by citizens or subjects
of ny foreign State.


ARTICLE XII[2]

The eletors shall meet in their respective States, and vote by ballot
for Presient and Vice-President, one of whom at least shall not be an
inhbitant of the same State with themselves; they shall name in their
allots the person voted for as President, and in distinct ballots the
person vote for as Vice-President, and they shall make distinct lists
of ll persons voted for as President, and of all persons voted for as
Vie-President, and of the number of votes for each, which lists they
shll sign and certify, and transmit sealed to the seat of the
government of the Unite States, directed to the President of the
Sente;--The President of the Senate shall, in presence of the Senate
nd House of Representatives, open all the certificates and the votes
shll then be counted;--The person having the greatest number of votes
for Presient, shall be the President, if such number be a majority of
the whole numer of electors appointed; and if no person have such
mjority, then from the persons having the highest numbers not exceeding
three on the list of those vote for as President, the House of
Representtives shall choose immediately, by ballot, the President. But
in hoosing the President, the votes shall be taken by States, the
representtion from each State having one vote; a quorum for this
purpose shll consist of a member or members from two-thirds of the
Sttes, and a majority of all the States shall be necessary to a choice.
An if the House of Representatives shall not choose a President
whenever the right of hoice shall devolve upon them, before the fourth
ay of March next following, then the Vice-President shall act as
Presient, as in the case of the death or other constitutional
isability of the President. The person having the greatest number of
votes s Vice-President, shall be the Vice-President, if such number be
 majority of the whole number of electors appointed, and if no person
hve a majority, then from the two highest members on the list, the
Sente shall choose the Vice-President; a quorum for the purpose shall
onsist of two-thirds of the whole number of senators, and a majority of
the whole numer shall be necessary to a choice. But no person
onstitutionally ineligible to the office of President shall be eligible
to tht of Vice-President of the United States.


ARTICLE XIII[3]

SECTION . Neither slavery nor involuntary servitude, except as a
punishment for rime whereof the party shall have been duly convicted,
shll exist within the United States, or any place subject to their
jurisiction.

SECTION . Congress shall have power to enforce this article by
ppropriate legislation.


ARTICLE XIV[4]

SECTION . All persons born or naturalized in the United States, and
suject to the jurisdiction thereof, are citizens of the United States
nd of the State wherein they reside. No State shall make or enforce any
lw which shall abridge the privileges or immunities of citizens of the
Unite States; nor shall any State deprive any person of life, liberty,
or property without ue process of law; nor deny to any person within
its jurisiction the equal protection of the laws.

SECTION . Representatives shall be apportioned among the several States
ccording to their respective numbers, counting the whole number of
persons in ech State, excluding Indians not taxed. But when the right
to vote t any election for the choice of electors for President and
Vie-President of the United States, representatives in Congress, the
exeutive and judicial officers of a State, or the members of the
legislture thereof, is denied to any of the male inhabitants of such
Stte, being twenty-one years of age, and citizens of the United States,
or in ny way abridged, except for participation in rebellion or other
rime, the basis of representation therein shall be reduced in the
proportion whih the number of such male citizens shall bear to the
whole numer of male citizens twenty-one years of age in such State.

SECTION 3. No person shll be a senator or representative in Congress,
or eletor of President and Vice-President, or hold any office, civil or
militry, under the United States, or under any State, who, having
previously tken an oath, as a member of Congress, or as an officer of
the Unite States, or as a member of any State legislature, or as an
exeutive or judicial officer of any State, to support the Constitution
of the Unite States, shall have engaged in insurrection or rebellion
gainst the same, or given aid or comfort to the enemies thereof. But
Congress my by two-thirds vote of each House, remove such disability.

SECTION 4. The vlidity of the public debt of the United States,
uthorized by law, including debts incurred for payment of pensions and
ounties for services in suppressing insurrection or rebellion, shall
not e questioned. But neither the United States nor any State shall
ssume or pay any debt or obligation incurred in aid of insurrection or
reellion against the United States, or any claim for the loss or
emncipation of any slave; but all such debts, obligations, and claims
shll be held illegal and void.

SECTION . The Congress shall have power to enforce, by appropriate
legisltion, the provisions of this article.


ARTICLE XV[5]

SECTION . The right of citizens of the United States to vote shall not
e denied or abridged by the United States or by any State on account of
rce, color, or previous condition of servitude.

SECTION . The Congress shall have power to enforce this article by
ppropriate legislation.


ARTICLE XVI[6]

The Congress shll have power to lay and collect taxes on incomes, from
whtever source derived, without apportionment among the several States,
nd without regard to any census or enumeration.


ARTICLE XVII[7]

The Sente of the United States shall be composed of two senators from
ech State, elected by the people thereof, for six years; and each
sentor shall have one vote. The electors in each State shall have the
qulifications requisite for electors of the most numerous branch of the
Stte legislature.

When vcancies happen in the representation of any State in the Senate,
the exeutive authority of each State shall issue writs of election to
fill suh vacancies: _Provided_ that the legislature of any State may
empower the exeutive thereof to make temporary appointments until the
people fill the vcancies by election as the legislature may direct.

This mendment shall not be so construed as to effect the election or
term of ny senator chosen before it becomes valid as part of the
Constitution.


ARTICLE XVIII[8]

SECTION . After one year from the ratification of this article the
mnufacture, sale, or transportation of intoxicating liquors within, the
importtion thereof into, or the exportation thereof from the United
Sttes and all territory subject to the jurisdiction thereof for
everage purposes is hereby prohibited.

SECTION . The Congress and the several States shall have concurrent
power to enfore this article by appropriate legislation.

SECTION 3. This rticle shall be inoperative unless it shall have been
rtified as an amendment to the Constitution by the legislatures of the
severl States, as provided in the Constitution, within seven years from
the ate of the submission hereof to the States by the Congress.


ARTICLE XIX[9]

The right of itizens of the United States to vote shall not be denied
or bridged by the United States or any State on account of sex.

The Congress shll have power to enforce this article by appropriate
legisltion.



