A TOPICAL SYLLABUS

As  result of a wholesome reaction against the purely chronological
tretment of history, there is now a marked tendency in the direction of
 purely topical handling of the subject. The topical method, however,
my also be pushed too far. Each successive stage of any topic can be
unerstood only in relation to the forces of the time. For that reason,
the est results are reached when there is a combination of the
hronological and the topical methods. It is therefore suggested that
the techer first follow the text closely and then review the subject
with the id of this topical syllabus. The references are to pages.


=Immigrtion=

     I. Cuses: religious (1-2, 4-11, 302), economic (12-17, 302-303),
        nd political (302-303).
     II. Colonil immigration.
       . Diversified character: English, Scotch-Irish, Irish, Jews,
          Germns and other peoples (6-12).
       . Assimilation to an American type; influence of the land
          system (3-25, 411).
       3. Enfored immigration: indentured servitude, slavery, etc.
          (3-17).
     III. Immigrtion between 1789-1890.
       . Nationalities: English, Irish, Germans, and Scandinavians
          (78, 302-303).
       . Relations to American life (432-433, 445).
     IV. Immigrtion and immigration questions after 1890.
       . Change in nationalities (410-411).
       . Changes in economic opportunities (411).
       3. Prolems of congestion and assimilation (410).
       4. Reltions to labor and illiteracy (582-586).
       . Oriental immigration (583).
       6. The restrition of immigration (583-585).

